<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0343EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RandallCitizenship     07-28 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Randall Citizenship,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer `Thrilled' About Citizenship Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN GOESSL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that an immigration appeals panel
has ruled that leftist writer Margaret Randall is an American
citizen who cannot be deported, the first thing she wants to do is
fly to Paris.
   ``Ironically, she will now finally be able to leave the country
and visit her grandchildren,'' said David Cole, Randall's attorney.
   The U.S. Board of Immigration Appeals ruled Thursday that
Randall became a Mexican citizen in 1967 under economic duress, and
the Immigration and Naturalization Service should not have
considered her politics in seeking to deport her.
   The board, which operates independently of the INS under the
U.S. Justice Department, determined that Randall never freely
renounced U.S. citizenship when she left in the 1960s for Mexico,
where she married a Mexican man.
   ``I'm absolutely thrilled, of course,'' the 52-year-old college
professor said. ``To tell you the truth, I'm a little numb.''
   Attorneys for Randall, an outspoken critic of U.S. policy who
lived 14 years in Cuba and Nicaragua, said the INS was trying to
punish her for her pro-communist views.
   Cole said the ruling ``should say to the INS, `Be a little more
careful in instituting deportation proceedings against citizens.'''
   Justice Department attorneys are reviewing the decision,
spokesman Dan Eramian said. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will
have the final word on the case. INS cannot appeal it to another
court.
   Randall, a poet, author and photographer, has written 45 books
in English and Spanish, including 17 books of poetry. She has
taught at the University of New Mexico, Trinity College in
Hartford, Conn., and the Macalester College in St. Paul, Minn.,
since returning to the U.S. in 1983 on a visitor's visa.
   The INS claimed that Randall gave up her U.S. citizenship as a
political protest and wanted Mexican citizenship in order to get a
passport to Cuba. It also claimed that as the wife of a Mexican
citizen, she could have found work.
   Randall claimed her husband, from whom she separated in 1967,
ceased providing for their three children, one of whom was ill. She
also said she was led to believe that work laws in Mexico forced
her to be a citizen before she would find a job.
   Randall was ordered deported in 1985 after her request for
permanent resident status as an alien was denied based on what the
INS said were communist and anti-American beliefs espoused in her
books.
   Norman Mailer, Kurt Vonnegut, Alice Walker, Arthur Miller and
William Styron were among writers who filed suit in U.S. District
Court in Washington, D.C., after the INS denied her application.
   Cole said the 3-2 decision by the appeals panel was unexpected.
   ``I think the decision affirms that U.S. citizenship is a
constitutional right and that one cannot lose one's citizenship
because the government doesn't like what you say,'' said Cole of
the New York-based Center for Constitutional Rights. ``It's sort of
a nice rebuke to the INS.''
   ``Now we just go to the passport office to pick up her
passport,'' Cole said. ``She's a U.S. citizen.''
   Randall, who has been living near her parents in Albuquerque,
said she wants to fly to Paris for the birth next month of her
third grandchild.
   ``I'm hoping I can be there when he's born, which was not
possible the first two times around,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
