<FIRST>r w PM-FightingBack     07-28 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fighting Back,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration to Fight Back on Clean Air Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, after weeks of
absorbing unrelenting criticism on its clean air bill, is taking
the offensive by questioning the motives of its critics.
   The stepped-up defense surfaced Thursday when a top
Environmental Protection Agency official, William Rosenberg,
accused Democratic critics of making ``unfair and totally biased
attacks'' on the bill and of falsely calling the proposal a sellout
to automakers.
   Rosenberg handed out a comparison sheet that said a rival bill
would be far costlier while achieving only marginally more
pollution reduction.
   The competing legislation was sponsored by Rep. Henry A. Waxman,
D-Calif., the most vocal critic of the administration plan. Waxman,
a staunch supporter of environmental groups that have denounced the
Bush proposal, held the first hearing on the administration measure
Monday.
   Rosenberg said the session was scheduled to ``politicize'' the
issue.
   While a number of House Democrats, as well as Senate Majority
Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, have attacked the
administration's bill, it was introduced in the House on Thursday
night with bipartisan support _ 90 Republicans and 57 Democrats.
   Several EPA officials said the final straw that triggered
Rosenberg's heated comments was the Waxman-chaired hearing of the
House Energy and Commerce environment subcommittee.
   For five hours, EPA administrator William Reilly, a career
environmentalist, and Rosenberg, the EPA's assistant administrator
for air, sat at the witness table while Waxman and other Democrats
excoriated the bill.
   Waxman even produced an ``auto lobbyists' scorecard'' to
emphasize his contention that the legislation won't reduce auto
emissions.
   Singled out was a provision to allow automakers to average
pollution emissions by an engine category instead of forcing each
vehicle to meet new anti-pollution requirements _ a ``red
herring,'' Rosenberg said Thursday.
   Committee Democrats complained about the exclusion of controls
on toxic chemicals emitted by cars, trucks and small industries,
and about the consideration of economic factors in determining the
health threat from toxic emissions. They also contended that the
bill failed to protect national parks.
   ``The reaction when we walked out was, `The stuff being said was
unfair, much of it was inaccurate, and we weren't given the chance
to get a word in edgewise,''' said EPA spokesman David Cohen.
   The agency's chief lobbyist, Patrick Quinn, said Reilly ``had
not been in a hearing with that level of antagonism. Reilly's
life's work has been as an environmental professional, and to sit
there and have such distortions and verbal badgering ... doesn't
sit well in a lot of people's stomachs.''
   Cohen said no formal strategy for aggressiveness was devised
after the meeting, but other EPA officials said a number of
staffers decided it was time to respond better to the criticism.
   Waxman said the hearing was fair and ``highlighted the
differences that we have for controlling emissions from cars and
trucks.'' He praised Reilly for doing ``as good a job as he could,
putting a good face on a bill that could actually increase
emissions for motor vehicles.''
   Rosenberg chose to make his comments at a news conference that
had been scheduled to release EPA figures on ozone and carbon
monoxide pollution. He immediately ripped into the critics.
   Asked by a reporter ``Why should we trust you?'' Rosenberg
replied, ``The issue is, why you should trust the critics?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
