<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0514EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     07-28 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeachment Trial Witness Refuses to Testify in Hastings Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators are threatening action that could
lead to jail for a disbarred lawyer who refuses to answer questions
in the impeachment trial of federal Judge Alcee L. Hastings.
   ``If you continue to refuse to testify, I believe this committee
will take steps that will force your incarceration,'' Sen. Joe
Lieberman, D-Conn., told William Borders on Thursday.
   Hastings, 52, a U.S. District Court judge in Miami, was
impeached by the House last August and is on trial in the Senate.
   Conviction by the Senate on charges of plotting to get a
$150,000 payoff, perjury and improper disclosure of wiretap
information would mean the loss of his judicial post and $89,500
salary.
   A federal court jury acquitted him in 1983 of criminal charges
of conspiracy to obtain a bribe.
   Borders, a law school classmate of Hastings' and once a
political power in Washington, was imprisoned after being convicted
on the charges in a separate trial. He was arrested in October 1981
as he drove out of a suburban Virginia motel with a cash-stuffed
garment bag and an undercover FBI agent by his side.
   Flanked by two attorneys, Borders angrily described for the
12-member Senate panel hearing evidence how he had ``lost my former
livelihood'' as a result of the case and been accorded ``harassing
and somewhat contemptible'' treatment by federal authorities.
   He refused to answer questions, saying that to do so would
violate his right against self-incrimination under the Fifth
Amendment to the Constitution as well as his rights under five
other amendments.
   He asked to ``finally be left alone to pursue the speck of
happiness that was left to me.''
   ``I respectfully refuse to answer any and all questions,'' he
said.
   Lawmakers threatened to cite Borders for civil contempt because
of his refusal. Jailing him would require action by the full Senate
and court approval. Senators warned there was no assurance that he
would not face only a civil contempt citation but charges of
criminal contempt.
   Senators said there was still time for him to extricate himself
by testifying, if necessary in a deposition witnessed by at least
one senator while lawmakers are on their August recess.
   At the hearings, the senators have heard tapes of FBI undercover
agent H. Paul Rico posing as a racketeer who wanted to have his
three-year sentence and a similar term imposed by Hastings on his
brother changed to probation.
   On the tapes, Borders is heard to say that he could get Hastings
to make such a change and even persuade the judge to return
$845,000 that had been forfeited to the government.
   Hastings says Borders, a longtime friend, was a ``rainmaker''
who was using his name to obtain payoffs. Hastings says he had
nothing to do with the scheme.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SpendingBills     07-28 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bills,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate OKs $225 Million for Atom Smasher, Increases Food Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate continues its rush to finish major
portions of its budget work as it nears the recess wire, deciding
to provide the first federal funds for building a giant atom
smasher in Texas.
   On a voice vote Thursday, lawmakers approved an $18.4 billion
bill for fiscal 1990 energy and water projects that contains $225
million for the superconducting supercollider, the $4.4 billion
research facility planned for Waxahachie, Texas.
   Final passage was delayed by a futile attempt _ that lasted
hours _ by opponents of the Medicare catastrophic care program to
delay the surtax many of the nation's senior citizens will have to
pay to finance the initiative.
   Earlier in the day, the Senate approved a separate $44.3 billion
agriculture bill that boosts spending on domestic food aid programs
and pressures the government to tighten its requirements for food
labels.
   Both Houses of Congress have approved three of the 13
appropriations bills for fiscal 1990 needed annually to finance
federal agencies. But the two chambers still must agree to
compromise versions of the three measures before sending them to
President Bush for his signature.
   Fiscal 1990 begins Oct. 1, but lawmakers are scheduled to begin
their four-week summer recess Aug. 5.
   In its energy legislation, the Senate provided $135 million to
begin construction of the 53-mile-long, doughnut-shaped
supercollider and $90 million for research and development.
   The underground facility would be the world's largest particle
accelerator, capable of throwing two proton beams at each other at
nearly the speed of light. Scientists say their research could help
them learn about nature's most basic building blocks.
   The project, expected to take five to seven years to complete,
would create an anticipated 3,500 construction jobs and 2,500
permanent jobs. It would be built 25 miles south of Dallas.
   The bill also contains $4.2 billion for water projects; $9.6
billion for nuclear weapons programs, and $350 million to study a
potential high-level nuclear waste storage site in Yucca Mountain,
Nev.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was defeated 58-40 when he offered an
amendment that would have delayed the Medicare surtax for a year.
   But the issue will persist. The House Ways and Means Committee
has already voted to cut the levy in half, and White House budget
director Richard Darman told reporters Thursday that the
administration was ``in the process of compromising'' on rolling
back the program.
   The agriculture legislation would expand federal spending for an
assortment of domestic food assistance programs to $18.8 billion,
$1.5 billion more than Bush sought in the budget he sent Congress
in February and $2 billion above 1989 levels.
   This includes $4.9 billion for child nutrition programs, about
the same as Bush's request; $2.1 billion for food aid to women,
infants and children, $200 million above Bush's figure; and $15.4
billion for food stamps, $1.3 billion above the Bush number.
   A report approved with the bill also directs the Food and Drug
Administration to ``move forward'' with clarifying the meanings of
``natural,'' ``low-fat,'' ``lite,'' and other terms food producers
commonly place on their labels.
   However, the report did not address the controversy over red dye
No. 3, the food coloring that is considered a potential carcinogen.
In its measure, the House ordered the government to refrain from
banning the food coloring until long-range studies of its health
effects are completed.
   Report language is not legally binding. Agencies must take such
commands seriously, however, or risk antagonizing lawmakers who can
retaliate against offending bureaucrats in future bills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
