<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0515EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PalmePuzzle     07-28 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palme Puzzle,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conviction Doesn't End Mystery of Premier's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conviction of Christer Pettersson
for the 1986 killing of Prime Minister Olof Palme is not likely to
lift the aura of mystery that surrounds one of Sweden's most
infamous crimes.
   Pettersson, a 42-year-old social misfit with a long record of
crime, drunkenness and drug abuse, was sentenced Thursday to life
imprisonment.
   But the Palme file still has plenty of blank pages for advocates
of conspiracy theories. It promises to become Sweden's equivalent
to the 1963 assassination of President John F. Kennedy.
   Palme, a dynamic four-term premier and Sweden's leading
political figure for two decades, was shot as he walked home with
his wife, Lisbeth, from a downtown movie theater on Feb. 28, 1986.
   The two professional judges on the jury voted to acquit
Pettersson for lack of evidence, but they were overruled by the six
lay jurors.
   In a 46-page verdict, the jury pinned its judgement on Mrs.
Palme's identification of Pettersson. She said she saw him standing
15 feet away just after her husband crumpled to the street.
   ``The way she identified him at the trial is, according to the
court, very convincing,'' the judgement said.
   It cited other witnesses who saw Pettersson waiting for the
Palme couple and following them. This testimony ``supported Lisbeth
Palme's identification to such a degree that the court finds it
without reasonable doubt that he fired the two shots.''
   The two dissenting judges noted that the murder weapon, a .357
Magnum revolver, was never found, and no physical evidence surfaced
to link Pettersson to the shooting. No one swore to seeing him fire
a weapon.
   ``The factor of uncertainty is so prominent that we can't vote
to convict,'' said Judge Michael af Geijerstam.
   ``It's evident that the verdict hinged on the relative
subjectivity of the jurors,'' as opposed to the legal approach of
the judges, said Anders Stening, a lawyer, in a television debate.
   The motive is the biggest unanswered question in the case. Why
would Pettersson kill Palme?
   The written judgement ignored the issue. During the five-week
trial the prosecution intimated that Pettersson simply hated all
authority. Pettersson, who maintained his innocence, claimed to be
an admirer of Palme.
   Why did no one claim the $8 million reward?
   Since Pettersson was arrested Dec. 14, news reports have
questioned whether Pettersson, a heavy drinker and user of
amphetamines, could have kept his mouth shut about the killing.
   ``Doubts will continue to gnaw, because Pettersson doesn't fit
the picture of the killer of a prime minister,'' said Ulla
Bondeson, a criminologist from Malmo. ``No official investigation
can ever kill the speculation,'' she said.
   ``This verdict is the worst possible conclusion. The national
trauma will continue,'' said political commentator Yrsa Stenius.
``There is no motive, no logical chain of events leading up to the
incident.''
   Palme's international stature and involvement in disarmament
issues gave rise to theories of international intrigue.
   Investigators focused on possible conspiracies during the first
year. Most centered on militant Kurdish exiles, angered at a
crackdown by Palme's social democratic government.
   The Iranian regime of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and the Iraqi
secret service were among others suspected. Those theories were
eventually dismissed as groundless, but speculation is bound to
haunt the case.
   Four hours before Palme was shot, the files on a tax
investigation against him disappeared in a break-in at the county
administrative appeals court.
   All computer files were obliterated and all documents stolen. No
connection with the murder was ever established.
   Among many initial lines of inquiry later dropped were accounts
that Palme was followed by men with walkie-talkies. These reports
led to speculation of a right-wing plot by policemen against the
leftist premier.
   Several Stockholm policemen were questioned and released well
before the arrest of Pettersson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
