<DOCNO> AP890728-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0528EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MustangKillings     07-28 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mustang Killings,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Attorney Concedes Failure in Prosecuting Wild Horse Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have conceded defeat in
the government's effort to prosecute six people charged with
capturing or killing wild horses and burros in rural Nevada.
   ``We underestimated the difficulty of proving these cases,''
Bill Maddox, the U.S. attorney for Nevada, said Thursday by
telephone from his Las Vegas office. ``We didn't do a very good
job.''
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Howard McKibben gave Maddox
permission to drop charges against the two remaining defendants in
a much-publicized case that grew from the suspected slaughter of
some 600 mustangs in central Nevada.
   Dave Morehead and Shannon Brennan were scheduled to go on trial
Aug. 8.
   ``I just took a very critical look at the case and, in my
opinion, we would have had a very difficult time proving their
guilt beyond a reasonable doubt,'' Maddox explained. ``This type of
case needs to be handled like a homicide. And with the information
we had that was too difficult.''
   Don Hill, an attorney representing Morehead, said the government
would have been wasting the court's time to go forward and
commended Maddox for ``having the courage to admit there wasn't
enough evidence.''
   Morehead, 38, a foreman at the C-Punch Ranch 70 miles north of
Lovelock, and ranchhand Brennan, 21, were charged with killing
about 40 horses and burros. The charges are misdemeanor violations
of the federal Wild, Free Roaming Horse and Burro Protection Act.
   The two were riding the range Thursday and could not be reached
for comment. But Dave Morehead's wife said they were relieved.
   ``We were hoping they'd drop charges a long time ago because
they never had anything to begin with,'' Vina Morehead said in a
telephone interview from her north-central Nevada home.
   ``It's been the worst time of our lives. It's just thrown us
into a tizzy. ... He should never have been charged in the first
place.''
   The original indictment was issued in January after months of
investigation following the Bureau of Land Management's discovery
of hundreds of dead mustangs over a vast area of north-central
Nevada.
   Bureau investigators believe the wild horses were shot over a
period of about two years, but the condition of many of the
carcasses made it impossible to determine whether they were killed
or died of natural causes.
   Last week, a jury returned an innocent verdict in the case of
Betty Irwin, a 63-year-old California woman who's part owner of the
sprawling C-Punch Ranch.
   Jury members said there wasn't enough evidence to convict her of
misdeameanor charges of attempting to convert a wild burro into a
pet.
   Nearly a month ago, U.S. District Judge Edward Reed dismissed
charges against cousins Eugene ``Skeeter'' Thacker, a 27-year-old
cowboy, and Ronald Hage, a 23-year-old miner. Reed said the
government didn't specify exactly which five horses the pair
allegedly killed.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Will Mattley earlier dropped charges
against a sixth defendant when the accused proved he wasn't in
Nevada at the time he allegedly killed mustangs.
