<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-28 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wealthiest Taxpayers Are Biggest Cheats, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the federal government had the staff to
audit upper-income Americans, it could collect billions of dollars
in unpaid taxes, says a study sponsored by a Democratic group.
   People who earn more than $50,000 a year, 12 percent of all
taxpayers, owed 40 percent of the $72.5 billion in taxes owed to
the government in 1985 but not collected, said the study, which was
based on data from the Internal Revenue Service.
   The top 3 percent of taxpayers, consisting of those who earn
more than $100,000 a year, accounted for 26 percent of the unpaid
taxes, said the study financed by Leadership for the New Century, a
group of progressive Democrats.
   The study was based on detailed audits of 50,000 to 60,000
Americans that the IRS conducts every three years to determine how
well taxpayers are complying with the law.
   People who earn less than $25,000 a year, 62 percent of all
taxpayers, owed 30 percent of the government's uncollected taxes in
1985, the study said. Taxpayers who make $25,000 to $50,000 a year
accounted for 31 percent of the unpaid taxes.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Senate Democrats Agree on Consensus Bill</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national service bill that blends several
Democratic proposals should be on its way to the floor next week,
senators say.
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor and
Human Resources Committee, said Thursday at least 10 national
service bills ranging in cost from $5 million to $5 billion have
been introduced this year in the Senate.
   The compromise plan is designed to promote public service among
Americans of all ages, Kennedy said. Incentives include academic
credit, stipends, job training, educational aid and assistance for
first-time home buyers.
   Kennedy said his committee is scheduled to complete work on the
bill next week in preparation for floor action after the August
recess.
   Kennedy and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine,
said they hope to achieve a bipartisan measure with Bush
administration support.
   Bush favors a purely voluntary approach to such service without
incentives or stipends and has proposed a $25 million program to
encourage such efforts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CIA Opened Station at Costa Rica's Request</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The CIA helped set up a communications station
in Costa Rica at that Central American country's request and
developed a program dealing with Nicaraguan nationals, according to
a court filing by Iran-Contra prosecutors.
   The document, filed Thursday in the criminal case against a
former CIA station chief, demonstrates the spy agency's efforts to
help prepare Costa Rica for a possible invasion by the leftist
government of Nicaragua starting in late 1984.
   The Costa Rican government asked the United States for help,
says the court document filed by prosecutors from the office of
independent counsel Lawrence Walsh.
   A program to assist and improve the effectiveness of Costa
Rica's defense forces was initiated as a result of the request, the
court document said.
   Costa Rica doesn't have a standing army, but rather a civil and
rural guard of 9,500, including 3,000 reservists.
   Prosecutors had proposed that the summary of information about
the three highly sensitive CIA programs be presented in the trial
of Joseph Fernandez, the agency's former station chief in Costa
Rica. He is charged with lying to the Tower Commission and the CIA
inspector general's office about his help to Oliver North's
resupply network to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   Fernandez says that he must be allowed to introduce greater
detail about the three programs to properly defend himself against
criminal charges. U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton in
Alexandria, Va., agreed.
   On Monday, the Justice Department, citing national security
concerns of the CIA, stepped in and obtained a stay of Fernandez's
trial from a U.S. Court of Appeals judge in Richmond, Va.
</TEXT>
