<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-EmergencyWorkers     07-28 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Emergency Workers,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Workers Fail to Protect Themselves Against AIDS</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Drug, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospital workers are doing too little to protect
themselves from the AIDS virus, even though one in 16
emergency-room patients was found to be infected at a major medical
center last year, a study has found.
   Health workers failed to take adequate precautions, such as
wearing gloves, masks and gowns, 66 percent of the time during a
six-week study period in the emergency room at Johns Hopkins
Hospital in Baltimore, researchers said.
   The failure rate for taking precautions rose to more than 80
percent when patients were bleeding rapidly, said the researchers,
led by Dr. Gabor D. Kelen of the hospital's emergency department.
   Many of the workers _ who included doctors, nurses and
technicians _ said putting on protective gear was too difficult or
time-consuming, or they believed the gear might get in their way,
the researchers said.
   Such responses were made even though it had been reported that
5.2 percent of emergency-room patients at Johns Hopkins were
infected with the AIDS virus in 1987, up to 6 percent by 1988, the
researchers said.
   The AIDS virus is believed to be passed mainly through sexual
intercourse and the sharing of contaminated hypodermic needles
among drug abusers. But health-care workers are in danger of
catching it from needle pricks, blood sprayed to the eyes, nose or
mouth or from getting infected fluids on skin cuts.
   At least 169 health care workers nationwide have become infected
with the virus through contact with patients, according to the
federal Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
   Johns Hopkins had tried to educate staffers at all levels about
the need to wear protective clothing, and had displayed 10 highly
visible posters outlining recommended precautions in strategic
areas of the emergency department, researchers said.
   In addition, gloves, masks, gowns and goggles had been placed at
the entrances of rooms where they might be needed, they wrote in
today's Journal of the American Medical Association.
   Still, ``health care workers took inadequate precautions,
particularly in those situations that most called for them,'' the
researchers said.
   Overall, workers donned needed gear 44 percent of the time, they
found, basing data on direct observations.
   In patients with profuse bleeding, the rate fell to 19.5
percent, the researchers said.
   In procedures requiring only gloves _ those that might involve
contact with blood or other body fluids but were unlikely to
involve being sprayed by such fluids _ workers wore gloves 64.8
percent of the time, they found.
   But for procedures requiring gloves, mask, gown and goggles _
those in which a worker might get sprayed with body fluids _ the
rate of wearing adequate gear plummeted to 16.5 percent, the study
found.
   The Johns Hopkins study found 152 infected people among 2,544
patients treated in the emergency room during the research period.
Ninety-five of them showed no signs of infection and didn't know
they were carrying the AIDS virus, researchers said.
   Being infected with the virus does not necessarily mean a person
has acquired immune deficiency syndrome, because the virus can be
present for years before symptoms of the deadly disease begin to
appear.
   The total number of AIDS cases reported since 1979 is 99,936, of
whom 58,014 have died, the CDC says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
