<FIRST>r a PM-FarmAccident     07-28 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Accident,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Die Trying to Save Each Other in Farm Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENOMINEE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening of the Menominee County Fair
centers once again around the Theuerkauf family.
   Last year, fair manager Shirley Charlier began the festival by
handing Carl Theuerkauf a plaque commemorating the centennial of
his family's dairy farm.
   Today, Charlier planned to start the fair with a moment of
silence. Theuerkauf and four family members died one by one
Wednesday as they tried to save each other from suffocating in a
manure storage pit.
   Dead were farm patriarch Carl Theuerkauf Sr., 65; sons Carl Jr.,
37, and Tom, 28; grandson Daniel, 15; and nephew Bill Hofer, 63.
   The elder Theuerkauf would have celebrated his 66th birthday
Saturday, a sheriff's deputy said. Instead, the farmer will be
buried that day.
   The entire county is grieving.
   ``People are devastated,'' said Charlier. ``Somebody asked why
would they do that. I don't know if I could say if one of my
children had fallen in the river if I would use my reason and not
go and help.''
   Menominee County officials believe four of the men died on
missions of mercy.
   ``I'm sure that when one person slipped or fell, out of love and
for help, one after another went in,'' said Richard Breyer with the
county farm extension service. ``It's just something there will not
be an answer as to why it had to be five people.''
   The five men were using a pump to empty the partially covered,
12-foot deep concrete pit Wednesday morning and were almost
finished when the drainage pump clogged.
   Hofer descended into the darkness to clear the blockage. Instead
of air, he breathed methane gas, and collapsed.
   Police can only theorize what happened next, since everyone who
saw the incident died.
   ``It's unknown which one went in next, but eventually they all
went in to save the rest,'' said Menominee County Sheriff's Deputy
Booth Whipp.
   County medical examiner Dr. Paul Haupt estimates it took about
90 seconds for each of the men to collapse and suffocate in the
invisible cloud of gas.
   Methane is an odorless gas that can be generated by animal
waste. The pit collects manure from the dairy barn until it can be
moved to an outdoor pit or loaded into a manure spreader.
   A week of very hot, humid weather likely caused the deadly
methane gas to build up faster than usual, Breyer said.
   Whipp said he believed the Theuerkaufs realized the danger ``but
they were more concerned with their loved ones.''
   A funeral for the four Theuerkaufs will be held at Christ
Evangelical Lutheran Church on Saturday. A service for Hofer will
be held later that same day at Faith Lutheran Church in Marinette.
   Breyer said close to 1,000 area residents helped the Theuerkaufs
celebrate the centennial of their farm last summer. And he said the
elder Theuerkauf was named Michigan Farm Manager of the Year
several years ago. The dairy farm near the Wisconsin line had more
than 250 cows and was one of the largest in Michigan's Upper
Peninsula.
   Former farmhands are pitching in to keep the farm running.
   ``We're all stunned and shocked by it,'' said Harry Theuerkauf,
the elder Theuerkauf's brother, who owns a Milwaukee law firm.
``It's hard to grasp. They all are going to be missed. Everybody
had plans for the fifth generation of Theuerkaufs to take over the
farm. Now things are up in the air.
   ``I wish there was an easy way to cope with this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0041 </DOCNO>
