<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-28 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds Steady Against Yen, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly against the Japanese yen
today, while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell
moderately.
   The dollar closed at 139.45 yen, up 0.10 yen from Thursday's
close of 139.35 yen. After opening marginally lower at 139.30 yen,
the U.S. currency traded between 139.30-139.88 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
269.45 points Thursday, shed 79.65 points, or 0.22 percent, to
finish the week at 34,705.63. The market's main index had gained
46.33 points at the end of the morning session.
   ``The dollar moved on a firm tone, though trading as a whole was
thin,'' said Shinichi Kato, a senior dealer with Mitui Bank.
   Investors seeking to put money in the United States bought
dollars despite the moderate decline in U.S. interest rates
following the second-quarter U.S. gross national product report
showing slower-than-expected economic growth, Kato said.
   The U.S. Commerce Department reported Thursday that the nation's
economy grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 1.7 percent in the
April-June period, down from the previous quarter's revised annual
rate of 3.7 percent.
   Theoretically, lower interest rates tend to make
dollar-denominated investment less attractive.
   On the stock market, the reversal in the Nikkei index's
direction came after the morning session that ended at 34,831.61, a
new high.
   Volume traded on the first section reached 900 million shares,
down from Thursday's 1.39 billion shares.
   ``The market needed a respite,'' said a dealer with Yamaichi
Securities Co., speaking on condition of anonymity.
   There still remains political uncertainty in in the market over
who will be Japan's next prime minister following Monday's
announcement by Prime Minister Sousuke Uno that he will resign to
take responsibility for a major defeat in Sunday's elections for
half the seats of the upper house, the dealer said.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party has decided to elect
Uno's successor as party president on Aug. 8 at a caucus of party
lawmakers. The party president will will be elected the new prime
minister in a special parliamentary session scheduled for Aug. 10.
</TEXT>
