<FIRST>r a PM-CustomsCommissioner     07-28 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Customs Commissioner,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outgoing Customs Commissioner Blasts Administration Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Outgoing U.S. Customs Service Commissioner
William von Raab has accused the federal government of lacking the
commitment to win the war on drugs.
   Von Raab, who is leaving office next week after being forced to
resign his position of eight years, said in a report today in The
New York Times that drug-fighting efforts were not working.
   Senior officials were too preoccupied with other problems,
according to von Raab, who has played a major role in combating
drugs during the Reagan and Bush administrations.
   He said Secretary of State James A. Baker III was worried about
Eastern Europe, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady only cared
about Third World debt and fixing the troubled savings and loan
industry and Dick Thornburgh, the attorney general, was concerned
about jurisdictional matters at the Justice Department.
   ``I'm very concerned that there is not enough real commitment of
a deep-seated nature among the members of the administration, bar
one or two, like Jack Kemp or Bill Bennett, that is necessary to
drive a tough, winning drug policy,'' von Raab said.
   Kemp is secretary of Housing and Urban Development, and William
Bennett was appointed by President Bush as the nation's drug czar.
   Referring to unnamed officials as ``country club Republicans,''
the commissioner said, ``You cannot have a Cabinet secretary or a
senior official in a department take the position that we cannot
get ourselves too deeply into this exercise because it will become
another Vietnam.
   ``If we don't approach this war with the intention of winning it
and doing what's necessary to win it, we won't win it,'' he said.
``And that means you have got to have fire in your belly to want to
win it.''
   Some officials dismissed von Raab's remarks. One Treasury
official who spoke on condition of anonymity said von Raab felt
rebuked by the appointment of a new commissioner. Others said he
was angered because he had been passed over for drug czar, a newly
created position in the Bush administration.
   Von Raab told ABC News that Bush, along with Bennett, is
committed toward stemming the flow of illegal drugs into the
country but blasted the State Department for having a ``cowardly
streak'' about drugs.
   He also warned little is being done while Bennett prepares his
program.
   ``It's just out of control,'' von Raab said, ``and in that sense
our national policy has been a total and abysmal failure.''
   He said the United States has failed to apply political and
economic pressure against drug-producing countries which allow
traffickers to roam freely.
   ``They feel no pressure whatsoever,'' he said in the television
interview. ``They are happily living out their lives as feudal
barons in the hills of Colombia, Peru, and Bolivia and no one's
touching them, including the United States. There's so much cocaine
out there that we can't control it.''
   After a U.S. drug agent was killed in 1985 by drug dealers in
Mexico, von Raab sealed the border to pressure the Mexican
government into finding the killers.
</TEXT>
