<FIRST>r a PM-MarathonSwim     07-28 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marathon Swim,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Celebrates Birthday With Swim on Two Continents</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Horning started his day with a swim
in Paris and ended it splashing in San Francisco Bay in a marathon
dip marking his 41st birthday and the 200th anniversary of the
French Revolution.
   ``Is this San Francisco?'' the sports promoter laughed as he
emerged from the bay Thursday night after swimming 1\ miles from
Alcatraz Island to Aquatic Park near Fisherman's Wharf.
   The swim down the Seine in Paris was ``wonderful,'' he said, but
the final leg in San Francisco took 45 minutes, a bit longer than
anticipated.
   ``The ebb tide was stronger than I expected,'' Horning said.
   Horning failed to complete his initial plan, which included an
additional swim from the Statue of Liberty in New York to Battery
Park at the tip of Manhattan. Airplane connection problems scuttled
that effort.
   ``The swims are the easy part,'' said Horning. ``It's catching
the planes that can be tricky.''
   Anyway, he did manage to swim to one Statue of Liberty.
   He swam through Paris from the Bastille to the little-known
French Statue of Liberty, on an island in the Seine down river from
the Eiffel Tower. The statue is a reduced-scale version of the one
in New York Harbor. Americans gave it to France in thanks for
France's gift of the original to the United States.
   The swim in France took 1 hour and 15 minutes, making his total
time in the water Thursday two hours.
   Such ventures are not unusual for Horning, who lives in nearby
Berkeley.
   Last year he marked his 40th birthday by swimming under 40
bridges in Moscow, New York and San Francisco.
   Why does he do it?
   ``I'm an epileptic and I hope this gives others confidence to do
what they want to do,'' he said shortly after getting out of the
water to the applause of a small crowd of friends, relatives and
reporters.
</TEXT>
