<HEAD>Kansas Governor to Texas Politician: Knock off the Wimpy Routine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas wimpy?
   Not in Gov. Mike Hayden's book. And any Texan who says so is
stirring up a twister full of trouble, he says.
   He shot off a telegram Thursday to Texas State Treasurer Ann
Richards, taking exception to her characterization of Kansas as a
wimpy state.
   After all, the Republican governor pointed out, Wichita State
University blasted the University of Texas in the College World
Series earlier this year.
   ``We refer Ann Richards to the members of the Texas University
baseball team if she has any questions about Kansas fortitude,''
Hayden said.
   Richards is a Democratic gubernatorial candidate in Texas who
delivered the keynote address last year at the Democratic National
Convention that made the phrase ``Where was George?'' part of the
campaign rhetoric.
   She says the proposed new slogan for the Texas license plate,
``The Friendship State,'' was too wimpy, although it might be fine
for Kansas or Ohio.
   Hayden retorted, ``She tried the wimpy strategy at the
Democratic Convention last year when she lashed out at George Bush.
Now she's lashing out at Kansas with the same attack. We say, Ann,
read our lips: Give the wimpy routine a rest.''
