<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-28 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady in thin European trading
this morning as the market digested U.S. economic growth figures
released Thursday.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar was lacking firm
direction following the release of data that showed the U.S. gross
national product slowed in the second quarter to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.7 percent from 3.7 percent in the first
quarter. A growth rate of 2 percent had been expected.
   One dealer in Frankfurt said while the dollar was pushed lower
by the news, the figures had not had a drastic impact on the
currency.
   ``It shows that there is still demand,'' said the dealer at a
U.S. bank on condition of anonymity.
   Traders also noted that at the end of a summer week and month,
the dollar was not expected to fluctuate widely.
   In London, the British pound cost $1.657, cheaper for buyers
than Thursday's late $1.6598.
   The fall in the pound was a change from its recent gains of 10
cents against the dollar over the past seven weeks and four cents
this week. British interest rates stand at 14 percent, making the
pound very attractive to investors.
   Other midmorning rates for the dollar in Europe compared with
Thursday's late rates:
   _ 1.8774 West German marks, up from 1.8692
   _ 1.6158 Swiss francs, up from 1.6075
   _ 6.3530 French francs, up from 6.3310
   _ 2.1163 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1085
   _ 1,350.50 Italian lire, up from 1,346.00
   _ 1.1832 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1827
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before London's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 139.45 yen, up 0.10 yen from
Thursday's close. In London, the yen traded lower at 139.30 yen.
   Gold opened in London, the major market, at a bid $372 a troy
ounce, down from $374 late Thursday. At midmorning, London's
dealers recommended a bid price of $371.95.
   Gold traded in Zurich at a bid price of $371.60, down from late
Thursday's $374.05.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold dropped $1.87 dollars an ounce to
close at a bid $373.
   Silver bullion traded in London at a bid $5.21 a troy ounce,
down from $5.23 late Thursday.
