<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scattered Thunderstorms Over Mid-Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Temperature tables were not available from the National Weather
Service due to the weather service's computer problems.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered thunderstorms along the mid-Atlantic Coast early today
produced high winds and drenched several areas, while forecasters
predicted a slight break in the Northeast's heat.
   Nearly 3 inches of rain fell in Meridian, Miss., in less than
two hours late Thursday. Scattered thunderstorms lingered over
parts of Ohio, Georgia, South Carolina and Florida early this
morning.
   Thunderstorms developing ahead of a cold front crossing the
Great Lakes region weakened Thursday night.
   Earlier, the storms produced large hail and damaging winds in
Wisconsin and Illinois.
   In the Northeast, thunderstorms produced severe weather in New
York and Vermont.
   Hail the size of dimes fell in Ira, Vt., while in the northern
part of the state, winds gusted to 58 mph at Milton. Also in
Vermont, winds blew down trees in at least five northern
communities, including Stowe.
   Evening thunderstorms in New York produced high winds that
downed trees and power lines at Rensselaer, while thunderstorms in
Massachusetts downed trees at Pittsfield.
   At least 30,000 people in New York had lost electricity by
midevening, but most had power back in less than an hour, according
to the Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
   Severe thunderstorms in the state were expected this morning,
but the National Weather Service said the rain should clear by the
afternoon, with high temperatures in the 80s.
   The region had three straight days with highs over 90 degrees.
   On Thursday, New England's electricity demand hit an all-time
summer high.
   In Connecticut, hospitals treated dozens of people for heat
exhaustion and respiratory problems. Forty-one children on a trip
in eastern Connecticut were treated at Windham Community Memorial
Hospital for heat exhaustion. They were all released by Thursday
night.
   Out West, high winds overturned a trailer near Lewistown, Mont.,
and isolated thunderstorms lingered over northwestern Montana and
the Nebraska Panhandle early today.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms in the Southwest produced
locally heavy rains in Utah and Arizona Thursday night. Flash
flooding was reported in southwestern Utah and in two counties in
southwestern Arizona.
   The high for the nation on Thursday was 112 degrees at Bullhead
City, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms likely
across New England and the mid-Atlantic states; scattered showers
and thunderstorms from the south Atlantic coastal states across the
lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys to southern and eastern
portions of the Ohio Valley; scattered showers and thunderstorms
over western North Dakota, the northern Rockies, Utah and Arizona;
and isolated thunderstorms during the afternoon over the central
and southern Rockies, the southern Plains and Missouri.
   Predicted highs: in the 80s and 90s across most of the nation;
in the 70s over the Upper Great Lakes, the northern Pacific Coast,
and along the California coast; and from 100 to 110 degrees over
the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 48
degrees at Olympia, Wash., to 89 degrees at Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
