<FIRST>r a PM-JasonLovesNY     07-28 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jason Loves NY,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Won't Use NY Logo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state says it's beaten Jason, the
indestructible hockey-masked killer of ``Friday the 13th'' fame.
   But Jason says this wasn't a battle he planned to fight anyway.
   State Economic Development Department officials claimed victory
Thursday in a battle with Paramount Pictures over use of the
copyright ``I Love New York'' logo in promoting the newest ``Friday
the 13th'' movie.
   The ads showed Jason, who periodically rises to slash up a camp
full of teen-agers, cutting through the heart of an ``I Love New
York'' poster.
   The ads were promoting the eighth in the series of ``Friday the
13th'' movies, titled ``Jason Takes Manhattan.''
   But New York officials objected to the filmmaker using the ``I
Love New York'' logo without paying the proper franchise fee.
Earlier this month, they threatened to sue for copyright
infringement.
   ``You slash our heart, we'll cut you off at the knees,'' said
state agency spokesman Harold Holzer. ``There's someone in New York
who's tougher than Jason,'' he said, referring to state Economic
Development Commissioner Vincent Tese.
   On Thursday, according to state officials, Paramount said it
would drop the ``I Love New York.''
   Paramount spokeswoman Deborah Rosen said the poster was intended
as a ``teaser'' that was scheduled to be dropped from circulation
once the movie is released today.
   A new poster, to be released with the movie, shows Jason looming
over the New York City skyline wielding a hunting knife. It carries
the slogan, ``New York has a new problem.''
   Holzer said the state has dropped its lawsuit.
</TEXT>
