<FIRST>r a PM-Khashoggi     07-28 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khashoggi,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Khashoggi Released from Jail, Must Wear Electronic Bracelet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi financier Adnan Khashoggi has traded his
jail cell for a 30,000-square-foot luxury apartment and an
electronic monitoring device he must wear after posting $10 million
bail.
   Khashoggi, who had been jailed in New York since Switzerland
extradited him to the United States on July 19, was released
Thursday after his brothers posted two $5 million checks.
   As he left the federal courthouse, Khashoggi smiled for cameras
and promised he would stay in the United States to face charges
that he helped former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos and his
wife Imelda defraud the Philippine treasury.
   ``I am pleased that the courts have granted me bail,'' he said
before being driven away in a silver limousine to his Fifth Avenue
apartment. ``I am anxious to begin work for my defense and look
forward to clearing my name at trial.''
   Khashoggi, Mrs. Marcos and another defendant, the California
Overseas Bank of Los Angeles, are scheduled to go on trial in
March. Marcos has been severed from the trial for health reasons.
The Marcoses are charged with stealing more than $100 million from
their government's treasury to buy real estate and art in New York.
   Khashoggi, who allegedly posed as the owner of some of the
assets as a cover, was indicted on racketeering, conspiracy, mail
fraud and obstruction of justice charges. However, Switzerland
released him on the last two charges only.
   Khashoggi's movements will be monitored by an electronic device
he must wear on his ankle. Although he can leave his apartment, he
is not allowed to travel outside the court's jurisdiction _
Manhattan, the Bronx and the northern New York suburbs.
   The duplex apartment, featured in House &amp; Garden magazine in
1984, was carved out of 16 separate apartments and contains such
amenities as a swimming pool in a two-story atrium, a sauna, a
7-by-10-foot bed covered in sable, marble floors, and Cartier
knickknacks.
   The Saudi-based National Commercial Bank filed a foreclosure
suit on the apartment last month. But defense lawyers told the
court the bank has given Khashoggi a year to clear up the $28.7
million default.
   Khashoggi, once one of the world's richest men, submitted
documents to the court last week indicating a net worth of $53.8
million.
   Khashoggi was released after an appeals judge denied a request
by prosecutors to revoke the bail arrangement set Tuesday by U.S.
District Judge John Keenan.
   One of the Barclays Bank checks posted as bail was signed by his
brother, Essam Khashoggi, and the other by his half-brother, Amr
Khashoggi.
   Prosecutors had opposed his release, saying that Khashoggi had
concealed his true wealth and was likely to flee.
   Khashoggi faces up to five years in jail and a $250,000 fine on
each of the two charges of mail fraud and obstruction of justice.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
