<DOCNO> AP890728-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Pope     07-28 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Pope,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope to Visit Mexico in May</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II will visit Mexico for a
week in May and may take part in the canonization of Juan Diego,
the Aztec peasant whose visions of the Virgin Mary gave Mexico its
patron saint.
   Several officials said the pope's visit also may coincide with
an official rapprochement between the Mexican government and the
church.
   The Foreign Ministry said the Mexican government gave its formal
approval for the papal visit, John Paul's first to Mexico since
January 1979.
   ``The trip was confirmed quite a long time ago; the only thing
that remained was the consent of the government,'' Monsignor Genaro
Alamilla, spokesman for the Episcopal Conference of Mexico's Roman
Catholic Church, told a news conference Thursday.
   It was not clear if the pope is intending to visit Cuba on the
overseas trip. President Fidel Castro in January invited him to the
Communist-ruled country, and Cuban and Vatican officials have held
discussions since then.
   Church officials said the pope would tour several southern
Mexico states and may take part in a ceremony canonizing Diego.
Diego has already been beatified, the next-to-the-last step in
attaining sainthood.
   The constitution of this overwhelmingly Catholic nation, written
when the church was considered closer to the upper classes than to
most of the people, does not recognize the church as a legal entity
and bars priests from any political activity, even voting.
   However, President Carlos Salinas de Gortari said in his
inaugural address Dec. 1 that it was time to revise relations
between the church and the state.
   Representatives of the church and the government have been
holding talks on the possibility of amending the constitution and
opening relations with the Vatican.
   ``The papal visit is not a confirmation that these institutions
will establish relations, but we can't discard the possibility of
an historical coincidence,'' said Archbishop Juan Jose Posadas of
Guadalajara, the head of the organizing committee for the papal
visit.
   Monsignor Geronimo Prigione, the Vatican representative in
Mexico, said the seven-day visit in May is not ``to steal power or
press for a legal change in the church-state relationship.''
   Diego's visions of the Virgin of Guadalupe are regarded by many
scholars as crucial to the conversion of Mexico from a pagan,
Indian nation to a Catholic, Spanish colony.
   Contemporary accounts say Diego first saw the virgin on Dec. 9,
1531, on a hillside where there had been a temple to the Aztec
goddess Tonantzin. She told him to tell the bishop she wanted her
own temple built on the spot.
   The bishop didn't believe Diego and asked for proof. The fourth
time she appeared, according to the accounts, the virgin filled
Diego's cloak with out-of-season roses. The accounts say that when
Diego unfurled the cloak to show the roses to the bishops, it was
imprinted with the virgin's portrait.
   The cloak is the centerpiece of the main altar at the Basilica
of Guadalupe in Mexico City, the shrine built on the site of
Diego's visions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
