<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyTrial     07-28 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsley Hotel Paid Mrs. Helmsley's Credit Card Bills, Former Aide
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helmsley businesses footed the bill for
thousands of dollars' worth of shoes and other items bought by
hotel queen Leona Helmsley, her former personal assistant said.
   Testifying at Mrs. Helmsley's tax-evasion trial in U.S. District
Court on Thursday, Martin Goldstein, the former assistant, said the
Park Lane Hotel paid most of Mrs. Helmsley's personal credit card
bills.
   Goldstein said the bill for Mrs. Helmsley's American Express
card, which she used only for catalog purchases, was passed on to a
Helmsley real estate company.
   In other testimony, Goldstein said he discovered Mrs. Helmsley's
record book listing expenses at her Greenwich, Conn., mansion more
than a year after government investigators had issued subpoenas for
documents relating to the estate, Dunnellen Hall.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is accused of evading taxes by disguising
renovations at the estate and other personal items as business
expenses. Two former aides, Joseph Licari and Frank Turco, are
charged with assisting in the alleged scheme.
   Mrs. Helmsley's 80-year-old husband, Harry, was indicted but
severed from the trial because he was found mentally incompetent.
   Goldstein said he discovered Mrs. Helmsley's Dunnellen file in
April 1988, a short time after her indictment, as he helped her
look through her office desk for a personal letter.
   Mrs. Helmsley told him to give the file to one of her lawyers,
he said.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita submitted copies of Mrs.
Helmsley's credit card bills as evidence.
   They showed numerous purchases at tony stores such as Tiffany &amp;
Co., Henri Bendel, Ann Taylor, Marshall Fields, Saks Fifth Avenue,
Gucci Shops and Delman Shoes, where Mrs. Helmsley bought thousands
of dollars in footwear. Many of the items were later returned.
   Among the purchases she made were $280 in clocks and watches
from Tiffany's, a $281 belt from Ann Taylor, a $345 men's robe from
Henri Bendel and $259 worth of briefs from Saks.
   Goldstein testified that Mrs. Helmsley did some of her shopping
by catalog.
   ``She would mark what she wanted, fold the page and give them to
me,'' Goldstein said, adding that he would give the catalogs to a
secretary to call in the orders.
   Goldstein was to be questioned by defense lawyers when the trial
resumes Monday.
</TEXT>
