<FIRST>u i PM-Iran 2ndLd-Writethru   07-28 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0501,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Prepares to Usher in Post-Khomeini Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with heavy voting reported, polling
time extended. Pickup 5th pvs, `Rafsanjani voted...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, all but assured of
victory in today's presidential election, has begun forming a
Cabinet that includes economists and technocrats to help guide this
troubled nation into the post-Khomeini era, sources say.
   The early turnout in Tehran was sluggish despite the
exhortations of Iranian leaders over the last few days for a
massive demonstration of unity. The opposition claimed there was
little enthusiasm for the election.
   Only a few dozen people were seen at polling stations in Tehran
after they opened at 7 a.m., although voting appeared to pick up
later.
   However, Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi told Tehran
Radio that voting was so heavy in some provinces that ``the polling
stations are asking for more personnel ... because of the crowds.''
   He said polling was extended for two hours beyond the scheduled
5 p.m. closing time.
   There was no word on when the results would be announced. The
government did not say how many eligible voters there are, but the
number was estimated at 25 million _ about half the population _
during parliamentary elections last year.
   The main Iranian opposition group, the Mujahedeen Khalq or
People's Holy Warriors, claimed polling was ``extremely quiet.''
   Among the voters was Rafsanjani, the 55-year-old Parliament
speaker and commander in chief, who was so confident of victory he
did not campaign.
   Rafsanjani voted at a special booth in the courtyard of the
modest residence that belonged to the late Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini in the north Tehran suburb of Jamaran.
   Rafsanjani cast two votes in separate boxes _ one for the
presidential ballot, the other for a referendum on whether to
increase the president's powers _ before camera crews from Iran's
state-run television.
   ``I'm happy to see the people voting, and this proves that the
revolution is strong. But I'm sorry the imam is no longer with
us,'' Rafsanjani said. Khomeini was referred to as the imam, a
Moslem term for religious leader.
   About 100 Revolutionary Guards and local residents chanted ``God
is great!'' and cheered the turbanned Rafsanjani, a middle-ranking
cleric, as he cast his votes.
   Prosecutor-General Mohammad Musavi Khoeniha, who led the crowds
that stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in November 1979, also
voted at Khomeini's house with other senior Iranian religious and
political figures.
   Iranian leaders and the state media for days have been exhorting
Iranians to turn out to demonstrate unity following the Khomeini's
death on June 3.
   ``Each vote cast is a bullet fired at the heart of Iran's
enemies,'' the radical Jomhuri Islami daily said this week.
   But one disgruntled merchant, who declined to be identified,
said: ``Why bother to vote? Rafsanjani has been part of the
government for years and he's responsible with the other clerics
for mess the economy's in.''
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on the condition they not be
identified, say Rafsanjani already has selected a Cabinet that
would include economists and technocrats, some of them dumped from
earlier administrations because of ideological and policy
differences.
   Newspapers polls predict Rafsanjani will win 86 percent of the
vote.
   The elections were moved up from Aug. 18 to accelerate the
transition of power following the death of Khomeini, who founded
the fundamentalist republic in 1979 that toppled the regime of the
late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi.
   Also on the ballot is a referendum on proposed constitutional
amendments that would give the presidency new powers. Khomeini
urged the changes to eliminate competing power centers that have
paralyzed the government.
   Incumbent President Ali Khamenei's second four-year term expires
Oct. 5 and he cannot run for a third term. He was elected Iran's
spiritual leader to succeed Khomeini on June 4.
   Khamenei is allied with Rafsanjani, who heads Iran's
``pragmatist faction.'' They are expected to open up the economy,
which conservative radicals have kept under tight reins since the
revolution, and to build bridges with the West, although that could
take time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
