<FIRST>r a PM-DeafSchoolSuperintendent     07-28 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaf School Superintendent,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled School for Deaf Gets First Deaf Superintendent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mississippi School for the Deaf has
its first deaf superintendent, a move applauded by critics who said
reported abuse could have been prevented if the administration were
more sensitive to students' needs.
   Michael Finneran, vocational principal at the California School
for the Deaf in Fremont, said Thursday that getting the job
achieves a near lifelong goal.
   ``This has really fulfilled my dream _ I've wanted to be a
superintendent since I was a little boy,'' Finneran, 41, said
through an interpreter, his 14-year-old daughter Clara.
   The state Board of Education offered Finneran the
$49,000-per-year post last week. He is to begin in mid-August.
   ``I don't think there's any question that this will be a big
boost,'' said Walter Moore, associate superintendent for programs
at the state Department of Education. ``I think the deaf community
will respond very favorably.''
   Finneran inherits a school on the rebound from months of scandal
that led to the ouster of longtime Superintendent Alma Alexander in
January.
   Hinds County Youth Court officials ruled in December that 21
students had been abused or neglected and mandated sweeping changes
in the organization of the 135-year-old school.
