<FIRST>u w PM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0441 07-28 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-HUD Official Fails to Appear Before House Panel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new to UPDATE with Wilson failing to show, subcommittee
to vote on subpoena. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Wilson, 41...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A onetime top aide to former HUD Secretary
Samuel Pierce failed to appear today before a congressional panel
investigating abuses in housing programs, and the chairman said he
will seek to subpoena the witness.
   Lance Wilson, former executive assistant to Pierce, did not
appear as scheduled today before the House Government Operations
subcommittee on employment and housing.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the subcommittee, on
Thursday turned down a request by Wilson for a postponement.
Wilson, now a first vice president at Paine Webber brokerage in New
York, said his attorney was in the hospital.
   It was the third time Wilson had asked for an extension, Lantos
said.
   ``There are certain questions that I want to ask Mr. Wilson with
respect to his request for a postponement,'' Lantos said. ``With
186 attorneys listed on the law firm's letterhead, could another
attorney not be able to advise Mr. Wilson, who is himself an
attorney, as to his constitutional rights?''
   Lantos said the subcommittee will vote Wednesday on issuing a
subpoena for Wilson to appear Sept. 27 and to produce ``all
relevant documents and records.''
   Lantos also read aloud a letter from HUD Inspector General Paul
A. Adams detailing his office's unsuccessful attempts to persuade
Wilson to answer questions for an investigation of HUD's moderate
rehabilitation program.
   Wilson would have been questioned today about his involvement in
several projects through a development group led by Philip Winn,
former assistant secretary of housing and current ambassador to
Switzerland, Lantos said.
   Appearing before the panel today was Joseph D. Monticciolo,
HUD's former New York regional administator.
   The panel planned to question him about his involvement in HUD
projects in White Plains, N.Y., and Puerto Rico, Lantos said.
   Wilson, 41, served as Pierce's top aide from 1981-84. He was
succeeded by Deborah Gore Dean, whom he recommended. Dean has cited
her Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination for
refusing to testify before the panel.
   After leaving HUD, Wilson worked at the New York City Housing
Development Corp., a group that raised money through bond issues
for low- and moderate-income housing development.
   Wilson also has been revealed as the owner or developer of six
projects that received HUD rehabilitation funds after he left the
agency.
   Monticciolo, a 51-year-old architect from Woodbury, N.Y., was
regional administrator from 1981-88, overseeing HUD programs in New
York, New Jersey, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   Since January 1988, he has been chief executive of Eagle Capital
Group, a real estate development company whose partners benefited
handsomely a result of Monticciolo's recommendations as
administrator, according to records and published reports.
   He was offered the $125,000-a-year job in 1987 by Sheldon
Goldstein, a wealthy Rockland County, N.Y., developer, the
company's lawyer told New York Newsday last month.
   Government records and published reports reveal that most
members of Eagle were involved in a Goldstein-led investment group
that bought seven housing projects from HUD in 1983. The group put
up $550,000 in cash, selling the projects three years later at an
estimated $17 million profit.
   On his last financial disclosure form filed with the federal
government a month after his retirement, Monticciolo listed a 15
percent ownership in Eagle. He did not place a monetary value on
his share.
   Eagle's 10 initial investors put up a total of $500,000 to
launch the company, Newsday reported. Monticciolo kicked in just
``several hundred dollars,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
