<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     07-28 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crippled Tanker Prepared For Sunday Bay Entry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Exxon Cleanup, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crippled oil tanker Exxon Valdez is still
aiming for a Sunday arrival in San Diego Bay, but the war of words
between state officials and Exxon isn't over.
   The Valdez, which spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil after
slamming into a reef in Alaska, must pass final navigational and
environmental tests before being allowed into the bay for extensive
repairs at the National Steel and Shipbuilding Co., Coast Guard Lt.
Larry Solberg said Thursday.
   The ship will be required to execute a series of maneuvers
offshore to simulate what it will have to do once inside the harbor
and it also must pass a final underwater inspection when it reaches
the mouth of the bay.
   A series of suspicious oily spills and other problems off the
California coast caused state officials to halt the Exxon Valdez so
tests could be conducted and emergency repairs could be made.
   ``Test results confirm that recent slicks that were reported in
the vicinity of the Valdez ... could not have come from the
Valdez,'' Frank Iarossi, president of Exxon Shipping Co., said
Thursday in a statement.
   State environmental officials said Iarossi was mistaken.
   ``I have not seen any results that indicate that,'' said Lt.
Reed Smith, pollution-response coordinator for the California
Department of Fish and Game.
   ``I'm quite concerned that we have a company that has had
releases of oil from its ship and which denies having releases.
That heightens my concern.''
   Smith said his department and the Coast Guard have gathered
evidence of three separate releases of oil from the Exxon Valdez
since it arrived off the coast of San Diego.
   Exxon officials said following the devastating oil spill in
Alaska that the Valdez was oil-free and that towing it southward
presented no threat to the environment.
   Among stipulations of an agreement reached Wednesday with Exxon
was one requiring it to have no discharges for 24 hours before any
attempt to enter the bay.
   The Valdez has been about 50 miles offshore for the past two
weeks since the Coast Guard ordered it away from the bay until any
leakage problems were solved.
   Exxon has put up $20 million to guarantee the Valdez's
performance in the bay and to cover the costs of a cleanup should a
spill occur.
</TEXT>
