<FIRST>r a PM-IsraeliDiplomat     07-28 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israeli Diplomat,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Arab Israeli Consul General to Leave Atlanta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only Arab ever to head an Israeli diplomatic
mission is leaving his post as consul general in Atlanta.
   Mohammed Khalid Massarwa, 46, said Thursday that the Israeli
Foreign Ministry told him his two-year term would not be extended
because the ministry was considering closing the Atlanta consulate.
   An Israeli Embassy spokesman in Washington, David Peleg, said
there are no immediate plans to close the consulate. He would not
discuss the reasons for not extending Massarwa's appointment.
   Much of Atlanta's Jewish community supported Massarwa as
evidence of Israel's commitment to pluralistic democracy.
   ``First and foremost, I thought it was terrific to have him
here,'' said Harriet Zimmerman, a vice president of the American
Israel Public Affairs Committee. ``I have a lot of respect for
him.''
   But critics who campaigned for Massarwa's return to Israel said
the ministry is dismissing him because of his comments favoring a
Palestinian homeland.
   Jay Starkman, leader of a ``Massarwa Must Go'' campaign, also
said an Arab could not properly represent the Jewish state.
   Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens had denounced Massarwa for
comments he made last summer in a speech to the Atlanta chapter of
the United Nations Association. Two Israeli newspapers reported in
September that Massarwa said allowing the Palestinians to establish
a homeland might solve Israel's security problems.
   Massarwa's statement conflicted with the policy of Israel's
governing Likud bloc. The rival Labor Party was responsible for
Massarwa's appointment in 1987.
