<FIRST>r w PM-BaseClosings     07-28 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Base Closings,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rules Committee Strikes Down Base Closing Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Rules Committee has rejected an
amendment that would tie the future of some military bases to an
audit, a measure that some lawmakers hoped would keep their
installations open.
   The move means the amendment will likely be dropped next week
when the military construction bill is considered by the House.
   The committee, which sets the ground rules for votes on the
House floor, said Thursday that the amendment violated rules that
bar ``legislating'' in spending bills.
   The committee, however, delivered a victory to supporters of the
Presidio, a San Franciso base that has been ordered to close.
   When the military construction bill goes to a floor vote,
lawmakers will be allowed to offer an amendment that would keep the
base open.
   ``As you can see, a little favoritism was played by the Rules
Committee,'' said Rep. Ed Madigan, R-Ill., whose district includes
Chanute Air Force Base, one of several that was covered by the
amendment rejected by the Rules Committee.
   Madigan said he will ask lawmakers to defeat the rules when the
military construction bill comes up next week, but he added: ``I
don't think that effort will be successful.''
   The amendment, as approved by the Appropriations Committee on
Wednesday, would have prevented the government from closing some
bases unless a audit found the savings to the Pentagon over six
years exceeds the cost of closure or reorganization.
   These bases, ordered to close or reorganize, were affected by
the Rules Committee action:
   George AFB, Mather AFB, Norton AFB, and Hunters Point Naval
Station, all in California; Pease AFB in New Hampshire; Fort
Sheridan and Chanute AFB in Illinois; Jefferson Proving Ground in
Indiana; Fort Dix in New Jersey; Lexington Army Depot in Kentucky;
Fort Meade and Fort Holabird in Maryland; Fort Devens in
Massachusetts; and Fort Huachuca in Arizona.
</TEXT>
