<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     07-28 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hashimoto's Chances Grow to Be Japan's New Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A governing party elder today took himself out of
the running to be Japan's next prime minister, strengthening the
chance that the party's youngest ever secretary-general will reach
the nation's highest office.
   The scandal-plagued Liberal Democrats formally decided today to
choose a new leader Aug. 8 in a vote by the party's members of
Parliament and seek his approval in Parliament Aug. 10, party
officials said.
   The secretary-general, Ryutaro Hashimoto, is in charge of the
search for a successor to Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, who announced
his resignation to take responsibility for the Liberal Democrats'
unprecedented defeat in parliamentary elections on Sunday.
   Former Deputy Prime Minister Shin Kanemaru, 75, who had been
viewed as opposing the 51-year-old Hashimoto, today said he had no
intention to be prime minister.
   Speculation centered on Hashimoto, whose star has been rising
fast in the conservative party in the past two months while Uno's
leadership was cut short by an influence-peddling scandal and
allegations he paid a geisha for sex.
   Hashimoto's chances were further bolstered when former Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, who controls the third largest faction in
the party, also said he preferred to have an ``young and
progressive'' person to head the party and the government.
   Uno announced his resignation after Sunday elections in which
his party lost control of the 252-member upper house of Parliament
for the first time in its 34 years.
   The party has a majority in the more powerful lower house of
Parliament, which chooses the prime minister.
   A party official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
``leaders seem to be trying to build consensus within the party
over Hashimoto and I have not heard anyone express strong
opposition so far.''
   But, he said, some party elders insist it is ``premature for the
party to give power to such a young politician in such a turbulent
time.''
   For decades, Japan's prime ministers have been men in their
middle 60s or older who reached the office after a serving a series
of increasingly important Cabinet and party posts. Hashimoto, in
Parliament since he was 26, has not held top Cabinet posts. He rose
to the No. 2 party post in June.
   Uno was virtually handpicked by former Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita two months ago, after Takeshita resigned to take
responsibility for a widespread influence-peddling scandal that
touched much of the party's top leadership.
   Officials of the Japan Socialist Party, which seeks to form a
coalition with three small centrist parties against the governing
party, said it would ask them to support Socialist leader Takako
Doi in the prime ministerial election in Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
