<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 3rdLd-Writethru   07-28 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0539,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Agrees To Begin Pullout, 74 Killed in Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to to UPDATE with 74 killed in anti-government attacks,
anti-India protests, curfew extended. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India today signed an agreement to
start withdrawing its peacekeeping troops, and at least 74 people
were reported killed in one of the worst days of ethnic violence on
this island nation.
   An Indian official said the pullout would begin Saturday, the
same day that talks would begin in New Delhi to set a timetable for
the withdrawal.
   The troops arrived in Sri Lanka two years ago, and President
Ranasinghe Premadasa had ordered them to be out of the country by
Saturday.
   ``We should be grateful to the government of India for agreeing
to recall the Indian army,'' Premadasa said in a prepared speech
for broadcast over television and radio tonight.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi had said a hasty withdrawal
could lead to more bloodshed on the island, where Tamil rebels are
fighting the Sinhalese-dominated government for a homeland in the
northeast.
   But an Indian Foreign Ministry spokesman, Aftab Seth, said the
two countries signed an agreement in Colombo today to begin pulling
out the estimated 45,000 Indian troops stationed in the region.
   In New Delhi, the Indian government said its troops would begin
pulling out Saturday. The government did not say how many soldiers
were to leave or when the withdrawal is to be completed.
   A Sri Lanaka Foreign Ministry official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said a seven-member Sri Lankan delegation headed by
Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne would fly to New Delhi Saturday
to start discussing a timetable.
   On Thursday, Wijeratne demanded that before he would travel to
New Delhi, India also would have to accept Premadasa as
commander-in-chief of all forces in Sri Lanka and honor a
cease-fire with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the largest
and the most militant rebel group. But Seth said Wijeratne will
discuss those two conditions when the minister travels to New Delhi.
   Sri Lanka's government clamped a nationwide curfew at midnight
Thursday and posted soldiers and heavily armed policemen in all
major cities. The curfew was extended this evening until 6 a.m.
Sunday.
   Despite the curfew, state-run television said at least 74 people
were killed in ethnic violence and nearly all of the deaths
occurred in the Sinhalese heartland, where extremists oppose
limited autonomy the government has offered to the Tamils and want
all the Indian troops out immediately.
   Sri Lankan television said most of those who died were killed by
Sri Lankan forces in areas where the Indians do not operate. No
other details on the killings were immediately available.
   Indian troops initially were deployed to supervise the July 29,
1987, accord that promised limited self-rule to Sri Lanka's
minority Tamils.
   In exchange, militant Tamils had to agree to surrender their
weapons. While most militias abided by the accord, he Tamil Tigers
backed out and began attacking Indian soldiers. About 1,000 troops
have died.
   After the Tamil Tigers opened peace talks with the Sri Lankan
government on June 1, Premadasa demanded that Indian troops
withdraw. His repeated calls for the withdrawal and Gandhi's
refusals led to fears of an armed confrontation between Indian and
Sri Lankan troops.
   However, Wijeratne ruled out a military clash with the powerful
neighbor in the northeast, saying ``we know our limitations.''
   Sri Lanka's army has about 40,000 troops.
   A leader of the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front, a
Tamil party that fears genocidal by the Tamil Tigers once the
Indian soldiers leave, said his party can mobilize ``10,000
cadres.''
   But the figure given by Ira Kuganeswaran, a member of
Parliament, is believed by observers to be highly inflated.
Kuganeswaran spoke by telephone from Vavuniya, 135 miles northeast
of Colombo.
</TEXT>
