<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels     07-28 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-Rebels,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uganda Rebel Leader Surrenders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the rebel Holy Spirit
Movement has surrendered to the government, Radio Uganda reported
Friday.
   Seberino Lukoya, the father of the movement's former warrior
priestess, gave himself up Tuesday to government troops in the
northern Ugandan town of Gulu, the report said.
   The Holy Spirit Movement has concentrated its activities in the
Gulu region since late 1987 when government troops crushed the
rebels' attempts to march on Kampala. The rebels died by the
thousands.
   The rebellion began earlier that year under the leadership of
Alice Lakwena, who convinced her followers to go into war unarmed
and smeared with an oil they believed would ward off bullets.
   Ms. Lakwena fled to Kenya in December 1987, while Holy Spirit
remnants fled north where her father took over its leadership.
   Lukoya said his surrender was a sign the guerrilla warfare
plaguing northern Uganda would soon end, according to Radio Uganda.
   The Holy Spirit Movement is one of several insurgencies fighting
President Yoweri Museveni's 3-year-old government.
</TEXT>
