<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Soviet     07-28 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Soviet,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Sound Out Space Development Cooperation With Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has proposed that the Japanese
provide technology for a joint project to develop a space aircraft,
Japanese officials said Friday.
   The proposals were made Tuesday when six Soviet officials
visited Japan's National Space Development Agency, an agency
official said.
   The delegates said the Soviet Union is ready to provide Japan
with technology to manufacture the Energia rocket, the world's
largest rocket that is capable of launching an 18-ton payload, or
export to Japan a rocket that can lift a two-ton payload, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The smaller rocket is priced at about $30 million, according to
the major economic daily Nihon Keizai Shimbun.
   ``We were just amazed at the (Soviet) proposals,'' the agency
official said.
   He said a Soviet delegation visited the government-financed
organization handling Japan's space development and rocket
launching, but never made such ``business-oriented proposals.''
   The latest Soviet offer is considered aimed at obtainining
foreign currency under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program of
social and economic reforms, the official said.
   An official of the Science and Technology Agency, who also would
not allow his name to be used, said the Soviet delegates visited
his agency July 17 but put forth no concrete terms regarding joint
projects.
   Japan plans to develop an unmanned spacecraft in the next decade
and eventually wants to send its own astronauts into space aboard
Japanese-made vessels.
   Last month, the Space Development Commission, Japan's highest
government organ supervising Japanese aerospace programs, announced
a 10-year plan that included development of the next-generation H-2
rocket, capable of lifting a two-ton payload.
   To date, Japan has had 19 successful launches with its N- and
H-series rockets, each of them carrying up to 1,200 pounds.
   It has yet to test a two-stage liquid combustion engine to be
used in the H-2 rocket, scheduled to be launched in 1993.
   The Soviet delegates, who came for the opening of a design
exposition, also met July 18 with officials of the Society of
Japanese Aircraft Contractors, a group of 180 Japanese companies
engaged in space-related products manufacturing.
   Western observers say it will not be long until Japan ventures
into the commercial arena to compete in space technology just as it
has in the automobile, computer and electronics markets.
</TEXT>
