<FIRST>u a PM-DC-10Attendants 3rdLd-Writethru a0571 07-28 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Attendants, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0571,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 232 Attendants Tell Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `Many of...' to restore earlier version's CORRECTION
to McGrady sted O'Grady.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendants from United Flight 232 today
described the horror of the DC-10's fiery crash in Sioux City,
Iowa, last week, and the joy at finding so many survivors.
   It was ``a roller-coaster ride with special effects,'' said
flight attendant Timothy Owens, who was seated in the middle of the
plane when it went down.
   He was one of five of the eight Chicago-based crew members who
were aboard the plane when it crashed July 19 who appeared at a
news conference this morning sponsored by their union, the
Association of Flight Attendants.
   Seven of the eight were among the 185 survivors of the crash.
   Association spokeswoman Cindy Yeast said the news conference was
an opportunity for the flight attendants to tell how they were
involved in the crash that killed 111 people.
   Most who spoke were teary-eyed and choked up as they described
the terror of the crash.
   ``The first time we hit, we bounced and I had my eyes open,''
Owens said. ``I saw overhead bins and coils and wires from the
ceiling. ``After that, that's when the tail section of the plane
just split apart and I saw a big beam of sunlight just coming
through the big opening in the back. And that's when we started to
roll over on the right wing.''
   Donna McGrady, one of the flight attendants, said she had her
eyes open as the plane crash-landed.
   ``I said, `Oh, God ....' The important thing that I thought
about was when's it going to stop.''
   McGrady remained belted in her seat as the DC-10's tail section,
where she was located, split off from the rest of the plane and
came to rest.
   ``At that particular time, to come out and to look and to see
nothing but debris...'' she said, her voice breaking. ``I said,
`Oh, God, where is the other part of the aircraft.'''
   Many of the at least 75 United employees in the audience at the
news conference dabbed at tears as McGrady told of the aftermath of
the crash, and her happiness at seeing survivors emerge.
   ``I said, `Thank you, Jesus, for the things that you've done for
us because we know there's no other way we could have made it
without your presence,'' she said.
   The head flight attendant on the plane, Janice Brown, said she
could not think of anything the flight attendants could have done
to save more people, and could not explain why those who survived
did while others died.
   ``I'm not going to second-guess God,'' Brown said.
   The crowd at a ballroom at O'Hare International Airport gave a
standing ovation to the five flight attendants from Flight 232, as
well as three of their colleagues who assisted on the ground. One
crew member and a flight attendant who was on board the plane but
not on duty at the time remain hospitalized. The eighth member of
the original crew, flight attendant Rene Le Beau, was killed in the
crash.
   After the news conference, United employees held a memorial
service for Le Beau and for four other United employees who were
aboard but off-duty and died in the crash.
</TEXT>
