<FIRST>u a PM-ChineseStudents 1stLd-Writethru a0522 07-28 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Students, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0522,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Hear Vow From Demonstration Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with leader addressing today's
meeting. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Wu'er, speaking...' Adds byline. Pan is
cq on 2nd reference for Zhongdang Pan in last graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRIS CHANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``goddess of democracy'' will again be erected
in Tiananmen Square despite a bloody crackdown on demonstrators
there by the Chinese military, a leader of the Chinese
pro-democracy movement said today.
   ``Some say China has no hope for democracy, but I say the hope
is just beginning,'' said Wu'er Kaixi, 21, an organizer of the
student demonstrations in Beijing, at the opening session of a
weekend Chinese Student Congress in the United States.
   ``I believe the Chinese can be united and will erect a goddess
of democracy in Tiananmen Square one day,'' he said.
   Such a ``goddess,'' made of plaster and fashioned after the
Statue of Liberty, had been erected in the square by the
demonstrating students before the military moved in on June 4.
   More than 300 people attended today's the session at the
University of Illinois-Chicago. Students or teachers from 150 U.S.
schools were expected.
   T-shirts being sold at the gathering included some depicting a
man blocking a line of tanks in Beijing's central square. The
statement ``You are not alone'' is printed on the shirts.
   Wu'er, speaking in Chinese, took aim at his homeland's
government.
   ``If the present communist government is so confident that
people love them, why should they be scared of elections?'' he
asked. ``Because there is a chance they may end up in history's
wastebasket.''
   Wu'er and Yan Jiaqui, 47, a political scientist, fled China
after the military crushed protests. They surfaced in Paris, where
they have been trying to rally worldwide support for the
pro-democracy movement in their homeland.
   They came to Chicago for the weekend strategy session, and both
were among a dozen people on stage at today's meeting, despite
earlier reports that they feared for their safety.
   ``I can no longer be afraid,'' Wu'er said Thursday night.
   ``I've already said what I have to do is to carry forward the
cause of those who died,'' he said on the ABC News program
``Nightline.''
   Wu'er, speaking from a television studio in Chicago, said on
``Nightline'' that conditions in China have grown more dangerous in
recent weeks as the government continues its crackdown on students
who led demonstrations in Beijing and other Chinese cities.
   ``I'm not sure anyone else will be able to come out,'' he said
of other student dissidents. ``But those who manage to come out
should carry forward the tasks that they wish to carry out, and
those who died wished to carry out.''
   Chinese officials have been harassing Chinese student activists
in the United States by making death threats in anonymous telephone
calls, Minxin Pei, 31, a Harvard political science student and
spokesman for the fledgling student congress, said at a news
conference.
   He said officials from the Chinese consulate in New York visited
his apartment, called him a traitor and a fool for his
pro-democracy activities and threatened ``big trouble'' if he
persisted.
   The student congress will try to set up a powerful radio station
south of China, said Zhongdang Pan, a 31-year-old journalism
graduate student at the University of Wisconsin.
   Pan said he also hopes to get a Chinese language newspaper
published in America and to send copies to China.
</TEXT>
