<FIRST>u i PM-Libya-Crash 4thLd-Writethru   07-28 0793</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libya-Crash, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0554,0814</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aviation Director Says Landing System at Airport Was Not Working</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with aviation director saying
instrument landing system at airport was not working at time of crash.
Pickup 21st pvs, `Investigators from...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal aviation director said today
the instrument landing system at Tripoli's airport was not working
when a Korean Air DC-10 undershot the runway and crashed while
trying to land in heavy fog.
   The system gives the pilot an automatic indication of the center
of the runway, but it had not worked for several months, Mohamed
Abughres, director of civil aviation, told reporters.
   Airline officials said 77 people died in the crash Thursday,
including six killed on the ground when the jet slammed into
farmhouses and cars about a mile short of the runway. They said 128
of the 199 people on board survived. Libyan officials said 78
people died on the jet.
   A diplomat at the South Korean Embassy in the Libyan capital,
who identified himself only as Mr. Chun, said many victims were
badly burned, making a precise count difficult.
   The crash was the second of a DC-10 in eight days. A United Air
Lines DC-10 went down July 19 in Sioux City, Iowa, killing 111
people. That crash occurred when a tail engine blew apart, cutting
off the flow of hydraulic fluid needed to control the jet.
   The president of Korean Air ruled out pilot error in the Tripoli
crash, but an investigator quoted the pilot as saying he may have
been wrong to try to land in the fog.
   Another KAL pilot was quoted as saying the jet had experienced
mechanical problems and that pilots had complained about it. ``We
pilots complained a lot about the DC-10 because it made lots of
squeaking sounds when flown in bad weather,'' South Korea's Munhwa
Broadcasting Corp. quoted the unidentified pilot as saying.
   That pilot said the airline and the government's Transportation
Ministry ignored their complaints about the 17-year-old jet.
   Libyan authorities defended as ``excellent'' the actions of the
air traffic controllers who were working when the plane crashed.
   JANA said the airport control tower told the pilot, Kim Ho-jung,
there was heavy fog and and visibility was only 800 feet. It said a
Soviet Aeroflot jetliner, informed of similar conditions about an
hour earlier, went instead to Malta.
   Abughres told reporters that all pilots of incoming aircraft had
been informed of the problem with the instrument landing system. He
said airport radar, radio beacons and other navigation aids were
all working.
   Libya's chief investigator, Mustapha Maghrebi, said Kim, one of
the 128 survivors, told officials he may have been wrong to attempt
a landing in the fog.
   But Korean Air president Cho Chung-kun told reporters and family
members in Seoul today that the pilot apparently confronted ``an
unexpected situation'' while trying to land. He ruled out pilot
error or mechanical problems.
   Cho did not say what he meant by ``an unexpected situation,''
but Korean Air officials privately indicated the control tower
improperly directed the jet.
   South Korea's Yonhap News Agency quoted an unidentified airline
official as saying, ``The plane was ordered to make a 270-degree
turn by the control tower and crashed at the moment of turning when
it hit an unidentified object.''
   Yonhap also quoted an airline official as saying the crew told
authorities the landing guidance system may have been out of order.
   JANA quoted unidentified sources in Libya's Civil Aviation
Commission as saying the crash was either caused by mechanical or
pilot error. It said the airport provided ``excellent'' aviation
assistance.
   Investigators from South Korea arrived in Libya today to help in
the investigation, and a medical team arrived to help treat with
survivors.
   In Seoul, an aviation expert of the Transportation Ministry said
``each side is trying to say they are not wholly responsible for
the accident.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The jet hit cars and two houses and split into three pieces
before coming to rest about a half-mile from the airport.
   JANA said more than 110 people were hospitalized. Airline
officials in Seoul said 40 people with minor burns were expected to
be released today.
   Most of the passengers on Flight 803 were South Koreans
returning to their jobs on engineering and construction projects in
Libya. Flight 803 originated in Seoul and had made stops in
Bangkok, Thailand, and Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, the airline said.
   In Seoul today, about 100 relatives of crash victims staged a
protest march for two hours on a road leading to Seoul's Kimpo
International Airport.
   Some carried signs calling airline officials ``murderers.''
Others demanded they be allowed to fly to Libya to view the plane.
</TEXT>
