<HEAD>Arkansas Congressman Switches to Republican Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; subs pvs 3rd graf, Robinson became, with
2 grafs to include other House defection this year and party breakdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tommy Robinson of Arkansas, complaining
there is no room for conservative Southerners in the national
Democratic Party, announced today he is switching to the Republican
Party.
   Robinson, a third-term congressman, made the announcement at a
White House briefing where President Bush welcomed him to the GOP
as ``a man of the people'' who believes in a strong defense and
traditional American values.
   Robinson became the third Democratic official in three days to
switch to the Republican Party, and the second House Democrat to
join the GOP this year. Rep. Bill Grant of Florida made the switch
in February.
   Robinson's defection leaves the party lineup in the House at 256
Democrats and 176 Republicans, with three vacancies.
   ``Even after losing five of the last six presidential elections
in the nation and Arkansas, the leadership of the Democratic Party
still is unwilling to listen to the majority of the American
people,'' Robinson said.
   ``... I simply cannot wait any longer for the liberal leadership
of the Democratic Party to see the light,'' he said. ``The hard
fact is that there is and will be no room for conservative Southern
Democrats in today's national Democratic Party.''
   On Thursday, retiring District of Columbia Police Chief Maurice
Turner made a similar announcement. Turner, who is considered a
mayoral prospect for the capital city, was welcomed to the
Republican Party in a meeting with Bush and Lee Atwater, chairman
of the Republican National Committee.
   On Wednesday, Louisiana Secretary of State Fox McKeithen shed
the Democratic affiliation carried for a lifetime by his father,
eight-year former Gov. John McKeithen.
   Bush called the younger McKeithen and told him, ``Yours was a
courageous decision.'' McKeithen, who is considering a bid next
year against Democratic Sen. Bennett Johnston, said his father told
him, ``You must be crazy.''
   A former sheriff, Robinson was elected to the House in 1984 from
Arkansas' 2nd Congressional District. He has a conservative, strong
pro-defense record and serves on the House Armed Services, Veterans
Affairs and Aging committees.
   Robinson's switch brings to 130 the number of party converts at
all levels _ mostly state and local officials _ announced by the
Republicans in their bid to realign the voter registration patterns.
   The number takes in party and elected officials, and some no
longer in office, down to the level of local clerk, alderman, local
committee member and school board member. The RNC did not provide
dates for many of the changes, but the dates that were given were
for this year.
   All the party switchers were from southern states.
   Robinson was in the news earlier this year for giving a
$60,000-a-year job on his congressional staff to the 22-year-old
daughter of his close friend, business partner and financial
backer, Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones.
   Robinson reported owing at least $100,000 to Jones.
   Although not illegal, the hiring of Jones' daughter raised
questions because other Capitol Hill aides at her level _ just out
of college _ earn far less and hold jobs less elevated than her
trio of titles _ administrative assistant, office manager and press
secretary.
</TEXT>
