<FIRST>r a AM-DismembermentSlaying     07-28 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dismemberment Slaying,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett Pleads Guilty In Dismemberment Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man pleaded guilty to second-degree
murder Friday for the slaying and dismemberment of his chess
companion and was immediately sentenced to prison.
   Robert Eugene Bennett, 51, of Klamath Falls, Ore., also waived a
presentence investigation during what was to have been only an
arraignment hearing. Third District Judge James Sawaya sentenced
him to an indeterminate term of five years to life.
   Deputy Salt Lake County Attorney Tom Vuyk said he had been
informed earlier that Bennett intended to plead guilty.
   Defense attorney Andrew Valdez said his client was concerned
about subjecting the family of his victim, Larry Duane White, to
the ordeal of a trial. Valdez said Bennett also wanted to avoid
revelations about his and White's sexual preferences.
   White, 51, disappeared Feb. 21. The next day, his severed legs
were found in a trash bin in suburban Salt Lake. His head and torso
were found May 8, buried at a home once rented by Bennett, who also
is known as Joe King Bennett and Roy William Anderson.
   Bennett occasionally played chess with White, a writer living
with his father in Salt Lake City. Bennett and White were to have
started work at a telemarketing company the week White disappeared.
   Bennett was arrested April 6 in Las Vegas on a federal charge of
falsely applying for a Social Security number.
   Bennett was investigated but never charged in the disappearance
of his wife, Floyd Jeanie Better, 36, in Beaverton, Ore. She was
last seen Feb. 22, 1988. Detectives dug up a piece of property
where they believed she might be buried, but found nothing.
</TEXT>
