<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Predicts Ultimate Victory In Defense Battle with Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Inserts 4th graf, ``I do not ...''; 10th graf, Bush said he
xxx; grafs 14-15, If he had; and 17th graf, ``I'm going to ...''; ^By RITA
BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today deplored votes by the
House of Representatives to cut four major defense systems but
predicted that his view would prevail by the time Congress finishes
work on his military budget.
   At a wide-ranging news conference, Bush adopted a soft-toned
approach to the House's defense bill slashes. But he said Thursday
was ``not the House's most memorable moment.''
   ``But we're going to keep on fighting for what we believe in,''
the president said. He said he would not accept further cuts in the
Star Wars budget to protect his other defense programs.
   ``I do not want to negotiate with the Soviet Union without as
many cards in my hands as possible,'' he added.
   Bush also foresaw ultimate victory in his fight to keep $50
billion of the cost of rescuing the savings and loan industry out
of the budget _ and the deficit. House-Senate conferees voted
Thursday night to reject Bush's plan and make the cost of the
bailout reflected in the deficit and reduce the long-term interest
cost.
   And on a third controversy in Congress, Bush disputed critics
who contend his attempt to amend the Constitution to prevent the
desecration of the American flag will wind up weakening the rights
of all Americans.
   ``We thought about it because you don't want to weaken
anyuthing, but I feel so strongly that a very carefully drawn
amendment can solve this problem that I don't worry about it.''
   He declined to say if he would sign a Democratic bill that would
make the act of destroying the flag illegal but stop short of
making it part of the Constitution. A House committee approved such
a measure Thursday, with bipartisan support even though many
Republicans agreed with Bush that a constitutional amendment is the
proper solution.
   Bush said he felt no ``disrespect'' for members of Congress who
want to go the legislative, rather than the amendment route, to
deal with the flag desecration issue.
   The issue arose when the Supreme Court ruled 5-4 that a Texas
law against flag burning was an unconstititoonal interference with
the rights of free speech.
   Bush called the news conference to ballyhoo the decision by
Arkansas congressman Tommy Robinson to switch parties, from the
Democratic to the Republican fold.
   Robinson, the third Democrat in three days to make the switch,
explained his decision: ``I simply cannot wait any longer for the
liberal leadership of the Democratic Party to see the light.''
   The focus of the news conference was clearly not on Robinson but
on the legislative setbacks that Bush has suffered in the last few
days.
   If he had to rate Congress' record so far, Bush said, ``I
wouldn't give it very high marks.'' He said that just because he
isn't attacking Congress ``in a personal way does not mean I'm
happy with the legislative calendar.'' He said Congress had
discarded his appeal to act on the S&amp;L crisis within 60 days.
   Still, Bush told reporters, ``I think we will prevail for most
of what we want.'' He pointed to the forthcoming defense battle in
the Senate, which he hopes will rescue his defense program.
   The House voted this week to slash spending for the B-2 Stealth
bomber, the Star Wars program, to make the MX missile mobile and to
eliminate all funding for the Midgetman missile.
   ``I'm going to put a lot of emphasis on the Senate and we will
work with people like (House Armed Services Committee) Chairman
(Les) Aspin, who does not want to see the defense bill gutted,''
Bush said.
   ``And I do think we will prevail for most of what we want _ a
strong SDI (Star Wars) program, a strong B-2 (stealth bomber)
program,'' he said.
   On other issues:
   _Bush said he still has confidence in William Lucas, his
embattled nominee to become chief civil rights enforcer in the
Justice Department.
   ``I am convinced that much of the criticism (against Lucas) is
pure gut American politics,'' he said.
   Bush said he was working hard to save the nomination. Critics
say Lucas lacks experience.
   _Bush carefully sidestepped questions about Felix S. Bloch, the
ranking American diplomat suspected of spying for the KGB.
   ``I can't give you the facts on it,'' the president said of the
spy case. ``I don't want to go into it while it is under
investgation.''
   He said he was ``very concerned about premature discussion and
disclosure _ that means leaks _ on this matter, because I think you
can jeopardize the case itself and perhaps the man's ability to get
a fair hearing.''
   _He came down on the side of the Commerce Department in its
decision to allow the export of small personal computers to the
Soviet Union, while acknowledging that Defense Secretary Dick
Cheney had opposed the switch in policy.
   ``We did have a difference inside the administration on this
question,'' Bush said. But he said he was confident that the
Commerce Department stance ``will not endanger the legitimate
national security needs of this country.''
   _Bush also defended his proposal to cut the rate at which
capital gains are taxed. Speaker Tom Foley and other Democratic
leaders have been fighting it.
   Bush hinted he would accept a compromise on that issue, but he
said his plan would stimulate the creation of both jobs and new
small businesses.''
</TEXT>
