<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CapitalGains     07-28 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Capital Gains,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Hints at Compromise on Capital-Gains Taxes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he is willing to
compromise with Congress on his proposal to cut capital-gains taxes
and he repeated his contention that such a reduction would actually
increase revenues.
   ``If there's some compromise that can spur investment, spur
jobs, increase employment _ the cause of new jobs starting up _ I'd
be interested in it,'' Bush told a news conference. ``I don't think
I should ever say it's got to be done just this way in terms of the
bills up there in the House Ways and Means Committee right now.''
   Bush's proposal would cut the 33-percent maximum capital-gains
rate to 15 percent, which would apply to stocks and most other
assets, but not timber and real estate. There is little support for
that proposal among Democrats on the committee.
   However, all 13 committee Republicans and six Democrats _ a
majority of the panel _ are backing a substitute by Rep. Edgar
Jenkins, D-Ga. It would cut the top rate to 20 percent for two
years for assets including timber and real estate, then raise it to
28 percent and protect against taxation of gains that are
attributable solely to inflation.
   Democratic leaders have blocked a vote on that proposal while
they negotiate toward a compromise with the Bush administration.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the committee chairman, told
reporters Friday: ``All we have been doing is discussing but
there's no offer'' of a compromise.
   ``A rate ... (reduction) is absolutely out of the question,'' he
added.
   Under discussion is a plan that, instead of cutting the
capital-gains rate, would prevent taxation of inflation-caused
profits and exempt from taxation an additional 1 percent a year of
asset value.
   Democrats generally oppose a cut in the capital-gains tax rate
because 80 percent of the tax reduction would go to those with
incomes over $100,000 a year. They also insist that while a
reduction would accelerate sales of investment temporarily, after a
year or so a cut in the rate would reduce revenues.
   Bush addressed both points Friday, as he did regularly during
his campaign last year.
   ``I have a good sound proposal. It was tested'' during the
campaign. ``And the other side, particularly the liberal Democrats,
... attacked me as having some kind of tax cut favoring the rich,''
he said. ``It's nothing like that at all.''
   As for causing a long-term revenue loss, he pointed to the
experience of a capital-gains reduction enacted in 1978. ``It's not
a revenue loser,'' he said.
   The Treasury Department predicts Bush's proposed reduction in
the capital-gains tax rate would raise $16.1 billion over five
years but then would lose $20.1 billion over the next three years.
   The staff of the Joint Committee on Taxation estimates that a
total revenue gain of $4 billion in 1989 and 1990, followed by a
string of losses that would total $71 billion through 1999.
</TEXT>
