<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0600 07-28 0778</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0600,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Agrees To Begin Pullout, 74 Killed in Ethnic Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with State Department comment.
Pickup 4th pvs, ``Tamils who ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India decided to resume withdrawing
its peacekeeping troops Friday, on one of the island nation's worst
days of ethnic violence in which state TV reported 74 people were
killed.
   The decision to start pulling out more troops starting Saturday
averted a showdown with Sri Lankan President Ranasinghe Premadasa,
who had called the continued Indian presence a threat to his
nation's independence.
   The Bush administration said it hopes the agreement saves lives.
   ``We welcome this development and hope that India and Sri Lanka
will be successful in reaching an agreement on a timetable for
withdrawal that minimizes bloodshed while recognizing Sri Lanka's
sovereignty and independence,'' said State Department spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler.
   Television in Colombo said most of those who died were killed by
Sri Lankan forces in areas where the Indians are not deployed. Most
died in the Sinhalese heartland, where extremists from Premadasa's
own ethnic community have violently protested government peace
efforts with the Tamil minority and the continued presence of the
Indian troops.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
say they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who account
for 75 percent of the population and control the government and
armed forces.
   India, spurred by its own politically powerful Tamil minority of
60 million, sponsored the July 29, 1987, peace accord designed to
give Tamils some autonomy in northern and eastern Sri Lanka. But
the biggest Tamil guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, reneged on the pact and started attacking the Indians.
   The telecast referred to those who died Friday as
``troublemakers and disruptive elements'' _ terms frequently used
for Sinhalese radicals.
   It said 16 people were killed when they attacked a police
station at Mannikhina near Kandy, about 60 miles northeast of
Colombo.
   Sri Lankan security forces killed 21 more people who defied a
curfew to stage anti-India demonstrations in the Monargala district
about 100 miles east of Colombo, state TV said.
   Five people were killed when they ignored a curfew in the
predominantly Tamil town of Batticaloa, 100 miles northeast of
Colombo, the newscast said.
   The other deaths were scattered throughout central and southern
Sri Lanka.
   Premadasa originally sought the departure of all of India's
45,000 soldiers by Saturday. He announced the decision about an
hour after it was publicized by government spokesmen in Colombo and
New Delhi.
   Neither side indicated how many Indian soldiers would leave, but
only a token force was likely to depart.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne and six other Sri Lankan
officials were to fly to New Delhi to discuss a timetable for the
withdrawal of the rest of the Indian troops.
   Premadasa sought to portray the Indian decision as a victory.
The two-year Indian military presence has fueled Sri Lanka's ethnic
violence among the Tamil guerrillas that the Indians were supposed
to disarm and Sinhalese extremists who denounced the Indian
presence as a violation of Sri Lankan sovereignty.
   ``The protests staged against the continuance of the IPKF
(Indian peace keeping force) in our country can now cease,'' he
said. ``By resorting to strikes and disruptive activities based on
such protests we are causing damage and harm to ourselves. It is
our own people who get killed.''
   Military troops and police were enforcing a nationwide curfew
designed to thwart threatened disruptions by Sinhalese radicals
accused of killing 4,000 people _ mostly Sinhalese government
officials and supporters _ since Indian troops started arriving
July 30, 1987.
   The curfew began Thursday and was to continue until dawn Sunday.
   Another 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
died in the Tamil separatist war that started in 1983.
   Premadasa said the talks in New Delhi were ``to prepare a time
frame, a timetable, for the complete withdrawal of the Indian army
and also to ensure the cessation of offensive military operations
and for reviewing the implementation of the Indo-Sri Lanka accord.''
   The compromise under which India was to resume its troop
withdrawal was signed Friday in Colombo by the Indian High
Commissioner, or ambassador, Lakhan Lal Mehrotra, and by Sri Lankan
foreign Secretary Bernard Tillekeratne.
   In New Delhi, Foreign Ministry spokesman Aftab Seth called the
agreement a ``victory of reason, goodwill and good sense.''
   At the peak of its involvement in Sri Lanka, India's
peacekeeping force numbered at least 70,000. The most recent
withdrawals were in January and February when about 5,000 Indian
soldiers left shortly after Premadasa took office.
</TEXT>
