<FIRST>r a AM-YonkersBudget     07-28 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yonkers Budget,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Comptroller Won't Certify Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state comptroller refused Friday to
certify Yonkers' 1989-90 budget because the City Council refuses to
clearly allocate money for court-ordered school construction in a
desegregation plan.
   The move could send the city into technical default and subject
it to a spending plan imposed by a judge.
   The budget struggle stems from the City Council's long-term
opposition to court-ordered desegregation, a stance that nearly put
the city into bankruptcy last year when a federal judge imposed a
series of fines.
   Spokesman Marvin Nailor said state Comptroller Edward Regan
would not sign off on the $372.3 million budget approved by the
City Council on Thursday because there was no clear inclusion of
$24 million for court-ordered school construction.
   The state Emergency Financial Control Board had refused to
approve an earlier, similar version of the budget because the $24
million had been drawn from the city's surplus and was not in a
fund designating it specifically for the schools.
   A compromise budget, submitted by the control board, utilized
about $12 million of the surplus combined with cuts and other
funding in an account earmarked for the schools, but it was
rejected two weeks ago by the City Council.
   The control board has imposed a wage and hiring freeze on the
city.
   The budget rejected by Regan had the school funding money in an
account called ``Claims and Judgments,'' with no particular
reference or formal allocation to the Board of Education.
   ``The majority of this council is dead set against putting their
fingerprints on anything related to desegregation,'' complained
Mayor Nicholas Wasicsko.
   Without a certified budget, the city would be technically in
default Monday, a situation under which the comptroller is supposed
to ask a state judge to impose a budget.
   City officials have indicated that the comptroller's office
would ask the judge to impose the control board's compromise
budget, which would avert layoffs, maintain service, and allow
leeway for raises.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand had ordered new schools built
as a way of remedying the more than 40 years of segregation he had
found in the city's schools and housing.
   Earlier this week, the city voted to challenge the location for
one of the schools, saying it was parkland.
   Defiance of the housing portion of Sand's plan last summer left
the city on the brink of bankruptcy when fines he imposed escalated
to $1 million a day. On the first day of the $1 million fine, the
city agreed to comply with his housing order.
</TEXT>
