<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Rabbis     07-28 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Rabbis,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rabbis: Israel Forbidden to Withdraw From West Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Orthodox rabbis issued a religious
ruling Friday that said Jewish law forbids Israel from withdrawing
from the occupied West Bank.
   In response, a left-leaning religious legislator accused the
chief rabbinate of interfering in politics and another politician
called for an investigation of the religious body.
   In the one-page ruling published Friday, the rabbis said
``pikuach nefesh,'' a central idea in Judaism that saving life
overshadows other religious commandments, ``obliges us not to
retreat from the borders we hold today.
   ``Withdrawal of the Israeli army may increase the danger of
fatal attacks from the abandoned territory,'' they said.
   Rabbinate spokesman Eitan Aizman said he interpreted the ruling
as saying ``it is a religious commandment to retain the land of
Israel in our hands.''
   Although not binding, their ruling is bound to be influential:
most Israeli Jews are Orthodox. Conservative and Reform Jewry, the
largest groups in the United States, are not represented in the
chief rabbinate.
   Israeli media reports said the ruling was issued in response to
a statement by Israel's former Chief Rabbi Ovadiya Yosef, who told
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak last week that Halacha, or the
body of Jewish religious teaching, justifies a land compromise as a
matter of saving lives.
   The rabbinate said it was ``surprised and sorrowful'' because
Jews could tell a ``non-Jewish ruler: we are obliged by law to hold
on to Judea and Samaria but you are prepared to kill Jews if we
don't withdraw. Therefore, we have to withdraw.''
   The 19-month Palestinian uprising against Israel's 22-year
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip has left more than 560
Palestinians and 36 Israelis dead. Israel fought wars with Arab
countries in 1967 and 1973.
   The chief rabbis' ruling referred only to Judea and Samaria, the
biblical names for the West Bank, and did not mention the occupied
Gaza Strip.
   It was published a day after Israel's Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir made an impassionate speech to leading rabbis in Jerusalem
for retaining all occupied land.
   ``It's possible to reach peace without, heaven forbid, giving up
a grain of the holy land of our forefathers,'' Shamir said. ``Peace
is not a monopoly of the traitors, concession-makers and
defeatists.''
   The chief rabbinate is presided over by Israel's two chief
Orthodox rabbis, Mordechai Eliahu representing Sephardi Jews from
Middle Eastern countries and Avraham Shapiro representing Ashkenasi
Jews from Europe and America.
   Sephardis and Ashkenasis have separate religious traditions.
   The rabbinate has made repeated but unsuccessful efforts to halt
movies and sports events on Saturday, the Jewish sabbath.
   Elazar Granot, a leader of the leftist Mapam party, responded to
Friday's ruling by demanding a government investigation to
determine whether the ruling ``wasn't an explicit and serious
deviation from the (rabbinate's) authority and whether proper
sanctions shouldn't be taken against this deviation.''
   Abraham Burg, a religious legislator from the Labor Party and
the son of a former Interior Minister Yosef Burg, charged that the
Rabbinate ``became part of the political establishment and somehow
lost its spiritual authority, becoming a pawn in the political
game.''
   ``Just as I don't expect the premier to rule about kosher, and
the chief of staff to teach me commandments, I don't expect chief
rabbis to get involved in state affairs,'' Burg told Israel army
radio.
   Burg's left-leaning Labor party advocates trading parts of the
occupied lands for peace. Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc opposes
any territorial compromise.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has officially endorsed a
two-state solution but Islamic groups, another leading force in the
Palestinian uprising, want a Moslem state that would include Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
