<DOCNO> AP890728-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CruseSentence     07-28 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruse Sentence,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shopping Center Gunman Faces Two Death Penalties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge rejected mental-illness pleas
Friday and sentenced a retired librarian to the electric chair for
killing two policemen during a 1987 shopping-center rampage in
which four other people also died.
   William Bryan Cruse also was sentenced to 100 years in prison
without parole on the other four killings and lesser prison terms
on 26 other convictions of attempted murder, kidnapping and false
imprisonment.
   Judge John Antoon called the shooting spree in which 10 people
were wounded in nearby Palm Bay ``perhaps unsurpassed in the state
of Florida.''
   Under mandatory-minimum sentencing regulations, Cruse's total
prison sentence would be 103 years in prison unless he is executed
for the slayings of the two police officers.
   ``We are pleased that William Cruse has been finally sentenced
to death. We feel it is a just punishment for the war Mr. Cruse
declared on Palm Bay two years ago,'' said State Attorney Norm
Wolfinger.
   Assistant Public Defender Marlene Alva, Cruse's chief trial
lawyer, would not comment on the sentences except to say that
``somewhere down the line, someone has to determine competency for
execution.''
   An appeal of the convictions and sentences will be filed soon,
she said.
   Cruse told investigators after his capture, following a
seven-hour siege, that he ``got into trouble'' because everyone
believed he was homosexual. He said he was trying to get even with
people who taunted him and that he was ``drunk and crazy'' during
the shootout.
   Cruse refused an opportunity to address the court Friday, as he
has in the past, but he did appear to wipe away a tear or two while
one of the shooting victims recounted his experiences amidst sobs.
   ``When we entered that battlefield, we did not know whether we
would come out alive,'' said Larry Glynn, 43, as he told the court
how he and a friend, drove more than 15 shooting victims to safety
in their pickup during the shootout.
   ``If you really want to punish Mr. Cruse, let him live,'' Glynn
said.
   The central issue in the case was Cruse's mental state. The
defense pleaded temporary insanity caused by mental illness.
Psychiatric specialists on both sides agreed that Cruse was
mentally ill.
   But the prosecution convinced a jury in April that mental
illness was only one factor involved in a finding of criminal
insanity under Florida law.
   The jury recommended the death penalty on each of the six
first-degree murder counts, but the judge did not have to follow
that recommendation.
   Although rejecting insanity, the judge did accept arguments of
``extreme mental disturbance'' that lessened the penalties in the
slayings of the four civilians.
   He imposed life sentences, without possibility of parole for 25
years, in each of those murders.
   Antoon imposed life terms on each of 22 counts of attempted
first-degree murder and the kidnapping of a store clerk who was
held hostage most of the time Cruse was barricaded inside a
supermarket.
   Antoon also handed down 30-year sentences on each of two counts
of attempted second-degree murder and a 15-year term for false
imprisonment of a second store employee.
   Except for the first-degree-murder sentences, all other prison
terms are to run concurrently, and each carries a mandatory-minimum
of three years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
