<FIRST>r a AM-SovereigntyRecords     07-28 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sovereignty Records,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mississippi Won't Appeal Ruling on Opening Sovereignty Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered that records
of the defunct state Sovereignty Commission _ which tried to thwart
the work of civil rights groups in the 1950s and 1960s _ be opened
to the public.
   ``The state of Mississippi acted directly through its state
Sovereignty Commission and through conspiracy with private
individuals to deprive the plaintiffs of rights protected by the
Constitution to free speech and association, to personal privacy,
and to lawful search and seizure, and statutes of the United
States,'' U.S. District Judge William H. Barbour Jr. ruled Thursday.
   Barbour permanently barred the state from enforcing a law making
it a crime to disclose the records, which have been sealed since
1977. But the judge ruled that the records won't be released
pending a possible appeal.
   Assistant Attorney General Jim Warren said Friday the state
won't appeal. Gov. Ray Mabus said he supported that decision.
   ``We feel that by closing this chapter of Mississippi and
opening the files will allow Mississippi to focus on the future,''
Mabus said.
   The records are held in six file cabinets by the state
Department of Archives and History in a vault in Jackson.
   The commission was created in 1956 and shut down in 1973. The
1977 Legislature ordered the records sealed until 2027. The ACLU
and civil rights activists sued the state the same year to open the
records.
   Barbour noted in his ruling that some records were destroyed or
removed years ago.
   ``A memo in the record establishes that in 1965, the commission
director ordered the destruction of all files which might show
interference by commission agents with voter registration. There
are other gaps which indicate that files have been lost, pilfered
or destroyed,'' Barbour wrote.
   Former Forest Mayor Erle Johnston was commission director from
1963 until 1968.
   ``Regardless of whatever information that was available to Judge
Barbour, we did not destroy files in 1965 or any other year,''
Johnston said.
   Johnston said neither he nor his secretary, who was in charge of
the files, disturbed the files, except for one which concerned
David Bowen, later a five-term congressman.
   ``The short file was actually a subtle criticism of Bowen's
fraternizing with ultra-liberal professors while he was at Millsaps
College,'' he said.
   Most plaintiffs in the lawsuit sought to make the documents
public but two of them, the Rev. Edwin King of Jackson and John
Salter Jr. of Grand Fork, N.D., requested the records remain closed
while an appeal is pursued, American Civil Liberties Union lawyer
Shirley Payne said.
   ``I just feel everybody's privacy was violated by the state in
illegally spying on people and it shouldn't be violated again by
making these records public,'' King said Thursday.
   ``My position is ... that the rights of citizens not to be spied
on or to be manipulated by a secret police is very important. I
don't think people who've been spied upon should have that material
released. The state should never have secured it,'' King said.
   Salter said private or personal information obtained by the
commission illegally should remain closed, but other, general
documents should be open.
   ``We always felt the personal material should be released only
to the victims. The victims would be free to use the material any
way they wish, including bringing damage suits against the state,''
Salter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
