<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Isreal     07-28 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Isreal,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Opposes Israeli Kidnapping of Shiite Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he did not condone
the kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem leader by Israeli commandoes in
Lebanon and doesn't know if the act will lead to freedom for an
American hostage.
   Bush, responding to questions at a news conference, also said he
had not been in touch with the Israelis after their capture of
Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid in the Lebanon village of Jibchit, 21 north
of the Israeli border, earlier in the day.
   Bush was asked whether Obeid's capture enhanced the cause of
peace in the Middle East.
   ``I don't think kidnapping and violence helps the cause of
peace,'' he responded.
   Sources in Lebanon said Obeid is considered Iran's closest ally
and was linked to the abduction of Marine Lt. Col. William R.
Higgins, head of the 75-man observer group attached to the U.N.
Interim Force in Lebanon, on Feb. 17, 1988.
   Higgins is one of nine Americans held in Lebanon, presumably by
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems.
   Bush said he didn't know what ramifications the capture of Obeid
would have.
   ``I can't tell you ... whether I think ... these two things can
interact _ the kidnapping and perhaps the subsequent release of
this man _ whether that'll benefit the Higgins case or not,'' the
president said.
   He did say, however, that ``the freeing of Colonel Higgins is
very much on my mind and the freeing of the other hostages is.''
   Bush said he had not contacted the Israelis, although other
Americans had. ``This thing ... just happened.''
   Obeid is reputed to be the spiritual guide of Hezbollah, or
Party of God, in south Lebanon.
   He has repeatedly denied, however, any ties with the pro-Iranian
group, which is affiliated with factions holding most of the 17
foreign hostages in Lebanon. Nine Americans are among the hostages.
</TEXT>
