<HEAD>WASHN: various ways?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush: I don't think kidnapping and violence helps the cause of
peace.
   Dick?
   Q. Mr. President, recently your secretary of commerce announced
that we would sell computers to the Soviet Union _ we hadn't sold
them before _ which drew a protest from Secretary Cheney. In light
of the Felix Bloch case and the new allegations of possible spying,
do you think it's time to begin relaxing our controls on technology?
   Bush: I don't want to send technology to the Soviet Union that
will enhance their military capabilities.
   And we did have a difference inside the administration on this
question.
   I am confident that, after having looked at it subsequent to
Secretary Mosbacher's decision, that this will not enhance the
technological _ won't _ put it this way _ that this will not
endanger the legitimate national security needs of this country.
   So we're _ we have had a difference on it.
   I've talked to both Cheney and Mosbacher.
   I don't see any connection, however, to the allegations against
Mr. Bloch.
   Yeah, Bernie?
   Q. Sir, how concerned are you that the Bloch case will actually
endanger national security? And can you give us any indication how
long this has been going on?
   Bush: I can't give you the facts on it.
   I don't want to go into it while it is being under investigation.
   I am very disturbed about the premature discussion and
disclosure _ that means ``leaks'' _ on this matter, because I think
you can jeopardize the case itself, and perhaps the man's ability
to get a fair hearing.
   So I am troubled by it, but I can't really help you on the facts
on the matter.
   Yes, Frank?
   Q. I'd like to continue with this kinder, gentler theme for a
moment. You've tried this with Congress for the entire six months
you've been in office, yet your crime bill has failed, your defense
bill appears to have been savaged, your nominee for civil rights
post, whom you say is qualified, is being given a rough ride, to
say the least, and the S&amp;L bill, you have great concerns about. How
would you rate your own legislative success in your first six
months?
   Bush: I'd be rating the Congress, wouldn't I, if I rated the
legislative success, and I wouldn't give it very high marks.
   I sent a savings and loan bill up there, and it's been there for
_ (aside) _ how many days?
   Staff: Since February 23rd.
   Bush: Since February 23rd.
   And I challenged the Congress to get something done in 60 days,
and it wasn't done.
   So in not going after people in a very personal way, attacking
some congressman or senator with whom I differ, that does not mean
I am happy or relaxed about the legislative calendar and the
performance on legislation.
   I am concerned about it.
   Every day the savings and loan sits out there unsolved _ it's
costing the American taxpayer 30 _ some estimates go from $10
(million) to $30 million a day.
   And if the fault _ I'll take the fault, the responsibility, when
we're slow getting legislation up; we've been criticized, and I
think properly so, from on a couple of subjects _ not getting the
legislation there on time.
   But on this one, I think the Congress has been taking too long
to resolve the matter.
   And there are others.
   The defense budget's not a question of timing so much as it is
the mix on our strategic system.
   So I would not give Congress very high marks on doing what I
want done on legislation.
   In giving it _ putting their spin on it, why that's something
else.
