<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1703EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     07-28 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burmese Authorities Release Convicts, Arrest Political Activists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government said it
freed thousands of criminals this week, but diplomats said
authorities also have arrested hundreds of political activists.
   The government also has sentenced to death three opposition
party members for a bombing at an oil refinery.
   Radio Rangoon reported Wednesday that 1,187 criminals were freed
nationwide that day, bringing to 5,131 the number released under an
amnesty announced July 20.
   The amnesty commuted death sentences to life imprisonment,
reduced life terms to 10 years and cut other terms cut by
two-thirds.
   But the amnesty applied only to cases before Sept. 18, 1988, and
not to cases of high treason or breaches of martial law imposed
since that date.
   On Sept. 18, the army under Gen. Saw Maung moved to crush a
nationwide mass movement for democracy, killing hundreds of people,
mostly unarmed protesters. He declared martial law that severely
curtailed public gatherings and freedom of speech.
   On July 18, the eve of a planned mass opposition rally, the
government tightened martial law and threatened offenders with
death sentences.
   Two days later, Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, the leaders of the
National League for Democracy, were placed under house arrest. The
government charged they had attempted ``to destroy the military and
create anarchy in the country.''
   On Thursday, a military tribunal sentenced to death three
members of their party who allegedly confessed they were
responsible for a package bomb that exploded and killed two people
at the country's main oil refinery on July 7.
   No details of the trial of Than Zaw, 27, Moe Kyaw Thus, 17, and
Nyi Nyi Oo, 25, were made public.
   Dissidents and Western diplomats in Rangoon said authorities
have arrested up to hundreds of dissidents since putting the two
opposition leaders under house arrest.
   ``They are going to people's houses at night, they are pulling
them off the streets, even off of buses or out of offices and
hotels,'' one diplomat said in a telephone interview from Bangkok.
   British officials say the Burmese government also has restricted
the movements of Ms. Suu Kyi's British husband, Michael Aris. He
had returned to Rangoon from Britain on Saturday last week.
   At a government news conference Friday, Foreign Minister Ohn
Kyaw denied rumors that Ms. Suu Kyi had begun a hunger strike to
protest her detention.
   He said both opposition leaders ``are in good health in their
respective houses.''
   Before her arrest, Ms. Suu Kyi said the suspects in the oil
refinery bombing were members of her party, but she had seen no
evidence that implicated them.
   Diplomats in Rangoon said Thursday they were baffled by the mass
release of criminals but speculated that the jails were being
cleared to make way for political prisoners.
   The government also released thousands of criminals during last
year's protests in a move diplomats said was designed to convince
the people that they needed a tough army presence.
   Saw Maung has sought to justify his rule by saying the country
was facing anarchy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
