<HEAD>WASHN: something else.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. Do you think this is just harbinger of things to come _ a
Republican president working with a Democratic Congress _ converts
notwithstanding?
   Bush: Nobody ever said it would be easy.
   Yeah.
   Q. Mr. President _
   Bush: In this department.
   Q. _ on a related matter, there are some fairly intense
negotiations on your capital gains tax cut proposal going on right
now. Are you willing to accept some kind of an indexing of capital
gains rather than the cut you've asked for as an alternate that
might be more acceptable to Democrats?
   Bush: Look, what I want to do is see capital income at different
rates.
   I want what's known as the ``differential.''
   And so let's see what can be worked out.
   If there's some compromise that can spur investment, spur jobs,
increase employment, the cause of new jobs starting up, I'd be
interested in it.
   And so I want to see what could be worked out.
   I don't think I should ever say it's got to be done just this
way in terms of the bills up there in the House Ways and Means
Committee right now.
   But I have a good, sound proposal, and it was tested _ it was
one of the things, I think, that was clearly in focus in the
campaign.
   And the other side, particularly the liberal Democrats,
particularly, attacked me as having some kind of a tax favoring the
rich.
   It's nothing like that at all.
   It will stimulate jobs.
   It will encourage business _ small business creation.
   And I stand for it.
   And if there's some way that that can be achieved by changing
the proposal I sent up there, fine, I'm willing to listen.
   Q. Is there a compromise in the works?
   Bush: Well, there's been some discussions _ and I can't tell you
how far along it is _ but there has been some discussion.
   I want to see something happen.
   I don't want to fall on my sword.
   I want to see this country have more job creation, and that
would be a part of this.
   And I want to see us get on with the job of balancing this
budget eventually.
</TEXT>
