<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1822EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Motorola     07-28 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Motorola,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hitachi Drops Suit Against Motorola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hitachi Ltd. has dropped a patent infringement suit
filed against the U.S. electronics firm Motorola Inc., a Hitachi
spokesman said Friday.
   Hitachi spokesman Yoichi Suga said the company withdrew the suit
because of new information that suggested ``what we thought had
been under the scope of the patent was not.''
   Motorola said: ``Hitachi's action removes all doubt that Hitachi
now admits the invalidity of the Hitachi patents.''
   The lawsuit filed in U.S. district court in Austin, Texas, in
May alleged that Motorola's 68HC11 microcontroller infringed on a
Hitachi patent.
   Hitachi initiated the suit a week after Motorola filed a
litigation alleging Hitachi microprocessors violated at least four
Motorola patents.
   Their disputes center on patents for digital electronic devices
that perform control and arithmetic functions in televisions,
watches, videotape recorders and other products. They often contain
hundreds of thousands of microscopic transistors on silicon chips
smaller than a fingernail.
   Motorola says it granted patent licenses concerning use of
microprocessing technology to Hitachi over a 10-year period.
   Problems started when Hitachi introduced its Zero Turn-Around
Time microprocessors in 1986, which Motorola claims use technology
not covered in their agreements.
   In its statement, the U.S. company indicated its intention to
continue its suit against Hitachi, which goes to trial Oct. 23.
Motorola is seeking an injunction against continued sales of
Hitachi H-8 and H-16 processors in the United States as well as
damages.
   ``We intend to use all available resources to protect our
design, intellectual property and technology investments,'' Steve
Marsh, marketing director of Motorola's Microcontroller Division,
said.
</TEXT>
