<FIRST>r a AM-DefenseProbe     07-28 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consultant Given 27-Month Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense consultant was sentenced to 27
months in prison Friday for his role in a scheme to bribe a Navy
engineer for confidential bid information about Pentagon contracts.
   Fred H. Lackner, 52, was also fined $25,000 by U.S. District
Judge Claude Hilton and ordered to serve a three-year term of
supervised probation following his release from prison.
   Lackner, of Woodland Hills, Calif., was sentenced on his March
31 guilty plea to conspiracy, bribery and wire fraud, admitting his
role in a scheme to bribe Navy engineer Stuart Berlin.
   Lackner could have received a 25-year prison term and been fined
up to $750,000.
   He testified at the April trial of two Teledyne Electronics Inc.
vice presidents that he had been a middleman between defense
consultant William Parkin and Berlin to obtain inside bid
information from the Navy.
   Lackner testified that he, Parkin, Berlin and another
co-conspirator were to share $150,000 that Teledyne paid Parkin for
help in getting an electronics contract. But Berlin was actually
told the four were sharing $100,000 because ``everyone felt he
really didn't do anything to aid the procurement.''
   Parkin and Berlin were each sentenced to 26 months in prison and
fined $25,000 for their roles in the bribery scheme.
   Parkin and Berlin also testified at the trial of George H. Kaub
and Eugene R. Sullivan, the two Teledyne executives who were
convicted of conspiracy and wire fraud. A third Teledyne executive
was acquitted.
</TEXT>
