<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-28 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Agrees to Questioning Ordered by Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading opposition legislator said
Friday he will comply with a court order that he testify on a
secret visit to North Korea by one of his party's lawmakers, news
reports said.
   Kim Dae-jung, president of the Party for Peace and Democracy,
said the warrant was based on charges ``fabricated by the national
intelligence agency,'' but said he has no choice but to comply,
said reports.
   Also Friday, newspapers reported that Im Su-kyong, a radical
student illegally visiting North Korea, has started a hunger strike
at the border village of Panmunjom.
   Ms. Im arrived at the border Thursday with pacifists from a
reported 30 countries and is demanding that she re-enter the south
through the demilitarized border zone as a gesture of national
unification.
   The government says she will be arrested on her return and
charged with violating national security.
   In Seoul, the Agency for National Security Planning said
Thursday it will serve Kim with a warrant for questioning about an
illegal trip to North Korea by National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won.
Suh is in jail on charges of espionage for visiting the north and
allegedly taking $120,000 from communist agents.
   Yonhap, South Korean's official news agency, said Kim told
reporters Friday in the provincial capital of Kwangju that the
court order is called a writ of detention.
   ``Detention means taking a person against his will,'' he said.
``I have no choice.''
   The order is bound to create more tensions between the
government and the leading opposition party and to bewilder further
South Koreans already shocked by the illegal trips of Suh, Ms. Im,
and a dissident clergyman.
   Unauthorized travel to the communist north is a crime, and many
South Koreans who fought the northern invasion 1950-53 remain
highly sensitive to suggestions a political leader may have
communist sympathies.
   Kim has charged the government with harassment and his party
Thursday filed a libel suit charging intelligence agency chief Suh
Dong-kwon and two investigators purposely spread unfounded rumors.
Kim has turned down three summons for questioning from the
intelligence agency, arguing he knew nothing about Suh's trip.
   Suh was expelled from the party after his June 28 arrest.
   About 200 lawmakers and party officers staged a sit-in Wednesday
at their headquarters after Korean newspapers claimed an
unidentified intelligence agent said Kim was suspected of writing a
letter to North Korean leader Kim Il Sung.
   ``The Roh Tae-woo regime has tried everything it can to destroy
and wipe out the party by taking advantage of the Suh Kyung-won
case,'' the opposition leader said Friday.
   ``We have fought to establish a foundation for democratization
in this country. We will not surrender to the politics of a
security agency.''
</TEXT>
