<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel Bjt   07-28 0875</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel, Bjt,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT ^Helicopter-Borne Israeli Commandos Kidnap Moslem Clergyman</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIBCHIT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli commandos on Friday kidnapped a
Shiite Moslem clergyman reputed to be a leader of the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah and allegedly linked to the kidnapping of a U.S. Marine
held hostage in Lebanon.
   Security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, suggested
Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid may have been kidnapped in a swap for the
American, Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, or for three Israeli
soldiers captured in south Lebanon more than three years ago.
   President Bush said he did not know if the incident would help
Higgins or the other eight American hostages but added, ``I don't
think kidnapping and violence helps the cause of peace'' in the
Middle East.
   The Israeli army confirmed the incident and accused Obeid, 33,
of instigating attacks on Israel and of being a major Hezbollah
figure.
   An Israel army spokesman, Col. Raanan Gissin, indicated a swap
was possible. ``Clearly when you capture one of their (Hezbollah's)
top leaders, it can deter terrorism and you also have a certain
amount of leverage in your hands,'' he said.
   Gissin said Obeid and two ``assistants'' seized with him were
``safely in Israeli hands and undergoing questioning.''
   Killed in the overnight raid was at least one resident of the
village of Jibchit, about 20 miles from the Israeli border and 35
miles south of Beirut.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the United
States was not consulted about or involved in the abduction.
   Lebanese police said the commandos entered Jibchit about 1:30
a.m. after landing in a helicopter outside town.
   A police official, speaking on condition of anonymity in line
with standing regulations, said about 12 commandos with
silencer-equipped pistols surrounded Obeid's building, then knocked
on the door of his apartment and forced their way in.
   They fled with Obeid; his cousin, Ahmed Obeid; and a friend,
Majid Fahs, the spokesman said.
   Obdeid's wife, Mona, was locked in a room with her hands tied
and her mouth taped shut, the spokesman said.
   Mrs. Obeid, interviewed later, said one of the attackers spoke
Arabic. ``He told me he would kill me if I yelled,'' she said.
   The Israeli military refused to give details of the raid, but
Israel television reported the commandos blew offthe front door of
Obeid's apartment with plastic explosives and whisked the three men
away in a helicopter in less than a half-hour.
   Lebanese police said a neighbor, Hussein Abu Zeid, opened the
door of his apartment to find out what was happening and was shot
to death. Israel radio said the man killed was a bodyguard for
Obeid.
   Another neighbor, Fayez Shokor, who lives across the street from
Obeid, said three helicopters were involved in the operation.
   ``I heard a suspicious noise... and went out to the balcony. I
heard someone shouting (in Arabic) `Kill me! I won't go with
you!''' said Shokor, a member of the mainstream Amal militia, which
has been fighting Hezbollah for control of Lebanon's Shiite Moslems.
   Shokor said he and five other Amal militiamen rushed to a nearby
valley in search of Obeid but came under Israeli fire.
   ``Two Israeli helicopters hovered overhead and they started
shooting at us with machine guns,'' he said. ``As the clash was
under way, a third helicopter took off, apparently carrying the
Israelis, Sheik Obeid and his companions.''
   Iran's Foreign Ministry said in a statement: ``This shameless
act by the Zionist regime will not remain unanswered by the Moslem
and combatant forces.'' The statement, carried by the official
Islamic Republic News Agency, said the operation was a ``clear
example of state terrorism.''
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, urged Moslems to
``let out their anger until Obeid is released safely.''
   Obeid is reputed to be the spiritual guide of Hezbollah in south
Lebanon. He has denied involvement with the fundamentalist group,
believed to be an umbrella for the kidnappers of 17 foreign
hostages in Lebanon.
   Higgins, 44, of Danville, Ky., headed an observer group attached
to the U.N. peacekeeping force in South Lebanon. Security sources
said he was briefly held at Obeid's apartment after his abduction
near the southern port city of Tyre on Feb. 17, 1988.
   His captors, the Organization of the Oppressed on Earth,
believed to be one of Hezbollah's affiliates, later took Higgins to
another hideout.
   The State Department and Israel described Obeid as a Hezbollah
member.
   Britain, which has three citizens held hostage in Lebanon, said
the raid could hurt the hostages, but Gissin said it would help
them.
   ``We believe Hezbollah leaders will now think twice before
harming their hostages,'' he said.
   Two Israeli soldiers, Rahamim Alsheikh and Yossi Fink were
captured Feb. 17, 1986, when guerrillas ambushed their patrol in
Israel's self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
Israeli officials said they believe Hezbollah was behind the
kidnapping.
   An air force navigator, Ron Arad, was captured by Shiite
militiamen on October 16, 1986, when his plane was shot down in
south Lebanon.
   The American held longest in Lebanon is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985. A Shiite Moslem group, the pro-Iranian
Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, claims to hold him.
</TEXT>
