<FIRST>r a AM-SovietHelp     07-28 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Help,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Ship Turns Fleeing Cubans Over to US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet ship on Friday turned over to amazed Coast
Guard officials three sunburned Cubans fleeing their communist
homeland on a flimsy raft.
   ``This is a first for us,'' said Coast Guard spokesman Luis
Diaz. ``It went very well. We had no trouble with the exchange.
This is not a common occurrence, and we were very happy to take the
men.''
   The three refugees were badly sunburned, dehydrated and had
difficulty talking and walking after their six-day, 125-mile voyage
that relied on Atlantic currents to push them to Florida.
   ``They are safely being attended by paramedics and glad to be
free,'' Diaz said as the men were brought ashore. All three were
taken to Jackson Memorial Hospital and still were being evaluated
at mid-afternoon.
   Coast Guard Petty Officer Veronica Cady could not explain why
the Soviets would surrender the Cubans instead of taking them home.
   The Soviet ship, identified in the reference book Jane's
Fighting Ships as an intelligence-gathering Zaporozhye, spotted the
three floating in a raft made of inner tubes and picked them up
Friday morning, 26 miles southeast of Cape Florida, the Coast Guard
said.
   ``The negotiations were very short and brief,'' Diaz said. ``We
were notified by the Soviet warship that they had picked up the
three men ... and they wanted to transfer them over to us.''
   When the 274-foot Soviet ship rendezvoused with a 41-foot Coast
Guard patrol boat for the transfer, the Soviet captain refused to
allow a Coast Guard party to board. The Cubans were transferred by
raft to the patrol boat for their trip to Miami.
   So far this year, the Coast Guard has picked up 97 Cubans on
rafts, including 31 this month alone.
   The refugees identified themselves as Arsenio Gomez Hernandez,
46, his son Pedro Gomez Cruz and a man who said he was 47 and gave
the name Gomez.
   Cuban refugees who make the raft trip to Florida are routinely
transferred to the custody of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service and released to relatives after questioning.
   The ship, the Soviet's first with on-board intelligence
capability, has been operating for several months off Cape
Canaveral on intelligence collection operations, said U.S. Navy Lt.
Cmdr. Steve Burnett, Atlantic fleet spokesman in Norfolk, Va.
   Heading in the opposite direction Thursday, two Cuban lobstermen
accused of smuggling Cubans to the Florida Keys were escorted back
to their island nation.
   The Coast Guard cutter Seahawk escorted the Sigma VII and the
two fishermen to international waters where they were met by a
Cuban gunboat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
