<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus     07-28 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Cypriot Authorities Free Eight Greek Cypriots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish Cypriot authorities on Friday
freed eight Greek Cypriot men detained for nine days after they
protested in the U.N.-policed buffer zone splitting this
Mediterranean island.
   The last two people among 108 arrested during the demonstration,
Greek Orthodox Bishop Chrysostomos of Larnaca and Father Giorgios
Papachrysostomou, remained jailed in the northern Turkish-occupied
sector after refusing to pay fines.
   The detentions have triggered a political crisis that has
aggravated sectarian tensions and delayed a round of reunification
talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot leaders.
   The 10 men were arrested July 19 with 98 women when Turkish
Cypriot riot police and soldiers burst into a church the protesters
were occupying on the Green Line dividing Cyprus.
   The women, who staged the demonstration to mark the 15th
anniversary of a Turkish invasion in 1974, have been released.
   The eight men freed on Friday were taken from a jail in the
Turkish-held zone and driven to the village of Astromeritis, 12
miles west of Nicosia, where they were handed over to United
Nations soldiers.
   The men, unshaven and several wearing torn shirts, linked arms
and sang a Byzantine hymn and the Greek national anthem as
relatives crowded around them.
   ``We were horribly treated at first ... beaten and threatened. I
was made to stand on one leg, blindfolded, while they questioned
me,'' said Dr. Andreas Constantinides, a surgeon who was providing
medical aid for the protesters.
   Parliament Speaker Vassos Lyssarides, standing in for President
George Vassiliou, who was on a visit to Greece, welcomed them on
behalf of the government.
   The protesters were sentenced on Saturday last week to three
days in jail on charges of entering the self-proclaimed republic of
northern Cyprus without permission and through an illegal gateway.
   The eight men released Friday were detained an additional five
days after they refused to pay a fine of $100 each. The bishop and
priest were expected to remain in jail until Thursday of next week
because they refused to pay $200 each in fines. None of the women
was fined.
   The Turkish Cypriots arrested the protesters even though they
were inside the Green Line area because they said the zone, even if
demilitarized, was still part of the breakaway state. The buffer
zone recently was expanded to include the church when Greek and
Turkish Cypriot forces agreed to pull back a bit in certain areas
of Nicosia as a confidence-building measure.
   Vassiliou said he was willing to go to reunifications talks set
for Wednesday, but the talks were called off when Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash decided not to attend. The closed-door session
was to be held at the home of U.N. Special Representative Oscar
Camilion.
   The negotiations on a U.N. blueprint for reuniting the island as
a two-zone federation are expected to resume next week, but no date
has been set.
   Greek Cypriots staged marches and demonstrations in Nicosia to
press for the detainees' release. Women protesters were holding a
sit-in that blocked the main entrance to the U.N. Peacekeeping
Force's headquarters in the buffer zone.
   Cyprus has been divided since the Turks seized the northern
third of the island after a short-lived coup by supporters of union
with Greece. The Turkish Cypriots, who make up about 17 percent of
the population declared their own republic in 1983, but only Turkey
recognizes it.
   The U.N. peacekeepers have been in Cyprus since sectarian
fighting erupted in 1963. The 2,300-man force now patrols the
112-mile buffer zone known as the Green Line that zigzags across
the island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0143 </DOCNO>
