<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru a0614 07-28 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0614,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Central Committee Meets To Define Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 4 grafs to ADD report congress to open a
day earlier and separate meeting of reformist Communists, speculation of
possible party split, Central Committee secretary saying 1,300 delegates
to attend main congress. Picks up 4th graf pvs: ``The choice ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD> With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders met Friday to
discuss plans for a fall congress to unite their divided ranks and
find attractive policies to win back waning support before
competitive elections next year.
   The meeting comes three days after party general secretary
Karoly Grosz and chairman Rezsoe Nyers, two of four members running
the party until the congress, held talks in Moscow on Hungary's
future.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev appeared to endorse
Hungary's move to a multiparty system, telling the Hungarians that
socialist nations are searching for ways to create ``a society of
free people, masters of their lives and countries.''
   Hungary's MTI news agency said the party's Central Committee
convened Friday, and added that the congress would open Oct. 6 _ a
day earlier than scheduled _ to accommodate a large number of
speakers. It did not specify the duration of the meeting.
   State TV reported that the Reform Circles, a network of
reform-oriented party members, would hold a separate national
congress Sept. 1-3.
   There has been speculation over the possibility of a split
within the party, but reformists have so far sought to maneuver
within the organization.
   MTI quoted Central Committee Secretary Jenoe Kovacs as saying
there would be 1,300 delegates to the congress.
   The choice of delegates, due Aug. 25, is considered crucial to
the program and new leadership the congress is to endorse to try to
boost the party's waning popularity ahead of multiparty elections.
They will be Hungary's first free general elections since 1947.
   The Budapest meeting comes as Poland's Communist Party Central
Committee holds crucial talks to decide its future after a similar
experiment led to devastating election defeats. Poles
overwhelmingly supported independent Solidarity-led candidates.
   MTI also reported that negotiations for a timetable and
framework for Hungarian elections encountered setbacks Thursday.
   The party and democratic opposition failed to agree on how to
divide the property of the Communist Party and arrange financial
support for competing parties.
   MTI said the party insisted at closed-door talks that its
extensive property does not belong to the people, as the opposition
argued.
   The opposition wants a moratorium on sales of party property
after the communists recently sold some buildings, and suggested it
be divided up so the party enjoy no unfair financial or
organizational advantages going into the elections.
   Hungarian opposition activists have complained that, in a
state-run economy, it is hard for them to find property and install
such basic necessities as telephone lines to enable them to compete
with the communists.
   The two sides also split over whether or not parties should
operate at workplaces, as the communists have done in the past, MTI
said.
   No date was announced for the next negotiations. The slow-moving
talks have yet to bring agreement on key points such as an election
date and access to the media.
   The daily newspaper Magyar Nemzet quoted unidentified sources as
saying the absence of Imre Pozsgay, the Communist Party's leading
reformer and a member of the four-man leadership, was ``palpably
felt'' at Thursday's talks. Pozsgay is on vacation, the daily said.
   In his absence, a more conservative member of the party
negotiating team, Gyoergy Fejti, tried to renege on previous
agreements, it reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
