<FIRST>r a AM-DeputyReturns     07-28 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deputy Returns,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Back at Work After Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy returned to work Friday, 10
hours after being shot in the back of the head when he tried to
stop a robbery _ when he wasn't even on duty.
   ``Somebody upstairs liked me; that's the only thing I can
figure,'' said Wyandotte County Deputy John Poke, 37, who was
wearing a gauze bandage around his head.
   The bullet entered Poke's head behind his left ear and went out
behind his left eye. Three pieces of fragment were left in his
temple. Poke spent just 90 minutes at the hospital.
   Police said four men apparently were involved in the holdup, but
no one was in custody Friday.
   Poke was off-duty when he drove by a grocery store late Thursday
and saw a man pointing a gun at the manager and forcing him toward
the store's safe.
   Poke said he pulled into the parking lot and pulled out his gun
as he walked toward a phone booth. The next thing he knew, someone
behind him was telling him to drop the gun.
   ``I saw a light flash. Then I felt a heat sensation from the
left side of my head,'' he said.
   Poke said the man fired four or five more shots and he fired one
shot at the assailant.
   ``I had blood in my eye, so his face was blurry,'' Poke said.
``When I got my bearings, it was like they disappeared into thin
air.''
   Poke estimated the gunman was no more than six feet away when he
shot the deputy. He said he could not figure out how most of the
gunfire missed him.
   Poke waved down a Board of Public Utilities employee, who called
the police. The thieves fled with no money. The store manager was
not injured.
</TEXT>
