<FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     07-28 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat People,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government to Investigate Reported Police Brutality Toward Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday promised a thorough
investigation of a report from the main U.N. refugee organization
alleging police brutality toward detained Vietnamese seeking asylum.
   Neither the government nor the United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees would disclose details of the report. U.N. officials
have said previously, however, that it would focus on a disturbance
at a detention center in which more than 100 Vietnamese boat people
were injured.
   Authorities say the violence at the Sek Kong enter began Sunday,
when some of the Vietnamese detained there hurled stones at police
guards trying to prevent escapes through holes cut in fencing
around the camp. The unrest flared again several hours later.
   The camp holds 7,000 of the 50,000 Vietnamese languishing in
this British colony after fleeing their communist homeland by boat.
    Police said only four Vietnamese requested treatment for
injuries after the incident, including three who said they were
hurt accidentally.
   The U.N. report also was expected to contain allegations of
previous incidents of police violence at Sek Kong and other
detention centers.
   In response to the report, a government statement said officials
were taking the complaints ``very seriously and all allegations
against the government staff concerned will be fully and swiftly
investigated.''
   Police already are investigating the case of a 59-year-old
Vietnamese man who died the night of the Sek Kong disturbance. An
autopsy showed the man did not die of natural causes, but no
details have been released.
   The Vietnamese at Sek Kong are among the boat people who must
prove they fled political persecution or face repatriation.
   Local news media have reported growing tension in the detention
centers amid signs that Britain and Vietnam are near agreement on a
program of forcefully repatriating boat people who do not qualify
as refugees.
</TEXT>
