<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;Ls     07-28 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Confident of Winning S&amp;L Fight With Democrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he felt confident
Senate Republicans would block Democrats from adding the
multibillion-dollar cost of the savings and loan bailout to the
budget deficit.
   House and Senate negotiators reached agreement late Thursday on
landmark legislation that would cost $166 billion over 10 years to
close and rescue hundreds of failed S&amp;Ls, sweepingly overhaul the
regulatory bureaucracy and impose tough new financial standards on
the industry.
   However, Bush wants to keep $50 billion of the spending out of
the budget deficit in the next three years. He objects to the
Democratic plan which would balloon the reported deficit, while at
the same time waiving the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law to
avoid automatic spending cuts.
   The package next goes to the full House, where a vote is
expected Wednesday or Thursday, and then to the full Senate before
Congress recesses Aug. 5 for vacation.
   Senate rules permit 41 senators to block any waiver of the
Gramm-Rudman law and Bush predicted at a news conference his
position would prevail.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, chief sponsor of the deficit-cutting
law, has already collected signatures from 40 other Republicans
vowing to support the president on the issue.
   ``It won't come to vetoing ... because we have forty-plus votes
in the Senate that, staying firm, will see our proposal prevail,''
Bush said. ``The House, as you know, has disagreed with us, but I'm
confident that we will do all right on that one.''
   Gramm, at a separate news conference, said the Democratic plan,
by waiving Gramm-Rudman, would destroy the spending discipline
imposed by the law.
   ``The problem with this sham is that next week we could do the
same thing for the nuclear cleanup ... education ... the war on
drugs ... and pretty soon we would have a balanced budget where the
deficit was $300 billion or $400 billion,'' he said.
   ``Unless God palsies my voice I intend stand up and raise a
budget point of order under the Gramm-Rudman law against this $50
billion increase in the budget deficit,'' he said.
   Democrats, however, argue that their plan will reduce the cost
of borrowing S&amp;L money. They say both plans evade Gramm-Rudman, but
theirs has the virtue of more honestly accounting for the spending.
   ``The bill provides funding on-budget, a provision that will
ensure ... that the facts about the cost will be laid clearly
before the American people,'' said Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,
chairman of the House Banking Committee.
   He said Gramm, by holding up money badly needed to rescue failed
S&amp;Ls, risks political damage in Texas, where about half the
industry's losses are concentrated.
   ``If Mr. Gramm or I or anyone else were seen as obstructionist,
we would have to face public indignation,'' Gonzalez told a third
news conference.
   His Senate counterpart, Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.,
noted at the same briefing that S&amp;L losses are accumulating at $20
million a day and urged Gramm and Bush not stand in the way of
swift resolution of the crisis.
   He argued that Bush, except for the financing mechanism,
received virtually everything else he requested when he first
outlined the administration's proposal six months ago.
   ``We ought not to get tangled up in parliamentary maneuvers at
this point. ... I would hope the administration would take a very
close look at what we have done here. We've given President Bush
his plan in every essential detail,'' Riegle said.
   Gramm, however, said Democrats, not Republicans, are delaying
the legislation. He said he warned in early June he would block
their funding plan on the Senate floor but they adopted it anyway.
   ``Quite frankly we are engaged in a game of chicken. It was not
a game I sought,'' he said.
</TEXT>
