<FIRST>r i AM-Ethipia-Carter     07-28 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethipia-Carter,0389</SECOND>
<UNK>Carter Confident of Ethiopian Peace Initiative</UNK>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter said
Friday he is confident peace talks between the Ethiopian government
and Eritrean rebels can bring an end to the civil war.
   Carter came to Zimbabwe from Ethiopia and said Ethiopian
President Mengistu Haile Mariam's Marxist government and the
Eritrean People's Liberation Front have agreed to set up
negotiating committees to discuss their differences.
   The front has been fighting for 28 years for autonomy in the
northern province of Eritrea.
   ``I think there is a better prospect now to end ... war than
there has ever been since the war began,'' Carter told reporters in
Harare.
   He said more than a million people have been killed in the
warfare.
   ``Both sides are now willing to try and bring about a resolution
of the conflict through direct talks,'' Carter said. ``We have been
doing everything we can to orchestrate direct talks between
President Mengistu and the Eritrean liberation forces.''
   He said Mengistu accepted an offer by the Atlanta-based Carter
Center to help bring the warring sides to the negotiating table.
   ``Any specific announcements will have to come from the parties
in the conflict,'' he said.
   Carter said that during the July 24-26 summit of the
Organization of Africn Unity in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, he met with
Sudanese military leader Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan El-Bashir and
discussed possible peace talks to end Sudan's 6-year-old civil war.
   ``I was encouraged by his commitment to the peace process,''
Carter said.
   He also said experts in mediation and arbitration supported by
the Carter Center were in contact with the rebels' Sudan People's
Liberation Army.
   ``We have been and will remain in touch with the leaders of both
sides,'' he added.
   Most of the rebels in southern Sudan are Christians or animists
and accuse the Moslem majority that controls the country of
discrimination.
   Carter announced earlier in Harare the establishement of a
non-government aid program called Project Africa to assist African
nations in agricultural development.
   He said the program will deal primarily with food security
strategies and ways of providing low-cost basic tecnology for
African farmers.
   Carter is to leave Harare Saturday and visit Zambia, Nigeria and
Ghana before returning to the United States.
</TEXT>
