<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Letter     07-28 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Letter,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letter From Gorbachev Critic Assails Reformers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denunciations of Josef Stalin and other Soviet
leaders are a prelude to open attacks on Lenin and the Bolshevik
Revolution itself, a critic of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev says
in a letter published in a magazine.
   The letter from Nina Andreyeva, a 51-year-old Leningrad
chemistry teacher, also said political reforms initiated by
Gorbachev are being used for personal gains by opponents of the
Communist Party.
   Her letter was published in the July issue of the conservative
monthly Young Guard.
   She said attacks on Stalin and other Soviet leaders ``are only a
screen to camouflage a gathering of forces for the beginning
attacks on Lenin, Marxism-Leninism, the October Revolution and the
victory of the U.S.S.R. in the Great Patriotic War (World War II).''
   ``It is hard for many people to see where the plurality of
opinion ends and open jeering at everything sacred begins,'' she
said.
   Since Gorbachev initiated a policy of glasnost, or openness,
after coming to power in 1985, figures such as dictator Josef
Stalin and the corrupt Leonid I. Brezhnev have been denounced
publicly.
   In March 1988, a letter from Mrs. Andreyeva defending Stalin was
published by the newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya, setting off a storm
of controversy and worrying liberals that glasnost might be ending.
   Some Soviet observers said that letter was sponsored by
conservative Politburo member Yegor Ligachev. Ligachev, who remains
on the Politburo but has since slipped from his No. 2 position,
also has complained that glasnost goes too far in uncovering past
mistakes and failing to praise past achievements.
   A month later, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda castigated
Sovietskaya Rossiya for printing the letter, and the reprimanded
newspaper admitted it had been irresponsible.
   In her latest letter, Mrs. Andreyeva questions Gorbachev's
program of perestroika, or reconstruction, of the political and
economic structure of the country.
   ``I have been getting mail from everywhere and people are
wondering why we are restructuring socialism. For years, we have
been talking about perestroika more than actually working on it,''
she wrote.
   She assailed reformist historians Roy Medvedev and Yuri
Afanasyev.
   ``Medvedev has published almost 30 books in the West without
even disturbing dust accumulated on archive files,'' she said.
``Afanasyev has surprised even foreign anti-Soviets by condensed
statements and assessments that heap ignominy on the Soviet order
and are insulting to our people.''
   Mrs. Andreyeva said sensational revelations by the historians
``lead not only to their popularity with the public at large, but
also to an impressive financial well-being.''
   She said opponents of the Communist Party are using perestroika
and glasnost to further their own means.
   While communists campaigned in the March election using methods
of socialist democracy, opponents ``armed themselves with
parliamentary methods of bourgeois democracy which, as is well
known, are not characterized by decency or nobleness,'' she said.
   She said unofficial groups are amassing large amounts of money
from the black market to push for legality in the country where the
Communist Party is the only legal political party.
   ``Fed by millions of rubles from the shadow economy, they are
striving to become legal. They lead to an aggravation of
inter-ethnic relations and stimulate the growth of nationalism,
which is finding an awesome expression in tendencies toward
separatism, which leads to tragedies and appeals for secession from
the U.S.S.R.,'' Mrs. Andreyeva said.
   She called for a return to earlier values.
   ``Socialism, though far from being perfect, is a fact of our
life,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0153 </DOCNO>
