<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Flag     07-28 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Flag,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Skirts Veto Question on Flag-Burning Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday refused to say
whether he'd veto a Democratic-sponsored effort to outlaw flag
burning because their statute does not go along with his insistence
on a constitutional amendment.
   ``I will see what comes down here, but I will continue to push
for the approach that I think is the best, given the Supreme Court
decision,'' he said.
   Asked if that meant he might sign the bill, Bush said, ``I
didn't say that.''
   The House Judiciary Committee on Thursday approved a
Democratic-sponsored criminal statute with a year in jail and an
unspecified fine for people who burn flags.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., and others argue that a
regular statute could overcome the Supreme Court ruling that flag
burning was a protected form of political protest. A constitutional
amendment, they argue, could erode First Amendment rights.
   Bush told reporters Friday the amendment he supports is
carefully drawn, so he isn't worried about infringing on the First
Amendment.
   ``I don't have disrespect for those who want to find a different
answer,'' he said. It was ``heartening ... that there's a wide
array of support for doing something about this question,'' he said.
   The president's words seemed to downplay the political battle in
Congress between supporters of the amendment and of the statute.
But the president's political operatives are working to use the
issue against Democrats who oppose his amendment by painting them
as somehow unpatriotic.
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., said Thursday that
White House Chief of Staff John Sununu urged GOP leaders this week
to speak out because the flag amendment was a ``wedge issue'' _ one
that divides and troubles Democrats.
   Foley said Friday he found it troubling that ``they want to take
the respect that Americans have for the flag and twist it into a
political issue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
