<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MonkeyHerpes     07-28 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Monkey Herpes,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lab Where Monkey Handler Died is Charged With Safety Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A research lab where a technician
died of a rare virus contracted from a monkey was cited and fined
Friday for unsafe working conditions and failure to tell employees
about the job risks.
   International Research and Development Corp. of Mattawan was
fined $30,600 for six violations, ``five for willful violations and
one for a serious violation,'' of the Michigan Occupational Safety
and Health Administration rules, the Department of Public Health
said.
   The investigation followed the June 20 death of Thomas McGeorge,
23, who was infected with the herpes B virus after being scratched
or bitten by a rhesus monkey, a species commonly used in lab
experiments.
   The violations include failure to record and medically monitor
77 employee monkey bites and scratches during the two months before
McGeorge's death.
   Other violations include failure to properly train employees in
the hazards and health risks of their jobs and failure to perform
follow-ups on injured employees, according to the report, signed by
Michael S. Mosher, district supervisor of the state OSHA.
   Questionnaires given to employees by the agency found that of 71
employees who had direct contact with the monkeys, 29 said they had
never heard of the B virus before McGeorge's death.
   Guidelines drawn up two years ago by the federal Center for
Disease Control say that all employees handling such potentially
infected monkeys should be told of the risks.
   Beside McGeorge, another former laboratory employee also is
infected with the virus. The 21-year-old man, whose name has not
been released, was discharged from Bronson Methodist Hospital in
Kalamazoo last week following three weeks of treatment, hospital
officials said.
   IRDC ``emphatically denies the cruel and untrue `allegations'
outlined in the MiOSHA report,'' company spokesman James Webb said
in a statement. ``No employee of IRDC has ever been willfully
injured nor has the company ever violated any laws.''
   Webb said the company plans to appeal the report's findings.
   The report said IRDC's records show tests conducted on the
approximately 190 rhesus monkeys from China before the experiment
began found that about 40 percent of them carried the virus.
   The virus is commonly found in rhesus monkeys and is harmless to
the animals. But it has an estimated 70 percent mortality rate
among humans once symptoms appear.
   The company has said the two infected employees never reported
any bites or scratches; but the report found that no illness or
injury log was kept, as recommended by the CDC.
   The company, also under investigation by the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, employs about 350 people, uses thousands of animals,
including monkeys, dogs, rabbits and rats, to test drugs and
chemicals for pharmaceutical companies.
   Blood tests on about 140 current and former IRDC employees have
not turned up any other cases of the virus, which attacks the brain
and central nervous system. Twelve inconclusive tests are being
redone, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-NavyCuts     07-28 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Navy Cuts,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Navy Announces Reductions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Navy will disband several air, sea,
marine and coastal artillery units this year and next as part of a
general reduction in Soviet armed forces, Tass reported Friday.
   The official news agency quoted Adm. Vladimir Chernavin, the
navy commander, but gave no details.
   Last December, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced plans to
trim the Red Army by 500,000 men and reduce the defense budget by
14.2 percent.
   Chernavin, in the interview with Tass, blamed recent accidents
of Soviet navy vessels on faulty design, poor workmanship and low
naval training standards.
   A nuclear-powered submarine carrying nuclear weapons sank off
Norway in April, and in June, a pipe burst in the reactor cooling
system of another sub.
   The admiral said the Soviet Union has lost only three
nuclear-powered subs in 25 years. Western sources count at least
five submarine sinkings and numerous other accidents resulting in
crew deaths and radiation leaks, but it is not known whether all
lost subs were nuclear.
</TEXT>
