<FIRST>u w AM-US-Afghanistan     07-28 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Officials to Press Soviets on Iran, Afghanistan</HEAD>
<UNK>By BARRY SCHWEID ^AP Diplomatic Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States will tell the Soviet Union
at a meeting this weekend in Stockholm it would be a mistake to
rearm Iran and Moscow should use its improving ties with Tehran to
help American hostages held in Lebanon, an American official said
Friday.
   The meeting in the Swedish capital between a U.S. delegation
headed by Assistant Secretary of State John Kelly and a Soviet
delegation led by Nicolai Kozyrev is part of a series of regional
sessions the two superpowers have been holding as part of their
improving relations.
   The main topic will be Afghanistan, where, the official said,
the Soviets have increased weapons shipments to the Kabul
government to a rate of $2{ billion to $3 billion a year. That is
about double the lethal aid Moscow had given President Najibullah's
government before the Red Army withdrew its last troops in
mid-February.
   Despite an over-all improvement in relations, the Soviets have
complained publicly about continued U.S. arms shipments to rebels
seeking to overthrow Najibullah. They charge both the United States
and Pakistan, which funnels the weapons to the Mujahedeen, with
violating the Geneva Accords that led to the Soviet troop
withdrawal.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the U.S.
weapons deliveries would continue in an effort to counter
stepped-up Soviet military supplies.
   In Washington Friday, Soviet Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, a
military adviser to President Mikhail Gorbachev, said both the
United States and the Kremlin ``ought to take steps to end
hostilities'' in Afghanistan.
   The Soviets meanwhile, are expected to reiterate their
complaints when Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze meets
Saturday with Secretary of State James A. Baker III in Paris, where
they will attend the opening of a month-long conference on Cambodia.
   After the death of the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, the Soviets
agreed to provide arms to Iran, but the official said it was not
clear whether potent weapons would be delivered or spare parts for
old Soviet arms.
   ``We think it would be bad for them to start rearming Iran and
we wouldn't like to see new military systems delivered,'' he said.
   The U.S. view is that Soviet weapons in Iranian hands would be
destabilize the Persian Gulf region. Kelly also is expected to tell
Kozyrev that arming Iran would hurt the Soviet image in the Arab
world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
