<DOCNO> AP890728-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u p AM-Robinson-GOP     07-28 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robinson-GOP,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arkansas Congressman 2nd Democrat to Switch Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Tommy Robinson of Arkansas became the
second House Democrat this year to switch to the Republican Party,
lambasting his old party Friday as ``unwilling to listen to the
majority of the American people.''
   The third-term congressman, making his announcement in a
nationally televised appearance from the White House, was welcomed
by President Bush as ``a man of the poeple, a man who believes in
straight talk, hard work and getting the job done.''
   Robinson, a former sheriff of Pulaski County, was the third
Democrat this week to be commended by Bush after announcing he was
changing his party affiliation.
   The others were retiring District of Columbia Police Chief
Maurice Turner, said to be considering a run for mayor of the
nation's capital, and Louisiana Secretary of State Fox McKeithen,
son of Democratic Gov. John McKeithen and a prospective opponent to
Democratic Sen. Bennett Johnston.
   Robinson has reportedly been considering a run for governor of
Arkansas in 1990. Robinson has said he has made a decision but
won't announce it until Congress finishes its business this year.
   Robinson's switch leaves the House with 256 Democrats and 176
Republicans, with three vacancies.
   The conservative lawmaker's party switch brought immediate
derision from his former Democratic colleagues.
   ``We Democrats are happy that Robinson has finally come out of
the closet politically so we can fight him out in the open,'' said
Rep. Bill Alexander, D-Ark., who called Robinson ``a Republican
sympathizer since he's been here.''
   ``I'm glad to have him out in the open instead of snaking me
behind my back,'' Alexander said.
   Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., called Robinson ``a cagey politician
(with) the ability to confuse a lot of people.''
   Democrats called on Robinson to resign his seat and seek
election as a Republican. ``The most important thing is for the
voters to render a verdict,'' said Democratic National Committee
spokesman Mike McCurry.
   But Robinson said he would not resign, as Texas Sen. Phil Gramm
did in 1983, when, as a Democratic member of the House, he changed
party affiliation. Gramm later won his seat back in a special
election.
   ``We have no party registration in Arkansas. Republicans vote
for me, Democrats, independents, the like. I am not going to
resign,'' Robinson said.
   Rep. Bill Grant of Florida made the switch from the Democratic
to the Republican party in February.
   As for his former comrades, Robinson said there is ``no room for
conservative Southern Democrats in today's national Democratic
Party.''
   ``Even after losing five of the last six presidential elections
in the nation and Arkansas, the leadership of the Democratic Party
still is unwilling to listen to the majority of the American
people,'' he said.
   Robinson, first elected in 1984, and re-elected in 1986 and
1988, serves on the House Armed Services, Veterans Affairs and
Aging committees.
   Earlier this year Robinson made headlines because he hired the
22-year-old daughter of his close friend, business partner and
financial backer, Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, and paid her
$60,000 as a member of his congressional staff.
   Robinson reported owing at least $100,000 to Jones.
   Other Capitol Hill aides just out of college generally make far
less than Miss Jones' salary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
