<FIRST>r a AM-ArsenicPoisonings     07-28 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arsenic Poisonings,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy Shows Suspect's Father Didn't Die Of Arsenic Poisoning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a woman charged with two
arsenic murders had the poison in his system when he died, but it
wasn't a fatal dose, the state's chief medical examiner said Friday.
   The body of Parker Kiser was exhumed a week ago to determine if
he was a victim of arsenic poisoning. His daughter, Blanche Taylor
Moore, is charged with two counts of murder and one of assault in
the arsenic poisonings of her two husbands and a boyfriend.
   Mrs. Moore, 56, a retired grocery clerk, has said she is
innocent.
   ``We did not find toxic concentrations of arsenic in Mr.
Kiser,'' said Dr. John Butts, the medical examiner. ``We did find
he had severe heart disease. We feel he died as a result of his
heart disease. We did find some arsenic in his system at low
concentrations.''
   Kiser died in September 1966 at age 62.
   Butts said the amount of arsenic wasn't a reliable indicator of
whether the poisoning was accidental or intentional.
   Lt. Steve Lynch the arsenic levels were a cause for concern, but
he said no charges have been filed in the case.
   Kiser's body was exhumed as police expanded their investigation
to consider other possible victims. Butts said he is examining the
medical records of four other dead people and expects to get more.
   Lynch said he also has made inquiries into sicknesses of living
people, including both of Mrs. Moore's sons-in-law.
   Mrs. Moore was charged earlier this month with murder in the
October 1972 death of James Taylor, her first husband, and the
October 1986 death of Raymond Reid, a boyfriend. She is facing
assault charges in the arsenic poisoning of her current husband,
the Rev. Dwight Moore, who was hospitalized shortly after the
couple's honeymoon this spring.
   Mrs. Moore is being held without bail in the Alamance County
Jail.
</TEXT>
