<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Fire     07-28 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Fire,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Evacuees Return Home; Thousands More Wait for Rain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of evacuees who fled forest
fires began returning to their homes Friday, but thousands more
awaited rains to dampen fires that still burned in central Canada.
   Firefighters said they had brought some fires under control,
allowing 1,400 more people to begin the journey to homes in
northern Manitoba and Ontario.
   On Thursday, more than 4,000 evacuees from those provinces and
Saskatchewan were allowed to return to their remote northern
communities.
   Canada's worst forest fire season in memory kept 19,000 people
in makeshift accommodations Friday, however, most of them in
Manitoba.
   Cooler temperatures and scattered rains have helped in the past
few days, but firefighters say a good downpour is the only
solution. Skies were mostly clear Friday.
   In Quebec, a forest fire that started more than three weeks ago
in the James Bay area flared again near a hydroelectric site. About
150 tourists were evacuated from there Tuesday.
   The first contingents of about 1,000 residents of Grand Rapids
in Manitoba set out in buses from Winnipeg for the five-hour drive
home Friday.
   Another 400 from Bearskin Lake, Ontario, began the long process
of being ferried back to their remote community in a 40-seater Dash
7 plane from Cochenour, north of Red Lake, and Big Trout Lake,
another reserve where many sought shelter.
   ``It's going to be a long day,'' said Deborah MacLean, spokesman
for the Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources, which she said is
looking for more aircraft to hasten the process.
   At last count, there were 236 fires burning in Manitoba, 188 in
Ontario and 114 in Saskatchewan. Most were started by lightning.
   Manitoba has been worst hit. Fires there consumed more than 1. 7
million hectares, including large tracts of prime timber.
   Officials say the fires have caused $30 million damage in
Manitoba and could drain $150 million more from the provincial
economy in lost revenue from tourism, fishing and logging.
</TEXT>
