<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Venezuela-Atomic     07-28 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela-Atomic,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oldest Atomic Reactor In Latin America Threatened With Shutdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY CAPLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Latin America's oldest atomic reactor
may be shut down after 30 years of operation because of a lack of
funds, said scientists using it for research.
   The RV-1, at Venezuela's Institute for Scientific Investigation,
enjoyed a heyday during the oil-boom decade of the seventies, said
Alberto Maneiro, one of two engineers still involved in programs
using the reactor.
   ``The main benefit we've gotten from it has been the training of
over 300 technicians and scientists in nuclear technology,'' said
Maneiro.
   The reactor, with a potential for producing just 3 megawatts of
power from its chain reactions, is running sporadically at about
half power, said Maneiro.
   ``We do the best we can for maintenance. The problem is the
government funding has dried up,'' said Maneiro.
   The institute uses isotopes from the reactor in medical
research, including the formulation of new parasite medications,
said Maneiro.
   Since the fuel used is primarily uranium and not plutonium, use
of nuclear waste as material for nuclear weapons is impossible,
according to Maneiro.
   Venezuela is a signatory of the Rio de Janeiro pact, which holds
it to maintaining a nuclear-free military.
   The head of the institute's physics department, Maximo Garcia
Sucre, said the reactor needs just $160,000 in immediate funding to
keep it running safely.
   If the money is not forthcoming in the next several months, the
institute will shut down the reactor, said Garcia Sucre, closing an
ambitious chapter of the small nation's efforts to lift itself into
the modern age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
