<FIRST>r w AM-Traficant-IRS     07-28 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Traficant-IRS,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Fighting $180,000 Tax Bill Tries To Cut IRS Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman who's fighting the Internal
Revenue Service in court over $180,000 in contested taxes, fines
and penalties fought the IRS in the U.S. House of Representatives
on Friday. He lost.
   Rep. James Traficant, D-Ohio, tried to cut funding for 100 new
IRS agents.
   ``The American people are upset,'' he argued on the House floor.
   ``The need for revenue cannot be deceived nor denied. But I say
here today that the need for justice is more compelling than the
need for revenue,'' Traficant said.
   His amendment to cut $3 million from a $5.6 billion
appropriation failed on a vote of 398-12, extending Traficant's
losing streak against the IRS.
   Before he was elected to Congress, Traficant successfully fought
a felony bribe case in which the government failed to prove that he
kept money from alleged organized crime figures.
   But based on evidence introduced in the 1983 criminal trial and
a signed statement Traficant gave the FBI, the IRS found that he
owed back taxes.
   U.S. Tax Court Judge John B. Williams Jr. ruled in the
government's favor.
   He concluded that Traficant owed back taxes of $59,278 and
penalties of $29,636. More penalties and interest accumulated
during Traficant's appeal, and his bill now totals an estimated
$180,000 _ roughly double his congressional salary.
   Earlier this week the congressman's lawyers argued his appeal of
that ruling to a three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. Circuit Court
Appeals in Cincinnati. The judges did not indicate when they might
rule.
   The case dates back to 1980, when Traficant was a candidate for
sheriff of Mahoning County, Ohio.
   He was accused of accepting bribes during the campaign from
organized crime figures. In the statement to the FBI, Traficant
admitted he took money with the understanding that if elected he
would not interfere with certain criminal activities.
   But Traficant said he gave the money back and signed the
statement under duress. A U.S. District Court jury cleared him of
the criminal charges.
   Traficant won that 1980 campaign and four years later was
elected to Congress. He's been re-elected twice.
</TEXT>
