<DOCNO> AP890728-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0634 07-28 0822</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0634,0849</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Meets to Chart Future, Decide on Jaruzelski Successor</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with comments by party spokesman Bisztyga
and Prime Minister Sekula; no pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party met Friday and debated
the government's responsibility for the nation's collapsing economy
and the party's dismal performance against Solidarity in the June
elections.
   Party chief Wojciech Jaruzelski opened the two-day meeting, but
party sources said he was likely to resign before the end of the
session, attended by the 230-member Central Committee and the 173
party deputies of the Parliament.
   Jaruzelski was elected president by the National Assembly July
19 and had said he would resign the party post he has held since
1981 if he won the presidency.
   Party spokesman Jan Bisztyga said at a news conference that
personnel matters will be taken up Saturday.
   Before the meeting, newspapers were filled with debate over the
idea of dissolving the party and forming new factions of the left,
or whether to fight to keep the party together.
   Politburo member Janusz Reykowski told reporters Friday: ``The
course of today's debate gives no justification to the opinion that
the party is breaking into factions. There is an idea of respect
for pluralism within the party.''
   The first day's discussion was marked by sharp criticism of the
party's performance in June elections, when the Solidarity trade
union won 260 of the 261 seats it contested, and of the
government's handling of the economy.
   In a surprise development, Politburo member Wladyslaw Baka quit
his post as party secretary in charge of the economy.
   Bisztyga said Baka resigned because he disagrees with the
government's inflation policy.
   Baka has been considered a likely candidate to succeed former
Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, who handed in his
government's resignation when the new parliament was seated last
month.
   Rakowski in turn is angling to succeed Jaruzelski in the top
party post.
   Baka could be shedding his party duties in preparation for
heading the government, or his resignation could be a sign Rakowski
has locked up the party post and Baka is being shoved aside.
   Baka accused Rakowski's government of lacking necessary
``stubbornness and consistency'' in its handling of the economy.
   Deputy Prime Minister Ireneusz Sekula, also considered a leading
candidate for prime minister, later rose to defend the government's
performance. ``The government was criticized for doing too much and
too little,'' he said. ``The assessments could be different when
emotions calm down.''
   Inflation is in triple digits, and basic foods such as bread and
meat are in short supply.
   Baka and Rakowski have disagreed over government plans to
sharply raise food prices Aug. 1. Baka agrees that increases are
necessary but that steps should first be taken to ensure proper
supplies and to assist people on fixed incomes.
   Politburo member Janusz Reykowski presented a report on the June
election, saying the party was unprepared for competitive balloting
and had not anticipated how much the Roman Catholic Church would
rally parishioners to support Solidarity.
   The PAP news agency said the report expressed hope the elections
will have a ``curative effect on the party'' and spur it to change.
   Chief party ideologist Marian Orzechowski, who also is
considered a possible successor to Jaruzelski, said the party must
change ``quickly and thoroughly.''
   ``Most of society has had enough of the party as it has been.
Secondly, a significant part of the party grass roots has had
enough of the style and ways of functioning of the party
leadership,'' PAP quoted him as saying.
   Jaruzelski challenged fellow Communists to decide what ``we
stand for.''
   He also said the next full congress of the 2 million-member
party ``should be set soon.'' The last was in 1986.
   Party sources said a congress could be called as early as this
fall, but Bisztyga said no date would be set during the meeting.
   ``The prevailing opinion is that the congress should be held as
soon as possible, as long as there is good preparation,'' he said.
   Besides Rakowski and Orzechowski, Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw
Kiszczak is considered a possible successor to Jaruzelski.
   In addition to Baka and Sekula, Roman Malinowski, leader of the
Communist-allied Peasant Party, is a likely candidate for prime
minister. Malinowski would be the first non-communist head of
government in the East bloc since World War II.
   Jaruzelski as president must nominate the prime minister, who
then must be approved by Parliament. Parliament is scheduled to
meet Monday.
   Rakowski, despite the worsening of the economy during his nine
months as prime minister, was believed to be gathering support for
the party chief's post from hard-liners and party members fearful
of Solidarity's growing influence.
   Rakowski is disliked by Solidarity for his antagonism toward the
union during the martial-law crackdown of 1981 and for his decision
last year to close the Lenin Shipyard, where Solidarity was founded
nine years ago.
</TEXT>
