<FIRST>r i AM-China-Dissident     07-28 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Dissident,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissident Leader Fired From Youth Federation Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of China's leading dissidents, now in the
United States, was fired from his post in a youth organization, the
official news ageny Xinhua said Friday.
   Political scientist Yan Jiaqi, was expelled from the All-China
Youth Federation and its standing committee, but there are no
reports of dismissal from his job as a researcher in the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences.
   Xinhua said the youth federation voted to remove Yan because he
``acted as a plotter behind the scenes during the recent Beijing
turmoil.''
   The federation includes the Communist Youth League, which
strives to promote patriotism and Communist ideology.
   Yan, 47, participated in the seven-week, pro-democracy student
movement that was crushed by the army June 3-4. He helped draft an
essay criticizing senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   He helped organize an unofficial ``Federation of Intellectual
Circles'' and was named president of the symbolic Democracy
University set up by the students who occupied Tiananmen Square.
   Police have issued an arrest warrant for Yan, but he fled with
his wife, Gao Gao, to Paris via Hong Kong. They are in Chicago this
week to attend the first Chinese Students Congress in the United
States.
   Several dissidents have been dismissed from minor posts in
recent weeks.
   Scientist Fang Lizhi, who has taken refuge in the U.S. Embassy,
was removed from all posts on the China Natural Dialectics Research
Society last week but officials at the Beijing Observatory, where
he works, said they had no orders to fire him.
</TEXT>
