<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Friday he supports his
embattled Justice Department appointee William Lucas ``100
percent,'' and charged Lucas' opponents are playing politics with
the nomination.
   ``I strongly support Bill Lucas,'' Bush said at an impromptu
news conference. ``I am convinced that much _ not all _ that much
of the criticism of him is pure American politics.''
   Criticism of Lucas stemmed from the Michigan lawyer's decision
to switch from the Democratic Party to the Republican Party, Bush
said. ``Then people piled on to a fare-thee-well,'' he said.
   Lucas, who Bush has tapped to head the Justice Department's
civil rights division, has yet to be confirmed by the Senate.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee on Thursday postponed for a week
the vote after Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., asked for more time to
study what he said was new information about Lucas. Heflin appears
to hold a key vote on the panel.
   Heflin said he wanted to look into a contempt of court citation
filed against Lucas over jail conditions when he was Wayne County,
Mich., sheriff. Additionally, Heflin said he was interested in
Lucas' problems gaining admission to the bar, as well as a finding
by the U.S. Customs Service that Lucas failed to report $4,000 in
jewelry on returning from a trip to Asia.
   Lucas' critics say he is unqualified for the job and is not a
strong enough civil rights advocate.
   But Bush said he is lobbying for Lucas' confirmation by making
telephone calls. The president said he told Lucas on Thursday
night, ``I'm staying with you 100 percent and it's going to be
right there and solid.''
