<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru a0643 07-28 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cambodian Factions Optimistic About Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last (n5th) graf, `They are...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with Khmer Rouge comments. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Hun Sen of Cambodia and resistance
leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk said Friday they expect positive
results from an international conference aimed at finding a
solution to the Cambodian conflict.
   The conference of nearly 20 nations opens Sunday in Paris.
   Speaking at a news conference, Hun Sen reiterated his hope that
while negotiations over Cambodia's internal problems were ``totally
bogged down,'' the conference could provide some solutions to other
problems.
   He was referring to the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops and the
assurance that foreign aid to the warring factions will be halted.
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze also indicated
optimism when he arrived Friday for the conference.
   ``If there were no hope for peace I wouldn't be here,'' he said.
   Secretary of State James A Baker III was expected to arrive
Saturday.
   In an interview on Radio Monte Carlo, Sihanouk predicted ``there
will be results,'' but he refused to be more specific.
   The four Cambodian factions, comprised of Hun Sen's government
and a three-party resistance coalition headed by Sihanouk,
confirmed their participation in the conference by reaching a
compromise Thursday on how they will be represented.
   The factions will sit under a Cambodian banner but with separate
plaques identifying each of the four groups.
   Hun Sen had demanded two separate delegations _ his own and
another representing the resistance. Sihanouk wanted one
``unified'' delegation.
   Hun Sen also said it was his hope that the four factions could
reopen internal talks during the monthlong international conference.
   Talks between the four factions broke off Tuesday after only
four hours in a dispute over the role of the Khmer Rouge, the
resistance group with the strongest guerrilla force.
   The Khmer Rouge was responsible for the deaths of hundreds of
thousands of Cambodians while it was in power from mid-1975 to
December 1978. Vietnam toppled the Khmer Rouge when it invaded
Cambodia in 1978. It has promised to withdraw its troops by the end
of September.
   Sihanouk is demanding a four-party interim government in
Cambodia that includes Hun Sen and the Khmer Rouge. Hun Sen opposes
the Khmer Rouge having a role.
   Khmer Rouge leader Khieu Samphan said in an interview on French
television that Vietnamese expansion was the real danger to
Cambodia and it would be conterproductive for the conference to
discuss atrocities during the Khmer Rouge rule.
   ``Everyone is free to judge,'' he said, but to discuss the Khmer
Rouge actions ``is to fall into the Vietnamese trap.''
</TEXT>
