<FIRST>u w AM-ThornburghAide     07-28 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh Aide,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Spokesman Questioned by Federal Grand Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh's spokesman
spent an hour and a half in front of a federal grand jury Friday.
   The spokesman, David Runkel, was called into the grand jury room
by Justice Department attorney Dana D. Biehl, who is spearheading a
probe of leaks to the news media about a federal investigation into
office hiring practices of House Whip William Gray, D-Pa.
   Earlier, reporters watched in a courthouse hallway as Runkel
turned in a grand jury subpoena to a U.S. marshal.
   Thornburgh's spokesman declined all inquiries after his grand
jury appearance. Biehl also refused to answer questions.
   Gray and other congressmen have contended that the leaks this
spring were a politically motivated attack timed to scuttle Gray's
chances of being elected whip, the third-ranking position in the
House.
   On May 31, Gray asked Thornburgh to appoint an independent
counsel to investigate ``illegal and unconscionable'' news leaks
indicating that Gray was under FBI scrutiny.
   Thornburgh declined to appoint an independent counsel but said
he had ordered ``a full investigation of the apparent unauthorized
disclosure of information in this matter.'' The attorney general
said he would dismiss anyone caught leaking material about criminal
investigations.
   FBI agents have interviewed several advisers to Thornburgh and
asked them whether they have been aware of leaks in the Gray case.
   Gray told reporters he was interviewed by FBI agents in
Philadelphia over the Memorial Day weekend, but was told he was not
the target of an investigation. He denied having a no-show employee
on his staff.
   Gray told Thornburgh in a letter that the leaks ``erode
confidence in due process in your agency.''
