<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-DC-10     07-28 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-DC-10,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight from Rio Lands Without Wheel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Libya Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian Airlines DC-10 landed safely at
Pearson International Airport Friday after it lost a wheel on
takeoff in Brazil, airport officials said. None of the 254 people
on board was injured.
   Airport spokesman Bruce Reid said the flight crew was aware of
the problem and the aircraft circled the control tower to confirm
the wheel was missing. He said fire crews and ambulances were
dispatched before the pilot was allowed to land at 7:30 a.m. EDT.
   ``We wanted to be prepared in the event that something went
wrong,'' Reid said.
   Canadian Airline spokesman Mike Dukelow said the missing wheel
was not critical to the landing, but that passengers were told to
assume the crash position as the jetliner came down. ``I'm sure
there was apprehension,'' he said.
   It was the latest in a series of recent incidents involving the
DC-10, including two crashes in the past nine days that killed at
least 188 people.
   Dukelow said that when the plane took off from Rio de Janeiro,
Brazil, the flight crew reported what they thought was a blown
tire, but pieces of metal on the tarmac indicated otherwise.
   The DC-10 has 10 wheels _ four on each wing and two on the nose.
Dukelow said the wheel that fell off was on the left wing. He said
company and federal officials were investigating.
   The International Airline Passengers Association said Thursday
it wants the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration to order DC-10s
out of use. The FAA and McDonnell Douglas Corp., which manufactures
the jets, rejected the demand.
   On Thursday, a Korean Air DC-10 crashed in thick fog near the
airport in Tripoli, Libya, killing at least 77 people. The crash
was under investigation.
   On July 19, a United Airlines DC-10 crashed in Sioux City, Iowa,
killing 111 people. That crash occurred when a tail engine blew
apart and cut off the flow of hydraulic fluid needed to control the
jet.
   A United Airlines DC-10 with 240 people on board experienced
hydraulic problems on Thursday night but landed safely at Los
Angeles International Airport, aviation officials said.
   On Tuesday, a Continental Airlines DC-9 made a rough landing at
Newark, N.J., also after experiencing hydraulic trouble. The plane
blew four of six tires and skidded about 7,500 feet before
stopping. None of the 89 passengers was injured.
   On Thursday night, a Piedmont Boeing 727 landed at Newark after
developing hydraulic problems, but a backup system made it a smooth
landing, officials and passengers said. There were 138 passengers
and seven crew members on board.
</TEXT>
