<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-28 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Thunderstorms Over New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A line of heavy thunderstorms crossed New England on Friday, and
showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the Rockies to
the Appalachians.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered ahead of a cold front
pushing across New England with hail, gusty wind and heavy rain.
During the afternoon, the storms extended from Pennsylvania across
eastern New York, Massachusetts and southern Vermont into Maine.
   Wind caused minor damage to a house near Gorham, Maine, and
downed trees in Franklin County, Mass. During the morning, the
thunderstorms had produced strong, gusty wind that downed trees
south of Cooperstown, N.Y.
   Wind gusts over 58 mph were reported at Greenfield, Mass.
   A few showers and thunderstorms spread across North Dakota into
northwestern Minnesota.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed over the middle
Mississippi Valley into the southern Plains and the central Gulf
Coast states.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed from eastern
Wyoming through Colorado into the southern Rockies.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered across the central
Appalachians.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 99 at Needles, Calif. Friday's low in
the Lower 48 states was 29 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Saturday, scattered afternoon and evening showers and
thunderstorms were forecast from the upper Mississippi Valley
through the middle and lower Mississippi Valley, the Tennessee
Valley and the Gulf Coast states to the southern Atlantic Coast.
Scattered showers and thunderstorms also were forecast over the
northern and central Rockies.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the central Pacific Coast,
the Pacific Northwest, parts of northern Arizona, and from the
Great Lakes into the upper Ohio Valley and much of New England;
between 100 and 110 from the central California valleys into the
desert Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across much of the rest of
the nation.
</TEXT>
