<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2208EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     07-28 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Prevent Anti-U.S. Demonstration</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Police on Friday prevented
nationalist militants from staging a demonstration to mark the 74th
anniversary of the U.S. invasion of Haiti, an organizer said.
   ``At the last minute the police forced us to change our route,
cordoned off the area and scared away potential demonstrators,''
said Francois Pierre-Louis, a leader of the leftist National
Popular Assembly, as he sat in a pickup truck equipped with a
loudspeaker.
   Several dozen militants stood around for about an hour before
dispersing.
   They had planned to begin the march on a seafront boulevard near
the compound for the U.S. Agency for International Development,
where a detachment of about 20 presidential guardsmen was posted on
Friday.
   ``We relocated them for security reasons,'' said Maj. Renaud
Sainbert, who led the unit. ``No one is preventing the
demonstration.''
   He did not say where the militants would be allowed to
demonstrate. The government had issued the group a permit limiting
the demonstration to a few downtown streets.
   After a long period of chaos, U.S. Marines invaded Haiti in 1915
and left in 1934. Between 10,000 and 18,000 Haitians who fought the
occupation were killed by the Marines between 1915 and 1922,
according to prominent Haitian historian Roger Gaillard.
   The Marines created a 4,000-man Garde d'Haiti, which evolved
into the 6,000-man army that now rules the impoverished Caribbean
island.
   ``Today we must recall what this invasion means to the
consciousness of our so-called sovereign people,'' Jean Dominique,
owner of the private station Radio Haiti Inter, said in an
editorial broadcast Friday.
   Haiti's biggest union, the Autonomous Central of Haitian
Workers, backed the demonstration.
</TEXT>
