<FIRST>u w AM-DiplomatSpy 2ndLd-Writethru a0695 07-28 0899</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Diplomat Spy, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0695,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Warns Against Spy Leaks as Leakers Say Bloch Spied For 14 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ``Sattler'' in 12th graf: ``In the,''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush expressed concern Friday that
news leaks may jeopardize the espionage investigation of U.S.
diplomat Felix S. Bloch, who investigators now believe began spying
14 years ago while serving in East Berlin.
   Like the FBI and Justice Department, Bush declined to provide
any facts about the Bloch investigation, which was leaked to the
public a week ago.
   ``I don't want to go into it while it is under investigation,''
Bush told reporters at a White House news conference. ``I am very
concerned about premature discussion and disclosure _ that means
leaks _ on this matter, because I think you can jeopardize the case
itself and perhaps the man's ability to get a fair hearing.''
   No charges have been filed against the 54-year-old diplomat, but
the State Department revoked his diplomatic passport and put him on
paid leave June 22. Under heavy FBI surveillance, he has been
visiting relatives in New York since last Saturday.
   Last Friday, State confirmed news leaks that the FBI is
investigating Bloch for possible ``illegal activities'' involving
``agents of a foreign intelligence service.''
   Since then, government sources, demanding anonymity, have said
he was videotaped passing a briefcase to a Soviet agent in Paris
recently and that the same Soviet agent was monitored telephoning
Bloch with what appeared to be a warning he was under investigation.
   A congressional source told The Associated Press the FBI
currently believes Bloch was recruited as a spy while he was
serving at the U.S. Embassy in East Berlin 14 years ago. The New
York Times reported Friday that Bloch admitted to the FBI he spied
for the Soviets ``for many years'' and that they ``paid me a lot of
money.''
   Government sources have said Bloch, who now has a lawyer, has
refused to cooperate with the FBI since a brief interview June 22.
   In 1974, Bloch became economic counselor in the newly opened
U.S. Embassy in East Berlin. He served there for two years after
transferring from West Berlin where he was economic-commerical and
trade promotion officer in the U.S. mission from 1970 to 1974.
   The 1970s were the heyday of Markus Wolf, 66, the very
successful head of East Germany's foreign intelligence operations
for 29 years until he retired in 1987. Wolf's agents worked
hand-in-glove with the Soviet KGB spy agency, U.S. officials have
said.
   In 1974, Willy Brandt resigned as chancellor of West Germany
after one of his closest aides was unmasked as a hand-picked spy
for Wolf.
   In the early 1970s Wolf's agents also recruited an American
student, James Frederick Sattler, who returned to Washington to
work for the Atlantic Council, a prestigious, private foreign
policy study group. Satler was unmasked as a spy in 1976 when he
was about to get a job on the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
Because he had not yet passed any secrets, U.S. officials could not
charge him with espionage, but they used a little-known spy
registration law to force him to register publicly with the State
Department as having East German spy training.
   Former CIA official George Carver said, ``Wolf makes (British
author) John le Carre's (fictional Soviet spymaster) Karla look
like a rank amateur.'' Carver said Wolf used every trap in the
book, including sex.
   In Austria, where Bloch served from 1980 to 1987 as economic
counselor and then as the No. 2 official in the U.S. Embassy,
Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak confirmed news reports that Bloch
had a ``friendship'' with a Viennese woman over a period of several
years. Austrian officials earlier described her as a callgirl.
   The woman returned from a vacation in Egypt and was questioned
by Austrian authorities this week, Austria's top police official,
Robert Danzinger, said, but this yielded no evidence she suspected
anything about Bloch.
   Danzinger said Friday that a suspected KGB agent who may have
been a contact man for Bloch traveled to Vienna several times in
the past 10 years on false Finnish papers.
   Danzinger said Austrian authorities were told by U.S. officials
on June 23 about a suspected KGB agent who allegedly had contacts
with Bloch.
   ``We assume he worked for the KGB,'' Danzinger said. ``We have
no information of our own that he is KGB. That information came
solely from Washington.''
   For the second day in a row, a top Soviet official denied any
links with Bloch. ``He had no connection with us, no link that
could raise the slightest suspicion,'' Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze told reporters at Orly airport in Paris.
   Several administration sources have suggested that any
admissions made by Bloch to the FBI or State Department security
officers fell well short of the legal requirements of a confession.
   The New York Times said the FBI had received information that
prompted interest in a recent trip Bloch was making to Europe and
planned a surveillance operation.
   The agency notified foreign intelligence services and
congressional committees, and somehow the information got out, the
paper said. As previously reported, U.S. eavesdropping picked up a
Soviet agent telling Bloch, ``A bad virus is going around and we
believe you are now infected.''
   The FBI also got permission to search his home but found nothing
incriminating, the paper said.
</TEXT>
