<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     07-28 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blacks Who Seek Treatment at White Hospitals Face Jail Terms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks who seek treatment at
whites-only hospitals in a mass defiance campaign may be imprisoned
for two years, authorities said Friday.
   In the tiny black homeland of Venda, thousands students
boycotted classes to protest what they say is a coverup by
officials investigating recent killings.
   Adriaan Vlok, the law and order minister, contends the effort to
seek treatment at white hospitals will include acts of violence
intended to disrupt segregated national elections scheduled for
Sept. 6.
   A militant black labor federation accused Vlok on Friday of
deliberately misrepresenting the plans for peaceful acts of
defiance before the election.
   In the first phase of the defiance campaign, to begin Wednesday,
anti-apartheid groups have asked blacks and people of mixed race to
seek medical treatment at eight whites-only hospitals.
   Authorities in Transvaal province, where four of the hospitals
are located, issued a directive saying no one could enter public
hospitals without official authorization. A violator can be
imprisoned for up to two years and fined $740.
   ``Of prime importance is the interest of our patients,'' said
Andre Cornelissen, a provincial administrator. ``I would therefore
make an urgent appeal to persons not to be a part of this defiance
campaign, which will exacerbate the fate of defenseless, sick
persons.''
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, the largest
organization involved, issued a statement denying Vlok's allegation
that the plans called for firebomb attacks on homes of election
candidates and other acts of violence. The congress said it was
considering legal action against Vlok.
   ``We want to state openly and categorically that the minister is
lying,'' it said. ``The arrogance of the minister and his
government is such that they seem to think they can make any
allegations they like and get away with it.''
   In a speech Thursday, Vlok said the call for ``militant mass
action'' was tantamount to a call for violence.
   Protests in Venda have prompted the homeland legislature to
consider a state of emergency, clouding preparations for
festivities in September marking the 10th anniversary of the
homeland's ``independence'' from South Africa.
   At the University of Venda, classes for 4,000 students have been
halted since Wednesday. Boycotts began earlier at some primary and
secondary schools.
   Venda is in the northeast corner of South Africa and has about
500,000 residents. It is one of four tribal homelands designated as
independent by South Africa but not recognized abroad.
   According to reports in two anti-apartheid newspapers, the
protests were inspired in part by three unsolved killings in the
past two weeks, believed by residents to be ritual murders.
   In South Africa, ritual murders are killings in which parts of
the victims' bodies are cut off and used in potions.
   Last year, police in Venda confirmed several ritual murders and
denied charges of a coverup aimed at protecting tribal chiefs and
government officials accused of involvement. The killings last year
prompted a general strike and the justice minister was dismissed.
</TEXT>
