<FIRST>r a AM-ContractsLawsuit     07-28 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Contracts Lawsuit,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Wins Lawsuit Over Access to Athletic Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The contracts of athletic officials at
state universities here must be open to public inspection, a
Superior Court judge said Friday in a ruling that limits what can
be shielded in personnel files.
   The ruling came in a lawsuit filed March 30 by The Associated
Press against five schools.
   ``Information of this kind which is related to the conduct of
public business and to the expenditure of public funds is required
to be disclosed,'' said Wake County Superior Judge E. Lynn Johnson.
   Contracts were sought to examine employment conditions of
coaches and athletic directors at Division I schools in basketball
and football. But the institutions said the contracts cannot be
made public because they are contained in personnel files.
   The lawsuit was filed against Western Carolina University, East
Carolina University, the University of North Carolina at
Wilmington, the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill and
North Carolina State University.
   Two schools, University of North Carolina at Asheville and
Appalachian State University, complied with the request for
contract information.
   ``We feel it is important that the conditions of employment for
these state officials be open to taxpayer scrutiny,'' said Ambrose
D. Dudley, chief of bureau for AP operations in North Carolina.
``The judge agreed.''
   State Deputy Attorney General Andrew A. Vanore Jr., who
represented the schools, was out of town and not available for
comment. A spokesman for the attorney general's office said a
decision hadn't been made on whether to appeal.
</TEXT>
