<DOCNO> AP890728-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2210EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Soviet     07-28 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soviet,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Defense Minister Says NATO Should Not Update Lance Missile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If NATO modernizes its Lance missile, Moscow may
resume production of medium-range SS-23 nuclear missiles banned
under a superpower treaty, the Soviet defense minister said Friday.
   Dmitri Yazov, addressing London's Royal Institute of
International Affairs, said a proposal to replace the Lance with a
longer-range version violated the 1987 Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty.
   He was winding up a four-day official visit, the first by a
Soviet defense minister to a NATO country since World War II.
   ``Why should we continue liquidating our Okas if NATO will not
renounce the modernization of Lance?'' said Yazov, referring to the
missile by a Soviet name.
   Under the treaty, all Soviet and U.S. land-based missile with
ranges of between 300 and 3,000 miles must be eliminated by 1991.
   Yazov said later that if ``the Americans begin to build Lances
with a range up to 500 kilometers (300 miles), we will be forced to
again make this Oka.''
   He said the Soviet Union believed the United States ``does not
have the right to build such a missile.''
   In Washington, a Bush administration official said SS-23s are
clearly covered by the INF treaty and that Lance missiles are not.
``It would be absurd for the Soviets to suggest that while we're in
compliance with the accord, they would have reason to violate it,''
the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   NATO, at a summit meeting in May, deferred a decision on
modernizing the Lance missiles. A proposal calls for tripling the
range of the current missiles, to just under 300 miles.
</TEXT>
