<FIRST>u w AM-EmbassySex     07-28 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embassy Sex,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Prints Prostitute's Story of Sex in Australian Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prostitute has told a newspaper she was paid
$800 for having sex with three men at an Australian Embassy party
while working for an escort service now under federal investigation.
   The unidentified woman's account, published in Friday's editions
of The Washington Times, drew a lengthy denial from Australian
Ambassador Michael Cook, who questioned her credibility and
reputation.
   Cook, in a letter to the newspaper's editor, said ``weeks of
careful investigation have entirely failed to substantiate'' the
woman's story.
   ``We cannot disprove your story, simply because no one can ever
prove a negative,'' Cook wrote.
   The Times reported that the woman worked for an escort service
that is now under federal investigation for credit-card fraud.
   Cook said the story was ``unfortunately bare of hard facts'' and
relied on sketchy information from ``one woman of uncertain
reputation.''
   Wesley Pruden, the newspaper's managing editor, defended the
story and noted it had also appeared in an Australian newspaper and
was aired on television in that country.
   ``We've been reporting this story for several weeks,'' Pruden
said. ``We are very confident that we got it right and when the
ambassador completes his own investigation I think he will see that
we were right.''
   The embassy's investigation was continuing and spokesman Brett
Bayly said Australian diplomatic officials here ``have been in
touch with American authorities.'' Bayly declined to specify what
U.S. agencies had been contacted.
   Cook noted in his letter that top embassy officals worked with
Times reporters and ``investigated the matter thoroughly'' after
they were contacted by the newspaper several weeks ago.
   ``For the story to be true would have required those involved
knowingly to have run extraordinary risks of being surprised,''
Cook said. ``If the party was supposed to have taken place during
the week, plenty of poeple would still have been working in the
embassy.''
   The newspaper said the woman, whom it did not identify, also
told of paid sexual encounters with with a Canadian diplomat and a
U.S. soldier who had worked as a bodyguard to Washington lobbyist
and host Craig J. Spence.
   Spence has been previously identified by the Times as a client
of a homosexual prostitution ring linked to the escort service for
which the prostitute said she worked.
   The U.S. attorney's office is investigating credit-card fraud
involving the escort services, according to sources, who have spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   The newspaper quoted the woman as saying that she and two other
prostitutes each had sexual relations with at least three men at
the embassy. The woman said she was paid $800 in ``crisp, new $100
bills'' after the party.
   The newspaper said the woman provided a detailed description of
the embassy party. She said the men ``took me one at a time'' into
a room ``which was like an office, it had office-type furniture.''
   She said the men did not identify themselves.
   Cook said that the woman's ``descriptions of the embassy's
interior geography and its furnishings simply do not fit the
facts.''
   He also said that her ``descriptions of the men are so vague as
to be useless in identifying who in the embassy might have been
involved.''
   Cook said that ``the source even appeared uncertain that the men
alleged to have been in the incident were Australians.''
</TEXT>
