<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     07-28 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Act on Petition for Reform Signed By 11,500</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six dissidents whose homes were
searched by police are being investigated for sedition in
connection with a petition for democratic reform signed by more
than 11,500 people, authorities said Friday.
   If charged and convicted, they could be sent to jail for five
years.
   Activist Petr Uhl said late Thursday that police searched the
six homes and confiscated documents. He said the targets appeared
to be Obroda, a new reform group, and the petition for liberalism
in Czechoslovakia, among the strictest of Eastern Europe's
communist states.
   By the middle of this week, more than 11,500 people had signed
the petition, which began circulating last month, Uhl said.
   The official news agency CTK said in a terse report that
Thursday's searches in Prague, central Bohemia and south Moravia
were carried out with a warrant from the Prague city prosecutor and
focused on the homes of those ``suspected of elaborating,
circulating and organizing actions of signatures of this appeal.''
   ``Further investigation concentrates on determination of the
responsibility of concrete persons,'' it said.
   Uhl said those whose homes were searched included Jan Urban, a
Charter 77 signatory who accompanied a visiting delegation from the
Polish union Solidarity to meetings with former Communist Party
leader Alexander Dubcek and with activists in Prague and Bratislava.
   Others, also of the Charter 77 dissident group, were former
spokespersons Libuse Silhanova, Stanislav Devaty and Milos Hajek,
current spokesman Sascha Vondra and Vladimir Kolmestr.
   Hajek told The Associated Press in Vienna by telephone the
documents police seized at his home included a draft of a letter to
Communist Party members and a draft for a declaration on the
anniversary Aug. 21 the 1968 Soviet invasion that ended Dubcek's
``Prague spring'' of reforms.
   About 10,000 people marched through Prague on the anniversary
last year.
</TEXT>
