<FIRST>u w AM-Baker 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baker, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0593,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary of State Off To Paris For Cambodian, Soviet Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 4: ``The secretary,'' getting Baker off the ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, hoping to increase
U.S. influence in Southeast Asia, will play a prominent role in a
conference opening this weekend in Paris on Cambodia's future.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, symbolizing U.S. interest
in a settlement of the 10-year war in the hapless country, will
represent Washington in a 20-nation conference that almost broke up
before it began.
   Baker will meet on the side Saturday with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, possibly laying the foundation for
a superpower summit meeting later this year.
   The secretary left Washington Friday afternoon for Paris.
   Disarray among four Cambodian factions threatens to cause a
breakdown at any point in the month-long conference, which will
have its ceremonial opening Sunday. Baker and Assistant Secretary
of State Richard Solomon, who will head the U.S. delegation after
Baker goes home Monday, are hoping that an agreement can be worked
out that preserves Cambodia's independence.
   A 10-year civil war between the forces of pro-Vietnam Prime
Minister Hun Sen and three guerrilla factions widened the
destruction of what remained of the Cambodian civilization after
the murderous rule of Pol Pot from 1975 to 1978. Before that, the
United States, in the Indochina war, contributed to the devastation
of the country.
   Currently, the United States is providing $3 million to $5
million a year in training and non-lethal supplies to the factions
headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk and Son Sann, while China is
arming the Pol Pot forces.
   The U.S. goal is a transitional government that does not return
Pol Pot's group to power _ it is suspected of murdering more than 1
million Cambodians _ nor leaves Hun Sen in charge after Vietnamese
troops pull out in late September.
   Frederick Z. Brown, a former State Department official who has
written a new book, ``Second Chance,'' about Cambodia, said at a
news conference Friday that the United States could be a major
player in Paris.
   ``A lot of people are looking to us because our involvement has
been relatively aloof,'' Brown said.
   He agreed with the stance taken by the Bush administration,
though, that the Cambodian parties themselves must arrive at a
solution for their country.
   Referring to the Indochina war, Brown said this was not the
occasion for ``a new crusade'' by the United States, which warred
with North Vietnam and bombed Cambodia. But, he said, the United
States now has ``a second chance'' to help in the country's
rehabilitation and to improve its standing in the region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
