<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-Israel     07-28 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-Israel,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Attitude Toward Elections Remains Unchanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent Palestinian state remains
the PLO's major condition for agreeing to elections in the
Israeli-occupied territories, Ahmed Abdel-Rahman said Friday.
   Abdel-Rahman, spokesman for the Palestine Liberation
Organization, said in a telephone interview that reports that the
PLO has softened its position on elections were ``fabricated by the
Israeli leadership.''
   ``The PLO position is that we are for elections but in the
context of a comprehensive settlement,'' he said. Such a settlement
would specify that the final result of negotiations would be a
Palestinian state, he added.
   Comments by a Soviet official and Palestinians who met with
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir had indicated the PLO might
have changed its stand.
   Abdel-Rahman said the comments did not represent the PLO's
position toward elections.
   Shamir has proposed elections in which the 1.7 million
Palestinians in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip would choose
representatives to negotiate an interim self-rule plan. Talks would
be held later on the final status of the territories.
   But Shamir has said the PLO conditions are not acceptable and he
would not deal with the PLO, which Israel considers a terrorist
group, even it the PLO abandoned those conditions.
   Israeli Labor Party legislators have said a U.S. document
reflected a softer PLO position. An Israeli official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Wednesday the document was relayed to
Israel by Soviet Middle East envoy Gennady Terrasov. The official
said Terrasov met an aide to Vice Premier Shimon Peres after
holding talks earlier with PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
   In Washington, State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutweiler
denied that such a memorandum existed.
   Abdel-Rahman said Terrasov met with Arafat and then with an aid
to Peres but insisted Terrasov only relayed the established PLO
conditions for accepting elections.
   He said Israeli leaders were behind the reports of a softened
PLO stance ``so they can say to the Americans that the PLO is
coming to their position.... Mr. Shamir is trying to win time.''
   A PLO leader, commenting on the reports of Palestinians meeting
with Shamir, said, ``The PLO did not authorize any Palestinian
inside the occupied territories to negotiate with the Israeli
government.''
   Salah Khalaf made the statement in an interview with the Kuwaiti
newspaper Al-Watan.
   Khalaf is the No. 2 man in Arafat's Fatah, the leading
Palestinian group in the PLO.
   He denied reports that four Palestinians from the occupied
territories met with Shamir on instructions from the PLO.
   Al-Watan, in a dispatch from Tunis where the PLO is
headquartered, quoted Khalaf as saying the PLO leadership ``did not
ask the four Palestinians who met the Israeli prime minister
recently to do so.''
   He said the PLO ``is against allowing any party outside the
legitimate institutions ... the power to open talks with the
Israelis under any circumstances.''
   Khalaf also denied the he had agreed during a recent meeting
with Robert Pelletreau, the U.S.ambassador to to Tunisia, that the
four Palestinians meet with Shamir.
   ``Such a topic was not raised during the meetings with
Pelletreau,'' he said.
   Pelletreau opened a dialogue with the PLO leadership after the
United States dropped its opposition to dealing with the PLO when
the organization renounced terrorism and recognized the state of
Israel in a statement last November.
   In an interview with the Bahrain-based Gulf News Agency, one of
the Palestinians who met with Shamir said details of the meeting
``reached the PLO leadership in Tunis via different channels.''
   Jamal Al-Tarifi, a pro-PLO lawyer, was intervewied by telephone
in London. He did not say he had received PLO clearance for the
meeting but told the agency, ``No meeting or initiative from any
Palestinian figure can succeed if it does not have the approval of
the PLO leadership.''
</TEXT>
