<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2008EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MoscowMayors     07-28 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moscow Mayors,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow's Deputy Mayor Studying U.S. Government Budget Processes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moscow's deputy mayor said Friday he
hopes to learn something from American methods of finance and
budgeting during a tour of U.S. cities, and has already found some
pleasant surprises _ like Boston Harbor.
   ``They told us there was a necessity to clean the harbor, but we
found that it was much cleaner and fresher than we were told,''
Valery A. Zsharov said after a George Bush-style inspection
tour.The harbor became a political issue during last year's
presidential campaign.
   Zsharov and his interpreter, Albert S. Gasparian, head of the
protocol unit for Moscow's Foreign Relations Department, said they
hope to learn how to deal with some of the problems of
decentralization in Soviet cities under Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's policy of perestroika.
   ``The cities have some of the good things in common, and some
problems in common, too,'' said Valery A. Zsharov. But he said the
economic approaches to solving the problems in his city will be
``quite different'' from that in U.S. cities.
   Zsharov arrived in Providence last week. He and his interpreter
and two other colleagues will leave Providence on Aug. 7 and will
travel to New York, Los Angeles and Atlanta before returning to the
Soviet Union.
   Their trip was sponsored by Brown University's A. Alfred Taubman
Center for Public Policy and American Institutions at the school's
Center for Foreign Policy Development.
   The visitors were taken to Boston for two days to meet with
present and former elected officials on the state, local and
federal levels, along with the heads of various state agencies,
developers and builders.
   As a result of legislation designed to decentralize bureaucracy
in the Soviet Union, the Moscow Soviet, or City Council, is trying
to improve its abilities in budgeting and finance and in boosting
economic development.
   The city has some 2 million employees, handling functions
usually carried out by private enterprises in the United States.
   As deputy mayor, Zsharov directs Moscow's main department of
trade, restaurants and consumer services, and coordinates joint
ventures for the city. He also has a strong voice in how the city's
4-billion-ruble budget is spent.
   Zsharov, 53, said that while there are similarities between
Boston and Moscow, there are strong differences such as employment.
   ``In Boston there is unemployment and we need labor. We have a
very high labor shortage,'' he said, chain-smoking Russian
cigarettes. ``The shortage creates some difficulties.''
   ``Moscow's problems are very open and clear,'' he said. ``The
most acute are housing and transportation. ... Much of our housing
was destroyed in World War II. It's much more acute than in the
U.S.''
   Zsharov was most impressed with the construction and building
industry in the United States.
   ``Up to now, we cannot boast that level of construction,''
Zsharov said. He said Moscow is working on a long-term program
through the year 2000 in an attempt to build enough apartments to
house everyone in the city.
   At Brown, the Soviets are studying how local, state and federal
governments in the United States make up budgets, distribute money
and interact with one another. They also will tackle problems like
environmental damage and urban revitalization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
