<HEAD>AIDS Carrier Charged with Biting Police Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MULHOUSE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man diagnosed as carrying the AIDS
virus was charged Friday with attempting to poison a police officer
by biting him, according to news reports.
   Agence France-Presse quoted a prosecutor as saying Philippe
Bouille, 29, bit a policeman on the finger when the officer tried
to arrest him for drunkenness in the village of Saint-Louis near
Mulhouse early Thursday.
   The prosecutor, who was not identified, said the bite was so
severe the officer's hand bled and Bouille shouted, ``I have AIDS
and now you are going to die, too.''
   ``This is the first time in France that a magistrate has decided
to bring criminal charges in this type of affair,'' AFP quoted the
prosecutor as saying.
   The report did not say if the policeman had requested or been
given a test for acquired immune deficiency syndrome. The fatal
disease is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer.
