<FIRST>r a AM-Landano     07-28 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Landano,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted in Cop Killing Freed After 13-Year Imprisonment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DARLENE SUPERVILLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent 13 years in prison for the
killing of a police officer was freed Friday after an appeals court
upheld a federal judge's ruling that crucial evidence had been
suppressed by prosecutors.
   ``I feel great,'' said V. James Landano as he left the federal
courthouse. ``Right now, I just want to get away.''
   Judge Leonard I. Garth, of the 3rd U.S. District Circuit Court
of Appeals, on Friday denied the state's appeal to overturn the
decision of a federal judge who reversed Landano's conviction on
Thursday.
   U.S. District Judge H. Lee Sarokin vacated Landano's conviction,
ruling that prosecutors covered up evidence casting doubt on
eyewitness identifications of Landano as the man who shot dead a
Newark policeman during a 1976 robbery.
   Sarokin said the prosecution showed a ``pattern of failures'' in
turning over exculpatory evidence.
   Sarokin was the judge who last year freed Rubin ``Hurricane''
Carter, a boxer serving life for a triple murder, on grounds that
Carter's conviction was tainted by racism and suppressed evidence.
   Garth set Tuesday as the deadline for prosecutors to appeal
Landano's release.
   ``The state does plan to continue with its appeal,'' said
Christopher Florentz, a spokesman for the state Attorney General's
office. ``We're going to do it as quickly as possible.''
   Landano, sentenced to life in prison, has maintained he was
framed by motorcycle gang members protecting the real killer _ his
childhood friend.
   Landano and three others were charged in the killing of 23-year
veteran Officer John Snow at the robbery of a check-cashing
establishment in Kearny. Landano was convicted as the gunman.
Victor Forni was later convicted of planning the crime for the
Breed motorcycle gang and served nine months of a two-year sentence.
   When Landano supporters compiled evidence pointing to his
innocence, Sarokin last month ordered investigative files seized,
and from them, Landano's lawyers found the papers on which the
judge based Thursday's decision.
   One was a Kearny police interview report with a witness at a
warehouse near the crime scene, who identified a picture of Forni
as the getaway car driver. The driver had been identified as the
gunman. The report was never given to Landano and the picture never
found.
   Sarokin also cited a handwritten document from Kearny police
files saying that the only eyewitness of the shooting had said of
Landano, ``hair not right _ suspect had curly hair.'' Notes on
another witness said the same thing.
   Newark police officials decried the judge's decision, saying
Landano should have been kept in custody until the crime was
resolved.
   ``To have him walk out of jail without being retried or the
triggerman who killed Officer Snow being located would be a great
injustice,'' said Newark Police Chief John Golba.
   The Newark lodge of the Fraternal Order of Police, the
bargaining agent for about 1,000 Newark policemen, said it opposed
freeing Landano and would protest the decision if Landano did not
get a retrial.
   Bail was set at $50,000, but Landano, a New York City resident,
was released on his own recognizance into the custody of his
attorney, Neil Mullin. It was not clear Friday if Landano would
face another trial. State Deputy Attorney General Carol Henderson
said the state would appeal Thursday's decision on the grounds that
the federal courts did not have the right to intervene in the case.
Ms. Henderson said Landano did not exhaust all his options under
the state court system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
