<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2302EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Garcia     07-28 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Garcia,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garcia Calls for Death Penalty for Terrorists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alan Garcia, in his final
state-of-the-nation address, urged Congress Friday to adopt the
death penalty for acts of terrorism.
   He also told Congress that a system of military courts should be
established to try suspected terrorists.
   Peru now has the death penalty only in cases involving treason
during time of war. Garcia did not elaborate on proposed military
courts to try cases involving terrorism. Those cases now are tried
in civil courts.
   Garcia also said that presidential elections will be held next
April as specified by law.
   Some members of his center-left Aprista party had called for
early elections because of the possibility of runoff balloting if
no candidate wins a majority of the vote. The law sets the date for
the presidential balloting to be on the second Sunday of the
election year and Garcia said the election would be on April 8,
1990.
   He said he would name a bipartisan congressional commission to
``guarantee an absolutely clean election.''
   Garcia is barred by the constitution from running for a second
term and the winner is to be installed on July 28. It is expected
there will be three major candidates representing Aprista, the
center-right Democratic Front alliance and a coalition of leftist
parties.
   Deputies wanting the presidential election to be held early said
that if a runoff is required the winner might not be determined in
time for the installation. A runoff election between the top two
vote getters would be held within 30 days after the first election.
Some deputies noted that in the last presidential election in 1985
it took more than two months for ballots from outlying areas to
arrive and be counted in Lima.
   Garcia, referring to attacks by guerrillas of the Maoist Shining
Path and pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, said ``the
armed forces are the greatest guarantee for our democracy against
subversion.''
   His address, on television and radio, could not be seen or heard
by many Peruvians because of a power failure. The blackout in
sections of Lima and other areas was caused by rebel bombings
Wednesday of substations in the power network near Huancayo, 140
miles east of Lima.
   Garcia spoke of disappointments during the first four years of
his 5-year term.
   ``After four years I can make a confession,'' he said. ``I
wanted to do more, to move the country along very quickly, change
the structure of economic power.
   ``But this is difficult to do, sometimes impossible, when you
use as your instrument a centralized, bureaucratic state made to
serve the big powers.''
   When he took office in 1985 Garcia said Peru would no longer
deal with the International Monetary Fund, which he called an
instrument of imperialism. He also announced Peru would limit
payments on its foreign debt to 10 percent of its foreign exchange.
   Money diverted from the debt service was used to finance jobs
programs, raise the minimum wage and subsidize imports.
   Public opinion polls showed that during his first year in office
Garcia's popularity soared to 90 percent. But surveys indicate it
has dropped to about 10 pecent now as the economy faltered and fell
with deficit spending, crippling inflation and labor strikes.
   In 1988 Peru's gross national product decreased by nearly 9
percent and inflation registered 1,780 percent.
   The foreign debt of $16.5 billion more than double's the nations
gross national product of $30 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
