<FIRST>r a AM-ChemicalDerailment     07-28 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Derailment,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Fire Doused on Derailed Train Tanker After 6 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chemical fire in a tank car finally
burned itself out six days after the derailment of a CSX
Transportation Inc. train, but about 200 residents remained
evacuated Friday.
   ``It was a lazy fire at times. We had introduced air ... through
an intake valve to intensify the burn'' and speed it up, CSX
spokesman R. Lindsay Leckie said.
   Emergency crews pumped about 2,000 gallons of chlorosilene out
of the tank car while the chemical, a liquid used in silicon
production, continued burning, he said.
   About 200 people living near the derailment site were asked to
remain evacuated at least through Friday night, Leckie said. They
will be allowed to return home after two other tank cars loaded
with flammable chemicals _ both intact _ could be removed from the
site, he said.
   Fourteen cars, seven loaded and seven unloaded, derailed just
before noon July 22, sparking fires that sent up huge plumes of
thick black smoke and initially forcing the evacuation of about
3,000 people within a 15-square-mile area.
   The accident cost CSX at least $1.5 million in damage to
equipment and other costs, Leckie said. The railroad, headquartered
in Baltimore and Jacksonville, Fla., is the nation's largest in
terms of revenue _ about $4.5 billion yearly.
</TEXT>
