<FIRST>u a AM-FiresRdp     07-28 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fires Rdp,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Fires Force University Evacuation While Idaho Blazes Rage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Idaho Fires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two California wildfires threatened homes and forced the
evacuation of a university campus Friday, and Idaho's governor
declared a state of extreme emergency because of hundreds of forest
fires there.
   A 6,000-acre wildfire bore down on ranch homes near the central
California city of Atascadero. In the Los Angeles community of
Walnut, a fast-moving fire edged toward several homes and the
nearby California Polytechnical Institute, Pomona campus, officials
said.
   In Idaho, Gov. Cecil Andrus authorized military reinforcements
Friday to join the battle against hundreds of forest fires burning
out of control. His emergency proclamation, which allows the state
to use the National Guard, will last for 30 days or until the fire
danger subsides.
   About 200 Los Angeles County firefighters were battling a
300-acre blaze, but officials could not estimate how soon they
would have it contained, said County Fire Department spokeswoman
Barbara Sapien. Firefighters were assisted by 21 engines and
bulldozers battling the blaze, about 30 miles east of Los Angeles,
the spokeswoman said.
   Campus police decided to evacuate the school as the fire
approached from the south, said Inspector John Tabak, of the Los
Angeles County fire department. It not immediately known how many
people were forced to leave.
   In central California, teams were deployed to water down homes
in the sparsely populated area near Atascadero, said California
Department of Forestry spokeswoman Tish Teely.
   The blaze had destroyed between 15 and 20 outbuildings,
including barns and corrals, Ms. Teely said. Owners evacuated
animals from some ranches, she said.
   ``It's very close to some homes and moving at a good clip,'' Ms.
Teely said.
   About 680 firefighters had the blaze 30 percent contained late
Friday. Teely said full containment was expected Saturday.
   Firefighters in northern Idaho were helped by high humidity that
slowed the flames, while the opposite was true for the Boise
National Forest.
   ``The humidity dropped considerably,'' said Lynette Davis, Boise
forest spokeswoman. ``When the air dried out, the fires got up and
ran.''
   A lightning storm earlier this week covered central Idaho with
500 fires, some limited to just a burning tree. Firefighters
concentrated on the larger blazes, while parachuting smokejumpers
or helicopter-borne crews tackled the small ones.
   The containment of small fires and shuffling of crews Friday
left it difficult to assess total acreage burned or manpower on the
fire lines.
</TEXT>
