<FIRST>u a AM-StokesTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0767 07-28 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stokes Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0767,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Cleveland Mayor Cleared of Petty Theft Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Stokes acquitted. Picks up
5th graf, ```I said...' SUBS 12th graf pvs, `If he...,' to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS J. SHEERAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHAKER HEIGHTS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Friday night found former
Cleveland Mayor Carl B. Stokes innocent of a petty theft charge for
taking a $17.25 bag of dog food from a store without paying.
   The eight-member jury deliberated for about three hours before
returning with the verdict.
   Stokes, now a Cleveland municipal judge, testified in his own
defense Friday that he had always intended to pay for the dog food.
   ``I'm not going to take a bag of anything without paying for
it,'' said Stokes, in his testimony in Shaker Heights Municipal
Court. Three of his children and his brother, Rep. Louis Stokes,
D-Ohio, were in the courtroom.
   After the verdict was read, Stokes rose from his seat in the
courtroom to the cheers of family and friends in the courtroom
gallery. He smiled broadly while accepting handshakes.
   Louis Stokes, who also is Carl Stoke's longtime political ally,
commented: ``I'm happy for my brother. He's been totally
vindicated. He maintained his innocence from the beginning. The
victory tonight reasures my faith in the judicial system.''
   Carl Stokes, 62, said he twice entered a pet store the morning
of June 2 through a rear door and asked two dog groomers about
buying dog food for his Rottweiler, Max. Each time they said the
store's regular employees had not yet arrived for the day, Stokes
testified.
   ``I said, `The hell with it, I'll get a bag of dog food and come
back and pay for it in the afternoon','' Stokes said.
   He said he was in a hurry to drive to downtown Cleveland for
three morning appointments.
   Five hours later, Stokes said, he returned to the store with the
intention of paying for the dog food but sensed hostility from two
regular employees he had known from past shopping trips to the
store.
   ``I really didn't feel safe,'' said Stokes. He concluded that
``they think I stole it.''
   Stokes said he was scared and again left the store without
paying for the dog food because he felt even the appearance of
wrongdoing could hurt his reputation or ruin his career.
   ``With a person like me, it doesn't have to be true for those
things to happen,'' said Stokes, citing television crews in the
courtroom of this Cleveland suburb as evidence of interest in
public officials.
   Asked by defense attorney Gerald Messerman if he could prove
whether he intended to return to pay for the dog food, Stokes said,
``There's no way to prove.'' But he said he had twice asked to buy
some dog food, had said hello to a police officer outside the store
moments later and returned to the store that afternoon.
   If he had been convicted of the first-degree misdemeanor of
petty theft, Stokes would have faced a maximum penalty of six
months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Stokes served two terms as Cleveland mayor, from 1967 to 1971,
and chose not to seek a third term.
   He worked as a news reporter for WNBC-TV in New York before
returning to Cleveland in 1980 to become a labor lawyer. He was
elected to the municipal bench in 1983.
   Last December, a hardware store security guard stopped Stokes,
who had a $2.39 screwdriver in his pocket. Stokes said he had
forgotten to pay for it. The store did not pursue shoplifting
charges.
</TEXT>
