<FIRST>u a AM-HeraldExaminerSale     07-28 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Herald Examiner Sale,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Herald Examiner Put Up For Sale, Employees Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hearst Corp. told employees of The Los
Angeles Herald Examiner on Friday that it is selling the daily
newspaper, an editor at the paper said.
   ``We got the announcement today,'' said Andrea Herman, the
paper's features editor. ``They have put up the paper for sale and
will evaluate offers from interested parties.''
   The reason for the sale was not publicly announced. But a
statement issued to newspaper employees said the sale stemmed from
``intense pressure'' from the paper's competition in the nation's
second-largest newspaper market.
   ``For a number of years, the Herald Examiner has been in an
extremely challenging situation,'' said the statement by Robert J.
Danzig, vice president and general manager of Herald Newspapers.
   In recent years the Herald Examiner has lost readers to the Los
Angeles Times and the Los Angeles Daily News, as well as growing
suburban papers.
   With a circulation of 238,392 daily and 183,122 on Sunday
editions, the Herald Examiner ranks as the 42nd largest newspaper
in the country, Ms. Herman said.
   Daily circulation peaked at 729,000 in 1967, when the Herald
Examiner was the nation's largest afternoon daily. The Newspaper
Guild launched a 10-year strike that year from which the newspaper
never recovered economically.
   ``We have weighed these considerations carefully and have
reached a conclusion that continuing our ownership of the Herald
Examiner is not compatible with the strategic direction of our
newspaper company,'' Danzig said.
   Hearst, a privately held company, has acknowledged financial
losses at the Herald Examiner but does not disclose specific
figures for the newspaper.
   Despite its financial difficulties, the Herald Examiner has
earned a reputation as a scrappy newspaper with vigorous coverage
of the city.
   The newspaper was the first to delve into the financial dealings
of Mayor Tom Bradley, and its queries into Bradley's ties with a
commercial bank prompted this week's City Council hearings into a
controversial deposit of city funds with the bank.
   Hearst hired the investment banking firm of Lazard Freres &amp; Co.
of New York to handle negotiations for the sale, according to the
announcement given newspaper employees.
   The paper has 760 editorial and administrative employees, Ms.
Herman said.
   John J. McCabe, the Herald Examiner's chief operating executive,
could not be immediately reached for comment. Editor Maxwell
McCrohon was out of town.
   The internal company announcement did not cite possible a
possible sales price or say if there would be any personnel
changes, Ms. Herman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
