<FIRST>a i PM-Cyprus-Divisions Adv02   07-28 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyprus-Divisions, Adv 02,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs Aug. 2 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cyprus Divided as Ever 15 Years After Turkish Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the dun-colored slopes of the Kyrenia
Mountains overlooking this divided capital, Turkish Cypriots have
carved a huge Islamic crescent and a fashioned a huge Turkish
Cypriot flag in stones.
   They're a constant taunt to the Christian Greek Cypriots,
reminding them that one-third of the east Mediterranean island is
still occupied by the Moslem Turks 15 years after they invaded July
20, 1974.
   Not that most Greek Cypriots want to forget or let anyone else
do so. Travellers leaving from Larnaca airport on the south coast
pass roadside posters reading: ``Don't forget the Turkish
invasion.''
   Greek Cypriots believe they hold the moral high ground and by
keeping the division of Cyprus prominent in the international arena
they will be able to end the occupation.
   The Kyrenia range, which looms over the island's central plain,
is in the territory the Turkish Cypriots declared a breakway
republic in 1983.
   Nicosia itself is split by the so-called Green Line, a
112-mile-long buffer zone that snakes across the island.
   It is patrolled by 2,300 United Nations peacekeeping troops who
have been in Cyprus since sectarian bloodletting erupted in 1964.
   Along the line, soldiers of the rival communities' forces face
each other from sandbagged pillboxes in urban alleyways and hilltop
bunkers, sometimes only yards apart.
   On the July 20 anniverary of the invasion, 1,000 Greek Cypriot
women, many of them refugees from the north, stormed through the
buffer zone to occupy a war-ruined, weed-encrusted school and
church.
   Turkish Cypriot riot police stormed the roofless buildings,
beating the women with clubs. One hundred women were arrested and
put on trial, a move that infuriated the Greek Cypriots.
   The protest by women demanding the right to return to their
homes in the Turkish Cypriot sector and the Turkish response
aroused sectarian passions and threatened to wreck U.N.-sponsored
talks on reunifying the island in a bizonal federation.
   The current round of negotiations between President George
Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash have continued for 10 months with little sign of
progress, despite initial hopes of a breakthrough.
   Denktash wants complete political equality, even though the
Turkish Cypriots form only 17 percent of the population, with the
north's Moslem identity intact.
   The Greek Cypriots want a federal framework, with the 200,000 of
their people who fled the north allowed to return, a move that
would swamp the Turkish Cypriots.
   Denktash, president of the Turkish Cypriot state, has cast
doubts on a federation.
   ``The Greek Cypriot leadership did not contribute to peace by
pushing the women toward our border,'' he said.
   The bottom line is that after the sectarian atrocities of the
past, the 120,000 Turkish Cypriots feel secure with their own
state, even if it is only recognized by Turkey and totally
dependent on the Turkish government economically and militarily.
   Denktash noted in a broadcast on Radio Bayrak, the breakaway
state's radio: ``The Greeks continue to have claims on the north.
But the Turks ... do not intend to be divided again.''
   If 1974 brought the Turkish Cypriots security, it traumatized
the Greek Cypriots.
   More than 2,000 of their people were killed. An additional 1,600
are missing, still unaccounted for.
   One-third of their number are refugees in their own land and
although many have successfully rebuilt their lives and businesses,
the issue remains inflammatory, as the women's protest showed.
   The Turkish army lost 2,000 men killed and the Turkish Cypriots
900 in 1974. Seven hundred others remain missing. Forty thousand
moved north.
   There are 30,000 Turkish regulars with tanks and missiles in the
north. To the Greek Cypriots, that's an intolerable violation of
Cyprus' internationally recognized sovereignty.
   ``Legitimacy is our main counterweight to the Turkish troops in
the north,'' President Vassiliou's adviser, Michael Attalides,
noted recently.
   There are also some 50,000 mainland Turkish settlers in the
north. The Greek Cypriots accuse Turkey of trying to alter the
island's demography.
   The politically powerful settlers are not welcomed by all
Turkish Cypriots either. Many see them as a threat.
   ``If the settler trend continues ... in 10 years the Greek
Cypriots will probably find they're negotiating with mainland
Turks,'' said Ozker Ozgut, leader of the opposition Turkish
Republican Party in the north.
   Many Greek Cypriots prefer to forget that the invasion was
triggered by a short-lived coup by militant supporters of union
with Greece, backed by the right-wing military junta that ruled in
Athens at the time.
   The Turks said they struck to protect the Turkish minority, for
whom union with Greece means total Greek domination.
   In the 15 years since 1974, differences have, if anything,
deepened.
   The Greek Cypriot economy has flourished, despite the loss of 70
percent of the island's agricultural land and the port of Famagusta.
   But the Turkish Cypriots, cold shouldered by the international
community, remain impoverished, dependent on Turkey for survival.
   A generation of young people on both sides of the dividing line
has grown up with no knowledge of the other.
   They are unable to grasp the passions of their elders and are
more prepared to accept the status quo.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Aug. 2</NOTE>
