<FIRST>a i PM-Namibia-Ex-Prisoners Adv03   07-28 0954</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Namibia-Ex-Prisoners, Adv 03,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs Aug. 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Namibian Ex-Prisoners Say Hundreds Remain in SWAPO's Dungeons</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, an accompanying story is PM-Namibia-Refugees, b0136</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japhet Isaack fled Namibia in 1978 to
join the SWAPO guerrilla movement and fight South African rule.
   But he said his toughest battle was for his own survival at
SWAPO prison camps in southern Angola, where hundreds of his
countrymen allegedly have been tortured and remain locked in
dungeons run by the guerrillas who accused them of being South
African spies.
   Isaack has worked with other recently released SWAPO detainees
to compile the names of 439 people they believe still are held and
94 more they think have been killed by SWAPO, the South-West Africa
People's Organization. They say the number of detainees could be as
high as 2,000.
   ``These people have been falsely imprisoned and tortured,''
Isaack said in an interview. ``We must not forget about them until
we know they are safe.''
   The lists have dates and locations in Angola where each
individual was last seen. The United Nations says it is
investigating but maintains it has no concrete evidence of
additional detainees.
   ``The population would like to know the whereabouts of 2,000
men,'' U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said after a
recent visit to Namibia.
   SWAPO, which has waged a 23-year bush war against South
African-led security forces, is favored to win elections set for
November and form a government when the territory receives
independence early next year on a date still to be decided.
   The organization said it released all 201 of its political
prisoners in April, including Isaack, from a camp in southern
Angola where they were registered by U.N. officials.
   But only 153, including women and children, have returned to
Namibia. Neither the United Nations nor SWAPO has said where the
remaining 48 are.
   Martti Ahtisaari, who heads the U.N. contingent monitoring
Namibia's independence process, declined to say whether the United
Nations has requested permission from the Angolan government or
SWAPO to visit the prison camps.
   The International Committee of the Red Cross says it has
repeatedly sought but never received access to SWAPO camps.
   ``We know there are missing people,'' said Nicolas de Rougemont,
head of the Red Cross operation in Namibia. ``Whether there still
are people in detention, we don't know because we can't verify.''
   SWAPO has acknowledged abuses against detainees, saying it was
engaged in a ``war for survival'' and had to ferret out suspected
South African spies. South African security officials continue to
boast that they have a huge network of agents working inside SWAPO.
   ``We considered (the prisoners) as spies, but not as enemies,''
said Theo-Ben Gurirab, SWAPO's long-time U.N. representative and
now head of its foreign affairs office. ``We recognized they were
brainwashed and we decided to detain them during the course of the
war.''
   More than a dozen ex-prisoners were interviewed by The
Associated Press, and all said they were falsely accused of spying
and that the guerrilla movement never presented evidence to support
the charges.
   ``We have committed no crime against the Namibian revolution and
we pledge to remain faithful to the total liberation of our
people,'' the ex-prisoners said in a joint statement.
   Virtually all the former detainees have long, thick scars
crisscrossing their backs, legs, wrists and ankles.
   Isaack said he was arrested and accused of spying in May 1986,
shortly after he had been named SWAPO's deputy representative to
the United Nations.
   During his time in detention, he said, he was hung upside down
from a tree and beaten unconscious with sticks and electrical
wires. He also was buried in sand with a plastic bag over his face
for minutes at a time, he said.
   Others have told similar stories and said additional forms of
torture included pouring gasoline onto open wounds after hours of
beatings.
   Several female prisoners said they were sexually abused and
beaten while pregnant. After giving birth, they remained imprisoned
and had no access to medical care for themselves or their children,
they said.
   The prisoners also said that during the regular torture sessions
they were threatened with death unless they confessed to being
South African spies.
   They told of living in filthy, overcrowded pits. Most said they
knew many people who suddenly disappeared from the prisons or died
in detention because of the unsanitary conditions and the severity
of the torture.
   Many of the former detainees are young, articulate and educated,
unusual in a territory where more than half the population is
illiterate. Three of the detainees were former members of SWAPO's
Central Committee.
   Ex-detainee Eric Biwa and other former prisoners say they
believe the old guard SWAPO leadership concocted a ``spy bogey'' as
an excuse for cracking down on young challengers who questioned
strategy, particularly the military effort.
   ``SWAPO has been unable to solve its internal differences in the
past,'' said Biwa, who was arrested while studying in Cuba in 1984.
``We will work against a SWAPO election victory because we fear
what they will do if they come to power.''
   SWAPO's Gurirab claims the organization will prosecute people
suspected of torture. SWAPO also has said that thousands of SWAPO
members or supporters were harassed, tortured or detained without
trial by the South African-led security forces.
   But the prisoners held by SWAPO say details about the past
abuses must be made public.
   ``Our hope is that Namibia will never again be ripped asunder by
war,'' the ex-detainees' joint statement said. ``But SWAPO must
release all Namibians unjustifiably called `enemy agents' and must
announce how many people it killed and why.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Aug. 3</NOTE>
