<SECOND>PM-Namibia-Refugees, Adv 03,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs Aug. 3 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Shortfall Noted in Numbers of Namibian Refugees Claimed by SWAPO</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Namibia-Ex-Prisoners, b0135</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of refugees are streaming
back to Namibia as independence approaches, but their numbers are
well short of the 80,000 that the SWAPO movement claimed and
received money for during its years in exile.
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has given
SWAPO, the South-West Africa People's Organization, more than $21
million in aid for the 80,000 refugees that guerrilla officials
said they cared for in neighboring Angola, Zambia and Botswana.
   But when SWAPO registered exiles for repatriation earlier this
year, it produced only 41,000 names. U.N. officials accepted this
figure without taking their own count, according to Sylvester
Awuye, deputy director of the U.N. refugee office in Windhoek.
   Fewer than 30,000 of the 41,000 have returned under the U.N.
program, which began in mid-June.
   SWAPO leader Sam Nujoma has said the conflicting refugee figures
are due to large numbers of schoolchildren who are not being
returned because war damage to schools and villages in northern
Namibia would deprive them of classrooms.
   ``In any nation you find that children are in a majority so
those who are registered to return are those ... above the age of
18,'' said Nujoma, who has yet to return to Namibia himself.
``After independence when we build the schools we will take them
along.''
   In addition to the U.N. program, an estimated several thousand
refugees have entered northern Namibia from Angola informally in
recent months. The border is more than 600 miles long and is
unmarked in many parts. Formal entry points are staffed irregularly
and can ususally be crossed with a few polite words to the border
guards.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Aug. 3</NOTE>
