<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-MajorDad Adv31   07-28 0890</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Major Dad, Adv 31,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, July 31, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CBS Comedy Hopes Resting on Shoulders of `Major Dad'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.D. ``Mac'' MacGillis' motto, gleaned from a
lifetime in the U.S. Marine Corps, is simple _ ``See the hill. Take
the hill.''
   It probably won't be that easy, though, when Mac, played by
Gerald McRaney in CBS' ``Major Dad,'' faces his biggest battle,
against a wise-mouthed space alien who lives on a very large hill
called NBC.
   ``Major Dad's'' assignment in the fall is to anchor CBS'
all-comedy Monday-night lineup. It's an uphill battle. A succession
of CBS half-hour comedies have tried and failed to make headway
against NBC's powerhouse puppet ``ALF'' in the 8 o'clock (Eastern)
time period.
   But after a second season in third place, and with a schedule
filled with aging hour dramas or new ones struggling to build an
audience, CBS desperately needs a breakout comedy it can move to
another night.
   The fate of two other new comedies will rely in part on the
popularity of their lead-in. ``Major Dad'' will be followed by a
new offbeat fantasy-comedy, ``The People Next Door.'' Sandwiched
between last season's hit ``Murphy Brown,'' and the proven
``Designing Women'' _ which, incidentally, stars McRaney's new
bride, Delta Burke _ is the other new show, ``The Famous Teddy Z,''
starring teen hearthrob Jon Cryer in a sophisticated comedy from
the creator of ``WKRP in Cincinnati'' and ``Frank's Place.'' The
venerable ``Newhart'' rounds out the night.
   Most of the television critics meeting here had a favorable
reaction to the pilot for ``Major Dad,'' in which the conservative
MacGillis and a liberal reporter for the local newspaper (played by
newcomer Shanna Reed) fall in love at first sight and decide to
marry. He has no experience with children. She has three daughters,
13, 11 and 6.
   In his first visit to their house, 6-year-old Casey (Chelsea
Hertford) peers at him out the window, then runs excitedly to her
mother to announce, ``It's G.I. Joe!'' Elizabeth (Marisa Ryan), 13,
observes over dinner, ``This guy has no hair.''
   ``Major Dad'' is not a show about the military, said executive
producer Earl Pomerantz, who noted, ``I'm a Jewish person from
Canada, and I know nothing about the Marine Corps,'' which he said
he had heretofore thought of not as fodder for comedy, but ``just
guns and sharp things.''
   ``I do `people' shows,'' he told the television critics. ``I
like shows with people in them ... rather than pieces of felt. . ..
That's what we're on against, a piece of felt,'' said Pomerantz,
referring to ``ALF.'' ``It's doing very well.'' ``ALF'' wins its
time period virtually every week.
   Pomerantz created the critically praised but short-lived ``Best
of the West,'' was co-executive producer of ``The Cosby Show'' and
has written for ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' ``Cheers'' and
``Taxi,'' among others. He said it is impossible to sit down and
create a show with the purpose of being a network hit.
   ``In 1984, nobody thought `Cosby' was going to be a hit. ... All
the questions were, how are you going to beat `Magnum, P.I.'? _
such a big hit,'' he said.
   Pomerantz and McRaney, who helped come up with the concept for
``Major Dad,'' think the chemistry between the seemingly mismatched
lovers will charm viewers.
   ``I think a lot of people have a notion of a Marine being about
as far right-wing as you can go without becoming Genghis Khan, and
a lot of other people have the notion that journalists are about as
left-wing as you can go without actually pledging allegiance to the
red flag,'' said McRaney.
   ``So you've got these two extreme differences, and the thing
that we would like to carry out in this show is the notion that you
can have divergent points of view, but we're all in the same game
here. Maybe it's too much of a cliche to say that love conquers
all, but it can conquer a lot.''
   Much of the research for the show was conducted at Camp
Pendleton in California and some outdoor scenes will be filmed
there, said Pomerantz. But most of it is filmed on a soundstage in
front of an audience, some of whom are Marines, he said.
   A Marine Reserve officer is an adviser on the show, and the
extras are real Marines, said Pomerantz, ``because we couldn't get
extras to get a haircut for $35 a day.''
   Marines seem to like the show.
   ``We showed this show to Marines,'' Pomerantz said. ``Actually
we didn't show it, all of a sudden it was bootlegged all over the
camps, and so when we came down there, they were already talking
demographics and can we beat `ALF.'''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   `SPY' CASE FOR NBC _ NBC plans to air what it is billing as a
``playfully irreverent'' special this coming season from the
publishers of Spy Magazine, the New York-based satirical monthly
that pokes fun at and dishes dirt about the rich, famous and
powerful. ... NBC also recently announced that Jim Henson, whose
``The Jim Henson Hour'' didn't make it as a weekly series last
season, will produce a four-hour miniseries for the network based
on ``Gulliver's Travels.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, July 31</NOTE>
