<FIRST>a w PM-DebbieDean     07-28 0894</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Debbie Dean,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday PMs July 31 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Files of Ex-Pierce Lieutenant Cast Light on Her Power At HUD</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At times Deborah Gore Dean's endorsement came
full of enthusiasm.
   ``This is a must! A go! I love this project!'' she said in an
April 1986 note about a proposal for a Department of Housing and
Urban Development grant to help finance a Baltimore project.
   No matter how it was delivered, Ms. Dean's endorsement carried
considerable weight, a fact not lost on HUD and congressional
investigators who question whether the woman who served as former
HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce's top lieutenant was qualified or
authorized to make such decisions at all.
   ``It's amazing to see all the things that she signed, most of
which she had no authority to do,'' said a new official at HUD who
asked not to be identified. ``She does appear to have enjoyed
considerable power.''
   As Pierce's executive assistant, Ms. Dean's job ostensibly was
to push the secretary's agenda and manage the day-to-day affairs of
his office.
   But a review of her files at HUD offers little evidence of a
Pierce agenda and ample evidence that Ms. Dean, whose position
carried no management authority, involved herself in a wide range
of HUD activities _ and considered hers to be the final word.
   Developers, consultants and others who did business with HUD
during Ms. Dean's three years as executive assistant appear to have
agreed with her self-assessment.
   ``We are very appreciative of your assistance in expediting this
matter,'' former HUD Secretary Carla Hills said in a March 1987
note to Ms. Dean thanking her for her intervention on behalf of a
Hills client.
   ``She has proven herself not only very capable of handling
day-to-day administrative matters but also of making the `wheels of
government' turn in an expeditious manner,'' then-Republican Rep.
Trent Lott of Mississippi said in an April 1987 letter to Pierce.
   Ms. Dean is a central figure in the current investigations of
HUD, internal, congressional and Justice Department reviews of
allegations of fraud, mismanagement and political cronyism at the
agency during the Reagan administration. She came to HUD after a
brief stint as an Energy Department aide and prior to that was a
part-time bartender and publisher of a lifestlye magazine.
   The 34-year-old daughter of a prominent Republican family
refused to testify when called before Congress, invoking her Fifth
Amendment right against self-incrimination. She also has declined,
through her attorney, repeated recent requests for interviews.
   She has, according to sources, offered to implicate Pierce in a
number of funding decisions in exhance for a grant of immunity. But
the subcommittee conducting the review has to date balked at the
offer and sought to gather information about Pierce through other
witnesses. There is nothing to indicate any impropriety by Pierce
but such testimony by Ms. Dean would contradict Pierce's earlier
sworn statement that he took no direct role in funding decisions.
   Ms. Dean's files, reviewed under provisions of the Freedom of
Information Act, do indeed contain evidence Pierce was more
involved in certain HUD decisions than he indicated in his
congressional testimony.
   Letters kept by Ms. Dean indicate Pierce intervened on projects
involving jazz musician Lionel Hampton, former GOP Sen. Edward
Brooke of Massachusetts and a Mississippi state lawmaker.
   But more abundant is evidence that those seeking help at HUD saw
Ms. Dean as their problem solver. Equally abundant is evidence that
she went to great lengths to keep in touch with prominent
Republicans and members of the Reagan administration. In between,
she wrote thank-you notes for the chocolates, roses, Teddy Bears
and other gifts given her by associates and admirers.
   The entreaties for help came from an array of sources _
developers, consultants, members of Congress and on occasion the
White House.
   Not all the mail, however, was complimentary.
   ``It is not that I have never been lied to before,'' Rep. Gene
Snyder, R-Kan., said in a 1986 letter to Ms. Dean protesting a
decision affecting a project in his state. ``I have been but not by
my own administration.''
   Also in the files is an angry letter from then-New Hampshire
Gov. John Sununu to Pierce, protesting a newspaper article in which
Ms. Dean was said to have speculated that home prices in the state
would drop if it had an income tax.
   Ms. Dean sent a letter of apology to Sununu and said she had
been misquoted. He is now White House chief of staff.
   Another letter offers evidence that Ms. Dean kept in touch with
former allies at the agency who left to go into HUD-related
business.
   ``I have tried to keep all of the commitments that you made and
that I made to you,'' Ms. Dean said in a 1985 letter to Philip
Abrams, one of a handful of HUD officials who teamed up on a number
of lucrative HUD projects after leaving government.
   In that same letter she wrote of a fight with Shirley McVay
Wiseman, then an assistant secretary at HUD, over a new policy
proposal. ``Shirley is impossible,'' she wrote Abrams.
   Three months later, when Pierce distributed a memo informing
senior staff that Ms. Wiseman was resigning, Ms. Dean could not
control her glee.
   Across the note, in inch-high letters, she scribbled: ``YEAH!''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance PM Monday July 31</NOTE>
</DOC>
