<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1604EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Rural-HeLeft Adv06   07-28 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rural-He Left, Adv 06,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 6, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Down on the Farm? Not After They've Seen TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Rural Crossroads</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHAWNEE MISSION, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At 40, Bill Hoch has been gone from
his parents' Emporia dairy farm half his life, but he says he
carries its early lessons with him every day.
   He believes many of his generation left rural life behind
because they were profoundly influenced by global images conveyed
through mass communications.
   ``All of a sudden we started seeing things from around the
nation, around the world, even from the moon. For our parents that
was the stuff of which daydreams were made, not reality. But for
us, it could become reality.
   ``The mid to late '60s created an enormous, almost magnetic pull
on people like myself, pulling us away from small-town rural life.
The attraction was political, social, artistic, but it all crested
on the wave of the communications revolution.''
   Hoch remembers growing up on the farm and delivering milk to
small towns, country schools and neighborhood farms that no longer
exist.
   ``When you look at rural life and how it's changed in the last
20 years it's easy to get depressed,'' he said. ``I find it
destructive and regrettable that so much has disappeared, because
beyond the economic impact, the loss has created a vacuum.''
   Now a resident of this suburb, Hoch regularly enjoys the
concerts, plays and sporting events Kansas City offers, ``and I'd
be reluctant to give that up. I enjoy the amenities of a city.'' He
says he needs the metropolitan environment for his communications
business.
   But he and his wife, Ellen, visit Emporia frequently. His
hometown, 100 miles southwest of Kansas City, has grown from 15,000
residents when he lived there to about 30,000 today.
   ``There's an enormous sense of stability in knowing my family
still lives on that same 100 acres we've owned for the better part
of a century.''
   Hoch's pet pony, Rusty, died only a few years ago at the age of
35 and was lovingly buried in his corral near the ancestral home. A
baby raccoon he rescued from a city tree was turned loose to roam
free in his parents' pastures. The pull of the place, where wheat
still grows and coming home for Christmas is expected, remains
strong for Bill Hoch.
   ``There used to be dozens of trucks and cars coming and going
every hour to the dairy. Now Mom and Dad go to town once a day and
that's the only dust churned up in the driveway. Even town has
changed. It used to be 10 miles away. Now it's grown so much it's
only three or four miles to the outskirts.''
   Hoch is grateful for the values he learned in his first two
decades on the farm. He credits them as the foundation upon which
he's built his urban life.
   ``I never turned away from the farm, I just physically left. I
wrestled with the choices. On the one hand there were dependable,
stable values and a very predictable way of life. On the other was
the excitment and challenge of the unknown.
   ``I never intended to stay away. I always thought I would go
back. I still think that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 6</NOTE>
