<DOCNO> AP890728-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1721EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv30   07-28 0936</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 30,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 30 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>USDA Says Dairy Outlook Improving As Congress Begins New Farm Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Last year's drought put the squeeze on dairy
farmers, but Agriculture Department analysts say that 1988 milk
production still set a record and that another boost can be
expected this year.
   The brighter outlook for milk producers comes as Congress begins
work to replace the expiring 1985 farm law. The 1990 farm bill, as
its predecessor, will have to contend with dairy price supports,
long a foundation of the industry.
   Relatively high milk prices and falling feed costs are the main
reasons cited by the department's Economic Research Service in a
new dairy outlook report. Despite the bullish view, there are a few
caveats.
   ``The past year may have sapped the financial strength of some
producers,'' the report said. ``Although higher milk prices
compensated producers fairly fully for rises in concentrate (grain)
prices, forage costs in most areas also were sharply higher.
   ``This financial strain may have been particularly acute for
those producers who expanded in late 1988 in spite of the drought
or were somewhat weak financially before the drought.''
   Farm milk prices in the second quarter averaged $12.20 per
hundredweight, up 77 cents from April-June of last year. Cow
slaughter has remained high and growth of milk output per cow has
slipped.
   But analysts said that if dairy farmers can recover quickly from
the recent slump _ as they expect will happen _ total milk output
in 1989 could exceed last year's level by 1 billion to 3 billion
pounds.
   Specifically, the agency forecasts 1989 milk output at 147.2
billion pounds, up from the record of 145.5 billion last year.
   ``The average price received by farmers in June was $12.10 per
hundredweight of milk, up 80 cents from a year earlier and the
highest June price since 1985,'' the report said. ``Thus far in
1989, milk prices have averaged 82 cents more than a year ago.''
   If prices go as expected from here on, the 1989 average of
prices paid to dairy producers would be the highest since the late
1960s, the report said.
   The boost for dairy farmers has not been without its cost to
consumers. Retail prices of dairy products continued ``to post the
largest year-to-year rises of recent years,'' the report said. In
June, the retail dairy index was up 6 percent from a year earlier.
   ``However, year-to-year increases during the second half may not
be as large as during the first half,'' the report added. ``For the
year, retail dairy prices are expected to rise 5 percent to 6
percent, the largest since 1981.''
   Department economists predict that consumer food prices overall
may rise an average of 4 percent to 7 percent in calendar 1989.
   At a House Agriculture Committee hearing July 12, the head of
one of the nation's most effective farm lobbying groups, the
National Milk Producers Federation, said the dairy industry is in
``a vastly different position'' than it was when the current law
was debated four years ago.
   ``Gone are the burgeoning surpluses of dairy products purchased
under the dairy price support program,'' said federation president
Tom Camerlo. ``Gone also is the $2 billion-plus price tag of the
dairy program.''
   Camerlo noted that U.S. milk production and consumption are in
close balance. As a result, he said, USDA has not had to buy any
cheese or non-fat dry milk this year to bolster market prices.
   However, USDA says that there have been heavy butter purchases
by the Commodity Credit Corp. and that some probably will be bought
in the second half of the year.
   According to a review of USDA spending operations, CCC spending
on dairy programs in the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1 will be
about $658 million, which Camerlo said will be ``a far cry from the
$2.1 billion cost'' of the program as recently as 1985.
   One reason for the reduction in dairy program costs has been an
insistence by Congress and the administration to roll back some of
the milk price supports from their record highs of the early 1980s.
   At that time, the high supports and rising production caused CCC
surplus inventories of dairy products to grow, which added to the
costs of operating the program. In 1983, for example, the support
program cost a record $2.7 billion.
   Fees were levied against dairy producers and other steps taken
to ease some of the growing financial burden. And the 1985 farm law
authorized a ``dairy termination program'' to reduce production and
program costs. The $1.8 billion program began April 1, 1986, and
lasted for 18 months, with producers themselves paying about a
third of the cost.
   Under the 18-month DTP, which also was called the ``whole-herd
buyout'' program, the department paid participating farmers to
dispose of entire herds, either through slaughter or export, and to
remain out of dairying for five years. More than 1.6 million dairy
cattle were cut from the U.S. herd.
   A report by the General Accounting Office, an investigative
agency of Congress, said earlier this month that the DTP ``will
reduce milk production from 1986 through 1990 by 39.4 billion
pounds below what it would have been without the program.''
   But the GAO report also said that the dairy buyout ``will not
have a lasting effect on milk production.''
   Thus, the report said, ``it is difficult to predict the benefits
or costs of a similar program that might be used to address future
dairy surplus problems.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 30</NOTE>
