<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nissan employees voted overwhelmingly
against being represented by the United Auto Workers, denying the
union a foothold in the nation's fully Japanese-owned auto plants.
   Employees voted 1,622 to 711 against the UAW at Nissan's sole
U.S. plant, according to results announced Thursday.
   The balloting followed an 18-month drive by the UAW and was seen
as a test of union muscle and a challenge to automakers' strategy
of locating plants in the traditionally anti-union South.
   In Tokyo, Nissan management welcomed the union defeat.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underscoring a consolidation in the drug
industry, Bristol-Myers Co. and Squibb Corp. said they would merge
in an $11 billion stock-swap deal that would create the world's
second-largest pharmaceutical concern.
   Under terms of a definitive agreementapproved by the boards of
both companies, Squibb will be merged into Bristol-Myers through a
tax-free exchange of 2.4 shares of Bristol-Myers common stock for
each Squibb share, the companies said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. economic growth slowed to a lackluster
annual rate of 1.7 percent in the spring while inflation raced
ahead at the fastest pace in more than six years, the government
reported.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the gross national
product, the broadest measure of economic health, turned in its
weakest showing since mid-1986 as growth was held back by a slump
in auto sales and housing construction.
</TEXT>
