its 31,000 salaried workers by year's end as part of $1 billion
cost-cutting program mandated by sagging sales and a changing
market, Chairman Lee Iacocca said.
   The cuts announced Thursday were billed as part of a long-term
effort to make the third-largest U.S. automaker more competitive.
</TEXT>
