<DOCNO> AP890728-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Discovery-Scrambling     07-28 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Discovery-Scrambling,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Discovery Channel Latest to Scramble Signal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Discovery Channel will become the latest
cable TV programmer to scramble its satellite-delivered signal to
fend off video pirates, a company official said.
   The Landover, Md.-based company will begin scrambling its signal
June 30, 1990, said Sandy McGovern, senior vice president of
affiliate sales and relations.
   So-called basic cable services such as CNN Headline News, ESPN
and USA Network already are scrambling their signals, as are pay
cable services such as Home Box Office, Cinemax, Showtime-The Movie
Channel and The Disney Channel.
   Backyard satellite dish owners and cable TV systems must have
proper equipment to decode the scrambled signals.
   McGovern said Thursday the company did not know how much
business it was losing to theft. But she said it counts 43 million
paying subscribers, while the A.C. Nielsen ratings company reports
``a few million'' more homes than that are watching.
   ``So we know there's some fairly significant theft,'' she said.
   Scrambling began in January 1986 when HBO first encoded its
signal. More cable companies followed suit, much to the dismay of
backyard satellite dish owners, many of whom paid about $2,000 for
their equipment.
   Congress passed the Satellite Home Viewer Copyright Act last
year, guaranteeing access to the scrambled signals to backyard dish
owners as long as they have paid for them.
   The law was a boon to a new group of cable TV middlemen who put
together packages of cable channels and sell them to satellite dish
owners for monthly or yearly fees.
   Despite the scrambling, however, the cable industry claims it
still loses millions of dollars to illegal decoding devices.
   The Discovery Channel, which began service in June 1985, offers
non-fiction entertainment in the areas of nature, science,
technology, history and exploration.
   It typically is provided to cable subscribers as part of basic
packages of cable channels, with the cable system operator paying
The Discovery Channel a fee per subscriber.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Visa-MCI     07-28 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Visa-MCI,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Visa, MCI Announce Credit Card Service</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Peirce, 4th graf, is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Visa cardholders have moved closer to the day
when a single piece of plastic will enable them to conduct nearly
any kind of business, including long-distance calls.
   Visa U.S.A and MCI Communications Corp. announced Thursday that
beginning Oct. 1, Visa card account numbers also will serve as MCI
long-distance calling numbers.
   Holders of Visa cards will be able to call from any telephone in
the United States to nearly anywhere in the world, with monthly
charges billed as one line on their Visa accounts.
   MCI will provide a separate, itemized billing.
   Roger Peirce, Visa's chief operating officer, said the MCI link
``represents a significant market opportunity and moves us closer
to Visa's goal of providing customers one card for all payment
needs.''
   Tim Price, MCI's vice president for sales, said the service will
be phased in over the next 18 months, with participating banks
representing 30 million cardholders scheduled to come into the
system by the end of 1989.
   By the end of 1990, the service will be available automatically
to any Visa cardholder, Price said.
   ``We'll be able to place ads saying `If you have a Visa card you
already have an MCI calling card,'' Price said.
   Major credit card companies already allow callers at some
airport pay phones and airplane phones to use credit cards, in bids
to grab larger shares of the credit business.
   The nation's largest long-distance company, American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co., confirmed in May that it was considering converting
its 40 million calling cards into general credit cards.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in May that AT&amp;T had reached an
agreement with Total Systems Services Inc., the nation's second
largest processor of credit card transactions. Total Systems would
not confirm the story.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said Thursday that AT&amp;T still is
exploring several options, including using the calling card as a
general charge card, but he said no final determination has been
made.
   Bert C. Roberts Jr., MCI's president and chief operating
officer, called the link with Visa ``one of the largest service
integration pacts involving two distinct customer bases and
operating systems.''
   An an incentive to cardholders, MCI will provide new customers
with 30 free minutes of long-distance calls for each MCI calling
service they subscribe to through VisaPhone.
   Cardholders will pay no enrollment or service fees for the
VisaPhone services.
   Initially, the service will be limited to Visa classic, gold and
business cardholders in the United States. Eventually, VisaPhone
will be available to 120 million Visa cardholders in the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
