<FIRST>r f PM-EntertainmentGizmos     07-28 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Entertainment Gizmos,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Progress Reported in Advanced Television, Digital Audio Tape</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Hold for release Friday AMs; time set by source.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress has been reported in the development of
the next two gizmos in the world of consumer electronics:
high-definition television and digital audio tape.
   Record companies and consumer electronics manufacturers
announced Thursday in London, as expected, that they had agreed on
a system that clears the way for introduction of digital audio
tape, or DAT, players in the United States.
   The players will permit people to make digital copies of music
from sources such as compact disc players, but they will not be
able to make digital copies of the copies.
   That is intended to prevent piracy through wholesale, high-speed
copying of digitally recorded music.
   ``The proposal for a technical restriction on unlimited DAT
copying establishes an important precedent for the protection of
intellectual property,'' Jason Berman, the president of the
Recording Industry Association of America, said in a statement.
   On high-definition television, progress in an interim step known
as advanced television was revealed by NBC, Thomson Consumer
Electronics Inc. and the David Sarnoff Research Center.
   French-owned Thomson, which makes RCA- and GE-branded television
sets, demonstrated the first wide-screen picture tube designed for
advanced television receivers. It said it would invest $75 million
in its Marion, Ind., plant to produce the new wide screens, which
have a 33 percent bigger width-to-height ratio than conventional
sets, as well as bigger conventional screens.
   NBC said it had conducted the first UHF broadcast of an advanced
television signal and the first cable transmission test of the
signal, which it calls ACTV 1.
   NBC also said it plans to test advanced television production
equipment by shooting news and sports _ including a New York Jets
football game this fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Airlines     07-28 0814</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Airlines,0841</SECOND>
<HEAD>United, Delta, USAir Profits Rise, Midway Earnings Fall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp., United Airlines' parent company, said its
second-quarter profit rose nearly 14 percent from a year earlier,
while Delta Air Lines' net income soared 85 percent, boosted by
business it picked up from strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   USAir Group said Thursday its second-quarter earnings rose 9
percent and Midway Airlines Inc. said its net income tumbled 48
percent from a year earlier.
   For the second quarter ended June 30, UAL had net income of $141
million, or $6.52 per share, up from $124 million, or $5.77 a
share, for the same period a year ago. Revenue of the Chicago-based
company rose to $2.5 billion from $2.3 billion.
   The company, which has been the object of heavy takeover
speculation in the stock market during recent weeks, also announced
that its board of directors amended UAL's ``poison pill''
antitakeover plan to make it tougher for a hostile bidder to buy
the company.
   Delta's fourth-quarter profit was $190.8 million, or $3.87 a
share, up from $103.3 million, or $2.11 a share, in the same period
last year. Revenue totaled $2.31 billion, up from $1.9 billion a
year ago.
   USAir reported net earnings of $100.7 million, or $2.29 a share
in the second-quarter, up from $92.5 million, or $2.14 a share, in
the same 1988 period. Revenue rose 16 percent to $1.7 billion from
$1.5 billion last year.
   Midway Airlines' net earnings fell 48 percent to $5.1 million,
or 46 cents a share, in the second quarter from $9.7 million, or 87
cents a share, a year ago. Revenue rose to $126.5 million from
$111.5 million.
   UAL reported higher operating expenses and declines in both
revenue passengers and revenue-passenger miles, resulting in a 1
percent drop in operating earnings.
   Spokesman Rob Doughty said he did not know how the crash last
week of a United jetliner in Sioux City, Iowa, would affect UAL's
third-quarter results. ``There would be expenses, of course, but we
really haven't seen an impact on revenue so far,'' he said.
   UAL's original shareholder rights plan, adopted in 1986, granted
shareholders the right, in the event of a threatened takeover, to
purchase for $185 one one-hundredth of a share of a new series of
junior participating preferred stock and two shares of common stock
for each share of common stock they already owned. The amended plan
changes the common-stock ratio to three for one.
   Such plans typically are used to make a hostile takeover
prohibitively expensive by creating more stock for a suitor to
acquire.
   UAL's stock has risen sharply in the past month on takeover
speculation. Doughty declined to comment on takeover rumors.
   UAL reported a 71 percent drop in net income for the first six
months of 1989 to $206.5 million, or $9.55 a share, from $701
million, or $19.12 a share, in the year-earlier period.
   The 1988 results included a $549 million one-time gain from
UAL's sale of its Westin Hotel Co.
   First-half revenue rose to $4.8 billion from $4.3 billion in
first-half 1988.
   Delta Air Lines said the strike by Eastern Airlines employees,
now in its fifth month, increased business for the Atlanta-based
carrier and contributed to record fourth-quarter earnings.
   ``Traffic in the last four months of the fiscal year was
inflated by a strike against a major Delta competitor, but traffic
also grew strongly in markets not directly affected by the
strike,'' said Thomas J. Roeck, Delta's senior vice president for
finance and chief financial officer.
   Hartsfield Atlanta International Airport was Eastern's largest
hub prior to the March 4 walkout by Machinists, pilots and flight
attendants, and is the center of the Miami-based airline's
rebuilding effort.
   Eastern was virtually grounded during the early days of the
strike by its pilots, flight attendants and Machinists unions.
   For its fiscal year ended June 30, Delta posted a profit of
$460.9 million, or $9.37 a share, up 50 percent from $306.8
million, or $6.30 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 17 percent
to $8.1 billion from $6.9 billion in the previous year.
   USAir, based in Arlington, Va., had first-half income of $116.2
million, or $2.65 a share, up 58 percent from year-earlier results
of $73.7 million, or $1.70 a share. First-half revenue rose to $3.2
billion, up from $2.7 billion.
   Strong traffic results by both USAir and Piedmont helped offset
softer yields stemming promotional fares, such as its Kids Fly Free
programs and reduced fares in the California markets, the company
said.
   USAir acquired Piedmont Aviation in 1987 and plans to merge with
the airline on Aug. 5.
   For the first six months of the year, Chicago-based Midway said
its net income grew 83 percent to $8 million, or 72 cents a share,
from $4.4 million, or 41 cents a share. Revenue was 21 percent
higher at $243.7 million, compared with $201.1 million in the 1988
period.
</TEXT>
