<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OilMop Bjt   07-28 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Mop, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Louisiana Company Cleans Up on Alaskan Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's been called ``black gold,'' and for a
little company in Louisiana, the thousands of gallons of oil that
the Exxon tanker Valdez spilled into Alaska's Prince William Sound
have proven to be just that.
   Oil Mop Inc., which makes systems to clean up, soak up and
remove oil from water, says its profits have increased sharply and
that it expects to make $4 million this year, double the 1988
figure.
   It has boosted permanent employees from 15 to 50 and hired an
additional 50 temporary workers, and announced plans to expand its
manufacturing facility by 80 percent.
   ``There's no doubt about it. The cleanup operation in Alaska is
the reason we're booming,'' said General Manager Wallace Landry.
   Exxon disclosed earlier this week that its estimated cleanup
cost for the March 24 spill would total $1.28 billion, making it
one of the most expensive industrial accidents in history.
   The giant oil company said the figure represented the price for
3,000 workers running hundreds of vessels and pumping equipment in
Alaska.
   Landry said Oil Mop is one of at least 100 small companies that
have benefited from the cleanup operation. In Louisiana, where the
depressed oil-based economy has hurt many companies, the spill has
been a boon.
   ``A lot of equipment and people that probably would not be
working right now are employed because of the spill. It will end,
of course, but I would envision staying in a pretty fast-paced mode
for at least another two months,'' Landry said.
   Companies that supply tow boats, pumps and generators, as well
as service and catering companies, are all busy, Landry said.
   Oil Mop, founded in 1970, is not new to the job of cleaning up
major spills. The company helped clean up the Ixtoc I well blowout
on Mexico's Bay of Campeche in 1979, which spewed 100 million
gallons of crude and ranks with the Exxon spill as one of the worst
oil disasters.
   Oil Mop's technicians had to recover diesel fuel from beneath
three feet of ice to clean up a spill in Nome, Alaska. When a
tanker went aground in the St. Lawrence Seaway, the company
recovered 100,000 gallons of oil in seven days.
   The Oil Mop system uses a rope made of a fiber that attracts oil
and repels water. An engine pulls the rope across the water surface
then and between rollers that squeeze the recovered oil into a
container.
   ``It's really simple,'' Landry said. ``The rope goes out for 100
feet or so and then it's pulled back through grandma's old fashion
wringer.''
   The company's manufacturing operation is running three shifts,
24 hours a day, to meet the demand for its products. The fiber is
whirled around special looms to form the mops and then attached to
10 and 15 foot sections of rope. The ropes are then strung together
in 100 foot lengths. Oil Mop is shipping thousands of feet of the
rope mops and dozens of wringer mop engines and wringers to Alaska.
   Oil Mop plans to work in the oil industry program, Petroleum
Industry Response Organization, which is being designed to take
aggressive action in preventing oil spills, responding to oil
spills and conducting spill-related research.
   In addition, the program will provide the equipment in the event
of a major oil spill. The anticipated initial outlay for the plan
will be $70 million to $100 million, plus annual maintenance of
between $30 million and $100 million. Oil Mop expects to get part
of that.
   ``The oil spill business is a funny business. I guess you could
say one company's poison is our meat. We've shown that we can
respond to a client's needs. With the new attention any spill is
going to get, you'd better be able to do that. If you can, it pays
off,'' Landry said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
