<FIRST>r f PM-Paramount-Associates     07-28 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paramount-Associates,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Selling The Associates to Ford For $3.35 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. has completed its
transformation from a conglomerate to a media company with the sale
of its financial services arm, The Associates, to Ford Motor Co.
for $3.35 billion.
   Paramount said in a statement Thursday the sale would give it an
after-tax gain of $1.3 billion. When the company announced plans to
sell The Associates in April, it said it planned to use the money
to finance acquisitions.
   Thursday's announcement came three days after Paramount, having
failed in its attempt to stop the merger of Time Inc. and Warner
Communications Inc., dropped its $12.2 billion hostile bid for
Time. Paramount said then that it remained committed to expanding
its publishing and entertainment businesses through mergers,
acquisitions, joint ventures or partnerships.
   The purchase marks the latest expansion of Ford's financial
services segment. Ford, the nation's second-largest automaker after
General Motors Corp., owns First Nationwide Bank, one of the
nation's biggest savings and loan institutions. First Nationwide,
with federal assistance, bailed out two failing Michigan thrifts
late last year.
   The Associates is the third-largest independent finance company
in the United States, with assets of nearly $14 billion. It has a
wide range of consumer finance services, and its principal
commercial business is in heavy-duty truck and trailer financing.
   The Associates was the last asset that Paramount _ formerly
known as Gulf &amp; Western Inc. _ put on the block as part of Chairman
Martin Davis' plan to change the company into an entertainment and
publishing empire.
   Gulf &amp; Western embraced a wide variety of businesses when Davis
became chairman in 1983, including sugar, zinc, chemicals, energy
products, race tracks, Kayser-Roth apparel and hosiery, Simmons
bedding and automotive, electronic and construction products.
   Davis pared the company to its core media businesses, among them
Paramount Pictures and Television, and publishers Simon &amp; Schuster
and Prentice Hall.
   The Associates' chairman, Reece A. Overcash Jr., will continue
in that post and will report to Kenneth Whipple, head of Ford's
Financial Services Group, Ford said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
