<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TelephoneDumping     07-28 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Telephone Dumping,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce Dept. Says Asian Nations Dumping Business Phones Here</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department says a preliminary
investigation showed manufacturers in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea
were ``dumping'' small-business telephone equipment in the United
States at prices far below their fair value.
   In a preliminary finding Thursday that could lead to hefty
antidumping duties on these phone products, the department's
International Trade Administration said equipment prices in Japan
were as much as 2{ times higher than the prices being charged in
the United States for comparable equipment.
   The U.S. International Trade Commission in February also made a
preliminary determination that the three nations' practices had
harmed U.S. manufacturers.
   Dumping is a practice in which overseas companies sell their
products in other countries at prices near or below cost in order
to force their way into a market. The difference between the
average domestic and average foreign prices of a product is called
the margin and is expressed as a percent.
   Companies found guilty of dumping must pay the margin in the
form of duties collected by the U.S. Customs Service to bring the
cost of the imported item up to its fair market value.
   The ITA established the following margins for Japanese
companies: Toshiba Corp., 136.77 percent; Matsushita, 178.93
percent and all others, 157.85 percent.
   For Taiwan, the companies and margins were: Taiwan Nitsuko,
129.73 percent; Sun Moon Star, 0 percent; and all others, 129.73
percent.
   For South Korea, they were: Samsung, 9.33 percent; Goldstar,
6.09 percent; and all others, 7.79 percent.
   After notice of the ITA finding is published in the Federal
Register _ a process that may take about five days _ antidumping
duties will be levied on the products.
   But the duties will be held in escrow pending a final
determination by the ITA, which is expected by about Oct. 10, and
pending a separate final determination by the International Trade
Commission.
   The ITC must find that U.S. businesses were injured by the
dumping, and a final determination is expected by mid-November, ITC
spokesman Jim Craig said.
   The U.S. investigation was prompted by a complaint filed in
December by American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. and Condial Corp.
   AT&amp;T claimed it and other U.S. phone manufacturers had been
injured by unfair pricing practices of 12 manufacturers in the
three countries.
   AT&amp;T spokesman Herb Linnen said the ITA finding ``represents
major progress on the way to the ultimate result AT&amp;T seeks _ the
elimination of unfair pricing in the United States.''
   AT&amp;T said the foreign manufacturers had captured about 60
percent of the U.S. market for small business phone systems,
growing from about 40 percent in three years. AT&amp;T and its U.S.
competitors claimed their business in that area had declined
dramatically in the interim.
   The ITA said imports of certain small-business phone systems and
subassemblies from Japan in 1988 were valued at $775.7 million;
from Taiwan, $342 million; and from South Korea, $227 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
