<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0735EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-FarmScene     07-28 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0913</SECOND>
<HEAD>Larger Soybean Crop Means Lower Grower Prices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A much larger soybean crop will mean lower
prices for growers but some relief for users, according to a new
Agriculture Department report.
   The department's Economic Research Service said Thursday the
assessment was based on the July 12 estimate of 61.3 million acres
planted to soybeans this year and a projected harvest of 1.95
billion bushels, up 27 percent from 1988 output.
   Analysts said the soybean crush in 1989-90 could climb to 1.115
billion bushels from 1.07 billion expected for 1988-89.
   Soybeans are crushed by processors into high-protein meal for
livestock feed and oil for cooking and other food use.
   ``Exports, too, should rise next year, but at a forecast 600
million bushels will lag the larger volumes of the early 1980s,''
the report said.
   By the end of the next marketing year, Aug. 31, 1990, soybean
inventories are expected to be about 265 million bushels, up from
125 million bushels at the beginning of the season, Sept. 1.
   As a result of the larger crop this year, soybean market prices
are expected to decline to an average of $4.75 to $6.25 per bushel
in 1989-90 from an estimated $7.35 this season.
   The larger soybean crush in 1989-90 ``will allow the United
States to maintain soybean meal exports'' at the current level of
about 5.5 million tons and still meet an expected increase in
domestic demand, the report said.
   Soybean meal prices may drop to an average of $140 to $180 per
ton in 1989-90 from this year's estimated $230 per ton.
   However, burdensome supplies of soybean oil will keep year-end
inventories at above 2 billion pounds for the third straight year.
Domestic oil use has lagged because ``substitute oils have been
widely available and aggressively priced,'' the report said.
   Exports of soybean oil in 1989-90 could be slightly below this
year's 1.43 billion pounds and will be shipped mostly under U.S.
assistance programs.
   Looking at other oilseeds, the report said peanut plantings of
1.68 million acres are expected to produce 4.5 billion pounds of
peanuts this year, up from 1.66 million acres and 3.98 billion
pounds in 1988.
   Domestic food use of peanuts is expected to reach a record of
2.25 billion pounds this season, based on strong increases for
peanut butter and salted nuts, the report said. Peanut exports are
projected at 650 million pounds.
   Sunflower plantings are down 12 percent from last year to about
1.82 million acres. Even so, sunflower seed production is projected
at 1.05 million metric tons (of 2,205 pounds each), up 205,000 tons
from last year's drought-stricken crop.
   Corn oil production for 1988-89 is estimated at 1.5 billion
pounds, up 5 percent from last season, the report said.
   Domestic use is expected to increase 13 percent to 1.2 billion
pounds, but exports are forecast to decline 10 percent to 331
million pounds. Corn oil production in 1989-90 is forecast at 1.55
billion pounds, up 3 percent from this year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the war
against foliage-eating gypsy moths has gained in Oregon but has
lost ground in North Carolina and Utah.
   James W. Glosser, administrator of the department's Animal and
Plant Health Inspection Service, said Thursday that Oregon has been
removed from the gypsy moth quarantine list because the pest has
been eradicated from Lane County, which had been the insect's
toehold in the state.
   Federal quarantine regulations restrict the interstate movement
of outdoor household articles _ lawn furniture and certain camping
equipment, for example _ that might harbor moths and spread them to
other states.
   ``Based on treatments and subsequent surveys, we have determined
that (the) gypsy moth no longer occurs in Lane County and that
there is no further need to restrict the movement of outdoor
household articles from this area.''
   Lane County was the only quarantined area in Oregon, so the
state has been removed from USDA's official list of gypsy moth
states.
   Meanwhile, Glosser's agency is designating all or portions of
Currituck and Dare counties in North Carolina as gypsy moth
``low-risk'' areas, thus adding North Carolina to the list.
   Glosser said inspectors have found the counties are infested by
the moths but that the number of egg masses per acre is not high
enough for them to be rated as high-risk areas.
   By agency reckoning, an area is high-risk when it has more than
50 masses of moth eggs per acre.
   Glosser said a portion of Salt Lake County, Utah, is a high-risk
area and that this adds the state to the moth list.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter has
announced two more appointments to senior-level jobs in the
Agriculture Department:
   _Ann M. Veneman, deputy undersecretary for international affairs
and commodity programs. Since 1987, she has been associate
administrator of the Foreign Agricultural Service in the department.
   _Gary K. Madson, deputy assistant secretary for congressional
affairs. He has been director of congressional affairs for the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission, and before that was a
congressional aide, including the staff of former Rep. Cooper
Evans, R-Iowa, who is a White House special assistant for
agriculture.
   The jobs each pay $78,600 a year, the department said Thursday.
</TEXT>
