<DOCNO> AP890728-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0738EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Nissan-UAW Bjt   07-28 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-UAW, Bjt,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Reject Union Due to Expansion Plans, Honeymoon, Analysts
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at Nissan's Smyrna plant
rejected the United Auto Workers by a 2-1 margin because of
expansion plans and a continuing ``honeymoon'' period with the
company, industry and labor analysts say.
   Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. U.S.A. workers voted 1,622-711
to keep the union out, officials announced Thursday. The UAW has
not organized any of the three fully Japanese-owned auto plants in
the United States.
   ``I think there's certain peculiarities to the Nissan situation
that contributed to this vote. The one that stands out is Nissan's
planned expansion, adding 1,800 or so jobs,'' said Harley Shaiken,
a labor relations professor at the University of California at San
Diego.
   ``I think that expansion tends to diffuse some of the
discontent. People who have trouble with their job today can
perhaps look forward to a promotion tomorrow with that kind of
expansion,'' Shaiken said.
   The company recently announced it would expand the capacity of
the plant to 440,000 vehicles a year from the current 265,000,
making it the largest single auto assembly plant in the country.
The plant has 3,200 employees, including 2,400 hourly workers who
were eligible to vote.
   David Cole, an industry expert at the University of Michigan,
said he was surprised by the vote margin, but noted that the plant
opened only six years ago. He said that isn't much time to build
ill will.
   ``There's still a bit of a honeymoon period. ... These plants
are comparatively new, and there's still about a third of the labor
force that's got problems with the system,'' said Cole, director of
the Office for Study of Automotive Transportation at the
university's Transportation Research Institute.
   Worker safety and assembly line speeds had emerged as the two
major issues in the UAW's 18-month campaign to organize the plant
that began making light pickup trucks in 1983. The plant also makes
Sentra cars, and a third _ as yet unannounced _ model will be added
when the expansion is completed in 1991.
   ``I guess the UAW didn't make its case inside the plant. I
imagine they'll keep trying, but if an effort like this fails, they
won't have much luck at other Japanese plants,'' said David Healey,
an analyst for Drexel Burnham Lambert in New York.
   Wages at the Nissan plant in Smyrna range from $11.10 to $15.74
an hour plus $1.45-an-hour guaranteed bonuses. Other bonuses are
tied to quality and financial performance. That is slightly lower
than wage rates at UAW plants, but the cost of living is low in
central Tennessee.
   Many workers at the $760 million plant 25 miles southeast of
Nashville have embraced the company's Japanese-style management, in
which they have a say in production and the shop floor is organized
into teams whose members rotate tasks as often as every two hours.
   Worker Redgie Gentry said a union would have been an end to the
teamwork.
   ``It was like someone was trying to divide our family,'' he said.
   The UAW accused Nissan of misrepresentation and intimidation to
keep out the union, including ``captive audience'' meetings and a
barrage of anti-union videos.
   In a statement, UAW President Owen Bieber and other union
officials said the election demonstrated that when a company was
``willing to use threats and misrepresentation to an unlimited
extent, that company can delay if not escape its day of reckoning.''
   Jerry Benefield, president of Nissan Motor Manufacturing U.S.A.,
denied the charges.
   ``I think the results of this election are very strong support
for the participatory management philosophy here at the company and
we're very happy we're going to continue that,'' Benefield said.
   Nissan offers many benefits not seen in many manufacturer
workplaces.
   Workers can lease Nissan cars and trucks at a discount; exercise
at a fitness center and a recreational facility that includes
tennis courts, a golf driving range and swimming pools; and put
away tax-free dollars in a 401(K) plan in which the company matches
employee contributions.
   Some analysts said the vote will keep the union out for some
time, but Cornell University labor relations professor Harry Katz
didn't think so.
   ``The UAW says you can get the flexibility with the cooperation.
But they've got to convince management to make that choice. So I
don't think they're doomed,'' Katz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
