<FIRST>r f PM-TaxBill Bjt   07-28 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tax Bill, Bjt,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Votes Restrictions on Cellular Phone Tax Writeoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House tax-writers are looking no farther than
the halls outside their closed meeting room to find $5 million a
year for a new tax break for a few corporations.
   The target: the cellular telephone favored by the lobbyists,
accounting firm representatives, paralegals and even a few of the
reporters who fill the halls any time the Ways and Means Committee
considers tax legislation.
   The committee, still adding pieces to a catchall tax bill that
originated as a deficit-reduction measure, voted Thursday to make
it more difficult to claim a tax deduction for cellular phones.
   Present law permits a partial writeoff for depreciation of
cellular phones used partially for business. Thus, if a lawyer uses
a phone 30 percent of the time for business, 30 percent of the cost
may be deducted.
   Committee aides said there is evidence some corporations and
individuals abuse the deduction by claiming personal calls as a
business expense.
   Under the committee amendment, no deduction will be permitted
unless more than 50 percent of the use is for business; the user
will have to keep records to substantiate the use. The same rule
already applies to cars and personal computers.
   The restriction was approved to pay for an amendment by Rep. Guy
Vander Jagt, R-Mich., that would save money for a few U.S.
corporations whose income is earned entirely in a foreign country.
Because the government is out of money, the panel requires that any
new tax cut be offset by a tax increase on somebody else.
   Vander Jagt's amendment was one of several added to a proposal
by Chairman Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., that simplifies the corporate
minimum tax. That levy was created to ensure that profit-making
corporations pay some tax even if their deductions and credits are
big enough to wipe out their regular liability.
   In another voice vote Thursday, the committee added to the bill
a permanent extension of the Reagan-era Caribbean Basin Initiative,
which temporarily granted tariff-free treatment of certain imports
from that region. The proposal also extends the preferential
treatment for the first time to apparel and other textile products.
   The CBI changes would guarantee that Caribbean countries would
be able to export as much sugar to the United States as they are
allowed to under existing quotas this year. Any reduction in total
U.S. imports of sugar would have to be borne by nations outside the
Caribbean.
   Meantime, Rostenkowski continued to delay a vote on reducing the
tax on individual capital gains. A majority _ 13 Republicans and
six Democrats _ of the panel supports a temporary reduction in the
tax, which applies to stocks and other assets.
   President Bush has called for a cut to spur the economy and to
raise revenues. Most Democrats oppose the cut on grounds it would
lose money after a year or two and because 80 percent of the tax
cut would go to those with incomes above $100,000 a year.
   Rostenkowski and House Speaker Thomas S. Foley have been
appealing to fellow Democrats to oppose a reduction. But as a
fallback, the two leaders are weighing a counterproposal that would
continue taxing capital gains at the same rates that apply to wages
and other income but to ``index'' capital gains so that profits
caused solely by inflation are not taxed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
