<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Consumers     07-28 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Consumers,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers Groups: Eastern Airlines Ticket May Be No Bargain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines says concerns expressed by
consumer groups that the carrier is using inexperienced pilots and
scheduling phantom flights are silly.
   Jim Ashlock, a spokesman for the strike-bound airline, dismissed
questions raised Thursday by three national consumer groups and
said the airline is following all Federal Aviation Administration
requirements in rebuilding its service.
   Public Citizen, the Airline Consumer Action Group and the
National Consumer League accused Eastern of hiring too many
inexperienced pilots, scheduling ``phantom flights'' that never
take off, generating excessive complaints and failing to give
refunds.
   ``The bottom line is that the flying public has a right to know
what's going on _ that they may be flying with an inexperienced
crew, that they are not getting much of a bargain flying Eastern,''
said Linda Golodner of the consumer league, a private non-profit
membership organization that promotes consumer and worker welfare.
   She endorsed a nine-page statement by Public Citizen, which
takes pro-consumer stands on a wide variety of issues, and the
airline consumer group.
   ``We're providing information travelers have to take into
account to decide for themselves whether to fly Eastern,'' said
Cornish Hitchcock, spokesman for Public Citizen.
   He said a major concern was that some Eastern flights would use
both an inexperienced pilot and copilot in the same cockpit,
contrary to FAA recommendations that at least one pilot have more
than 100 hours of experience on the type of aircraft to be flown.
   ``These are the silliest things I've ever heard,'' Ashlock said.
   Eastern planned to increase from 225 to 390 daily flights Aug.
1, but Ashlock said from Miami that the number would be held to
about 350 until mid-August because of the inability to get enough
pilots through training.
   Before the strike began March 4, the airline flew about 1,000
flights a day.
   Ashlock acknowledged that the airline has ``zeroed out'' some
scheduled flights by stopping ticket sales, but he said it was only
done to protect consumer on flights where crews likely would not be
available.
   He said the high number of complaints recorded by the
Transportation Department in a report earlier this month does not
reflect current problems but stems from the immediate aftermath of
the strike when Machinists, pilots and flight attendants walked off
the job, leading the airline to file for reorganization under
bankruptcy laws.
   The bankruptcy court has power over ticket refunds, Ashlock
said, adding that the airline is following all FAA requirements in
training and assigning pilots.
   ``We wouldn't want to break any FAA rules and we couldn't if we
did want to,'' Ashlock said.
   Hitchcock, at a Public Citizen news conference, said passengers
should be aware that a bankruptcy court decision earlier this month
setting up a $5 million reimbursement fund for travel agents may be
acting as an incentive for agents to sell Eastern tickets.
   The agreement, he said, requires that Eastern increase the fund
only if agents sell more than $3.6 million in Eastern tickets each
week.
   ``From a passenger's standpoint ... this agreement raises
serious conflict of interest issues,'' Hitchcock said.
</TEXT>
