<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DC-10Engine     07-28 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Engine,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Scrap Parts Were Used in United DC-10 Engine, GE Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. says the engine that
apparently failed in a United Airlines jet crash in Iowa could not
have been made with scrap parts from an Air Force plane.
   Dwight Weber, a spokesman at the GE plant in suburban Cincinnati
that built the DC-10's three CF6-6 engines, on Thursday rejected a
suggestion by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., that GE may have used old
parts in new production engines.
   ``The parts Dingell refers to, we can categorically say, were
not used in the Flight 232 engine,'' Weber said. ``GE does not use
recycled parts in new production engines. However, repaired parts
are commonly used in overhauled engines.''
   Dingell, in a letter Wednesday, asked the Federal Aviation
Administration to investigate whether scrap parts were used in the
tail engine of the United jet that crashed July 19 at Sioux City,
Iowa, killing 111 people.
   Dingell chairs a House Energy and Commerce subcomittee that
oversees such investigations.
   Weber said the fan section parts of the engine that failed on
United Flight 232 are not interchangeable with fan parts from the
GE-manufactured TF-39 engine which powers the Air Force's C-5A
aircraft.
   ``The TF-39 parts wouldn't fit in the CF6-6,'' Weber said.
   GE said the CF6-6 engine, produced from 1971 to 1981 for use
specifically on DC-10 series 10 craft such as the crashed United
jet, has established a reliable safety record during 17 million
hours of commercial flight.
   Dingell's letter asks a response from the FAA by Aug. 4. Dingell
told reporters Thursday in Washington that he is not making
allegations against manufacturers, but wants a government
assessment of the issue.
   ``We're simply following up on an inquiry we made to the FAA
several years ago in which we asked them to look into the problems
of spare parts. We have no information, and are making no
allegations, about the behavior of any manufacturer,'' Dingell said.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigator Jack Young was
at GE's Evendale plant Thursday to examine GE's manufacturing
records for the No. 2 engine of Flight 232. Federal investigators
want to know why the engine's fan section disintegrated about 45
minutes into the flight from Denver to Chicago, NTSB spokesman Ted
Lopatkiewicz said. The NTSB investigation was to continue today.
   Lopatkiewicz said wreckage of the engine is to be transported,
probably next week, from the Iowa crash site to GE Evendale for a
thorough, tear-down examination under NTSB supervision.
   Lopatkiewicz said the No. 2 engine's fan section was missing
from the wreckage.
   Weber also said a different generation of GE's CF6 series
engines powered a Korean Air DC-10 jet which crashed early Thursday
in heavy fog short of the airport in Tripoli, Libya, reportedly
killing at least 75 of the 200 people on board. The Korean plane
was powered by GE's CF6-50 engines, a higher-thrust model which
entered commercial service in October 1972, Weber said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
