<DOCNO> AP890728-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0759EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Earns-Autos     07-28 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-Autos,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford, GM Point to Incentives For Earnings Dip</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chrysler Cuts, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos DT1-2 of July 27</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's two largest automakers in part
blamed their own costly incentive programs for shaving profits in
the second quarter.
   General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. on Thursday reported
earnings slipped 3.9 percent and 15.6 percent, respectively,
compared with the year-ago period.
   ``With all the incentives and the slower sales in the United
States, it was anticipated,'' said analyst Joshua Harari of
Standard &amp; Poors Corp. of New York.
   As the quarter began, both companies broadened their incentive
programs, featuring higher cash rebates and lower financing rates
than previously offered.
   The incentives continued through the quarter and could run at
least through the end of the model year, usually noted on Sept. 30.
   Chrysler Corp., which has rebates or low-interest financing
deals on nearly all of its cars and trucks, is scheduled to
announce its second-quarter results on Monday.
   GM earned $1.45 billion, or $2.23 a share, during the three
months ended June 30, compared with $1.51 billion, or $2.26 a share
during the same time last year.
   GM's revenue, including sales by the GM Hughes Electronics
Corp., Electronic Data Systems Corp. and General Motors Acceptance
Corp. subsidiaries that reported earnings Wednesday, rose 1.3
percent during the quarter to $33.6 billion, from $33.18 billion
last year.
   Ford reported it earned $1.4 billion, or $3 a share, compared
with $1.66 billion, or $3.43 a share in the second quarter last
year.
   Ford's revenue rose to $25.9 billion during the quarter, from
$24.96 billion in the same period last year.
   Earnings from Ford's financial services group fell 19.9 percent
to $173 million, due to lower net interest margins, the company
said.
   Ford's U.S. profits softened due to expensive incentive programs
and reduced profit margins, said David McCammon, the company's vice
president for finance and treasurer.
   He said incentives during the second quarter cost Ford between
$600 and $700 a vehicle, up sharply from the $200 to $300 average
cost per vehicle during the previous quarter and the second quarter
of last year.
   GM spokesman Terry Sullivan said per-car incentive costs for the
quarter were unavailable. However, GM spent about $715 per car last
year on incentives and said costs for the programs would be higher
this year, he said.
   Chrysler Motors Corp. Chairman Bennett Bidwell, who oversees the
company's vehicle-making arm, said the nation's No. 3 automaker
spends about $700 per vehicle in incentives.
   The buyer enticements are a double threat to automakers'
profits. When sales slump, profits generally do, too. To boost
sales and profits, companies take a gamble by offering incentives
that are costly in the short-term but designed to produce more
buyers in the long-term.
   But when interest wanes, as recent sales declines apparently
indicate, returns on incentive costs may come later, if at all, and
that cuts into short-term profits.
   GM's domestic car and truck sales through the first half of this
year were 7.7 percent behind last year's pace, and Ford's were down
by 3.6 percent.
   Both Ford and GM reported increased profits in their overseas
operations.
   ``They both had good first halves of the year in Europe,''
Harari said. ``This plays an important part in supporting their
earnings _ it has for the last two years.''
   For the first six months of the year, GM earned $3.01 billion,
or $4.60 a share, up 15.7 percent from $2.6 billion, or $3.82 a
share, during the first six months of last year. Revenue during the
January-June period rose to $59.63 billion, from $56.34 billion.
   Ford's earnings for the first half of 1989 fell 7.6 percent to
$3.04 billion, or $6.45 a share, from $3.29 billion, or $6.74 per
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $51.76 billion, from $48.15
billion.
   GM and Ford said they were continuing cost-cutting programs.
Also on Thursday, Chrysler announced a cost-cutting program aimed
at carving $1 billion from its $26 billion budget during the next
15 months. Cuts will come from all operations, included about 2,300
salaried employees who will be taken off the payroll.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
