<DOCNO> AP890728-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0805EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MarginDebate     07-28 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Margin Debate,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Margin Rules: SEC Report Reopens Debate Over Index Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A debate is heating up again over margins, the
amount of money investors must put up to buy stock index futures
contracts, and whether they cause sharp market fluctuations because
they're too low.
   At issue is how much money or collateral investors must deposit
with brokers when buying or selling futures contracts tied to the
rise and fall of stock indexes such as the Standard &amp; Poor's
500-stock index.
   A futures contract is an agreement to buy or sell a specific
amount of a commodity or financial instrument at a set price for
future delivery. The collateral used in buying futures contracts
and other commodities and securities is known as a margin.
   On Thursday, an SEC report to a House subcommittee considering
legislation to reform the securities industry expressed concern
that low margins ``may lead to market volatility in the future.''
   In the stock market, which is regulated by the SEC, investors
must put up at least 50 percent of a security's value. But in
commodity markets, which buy and sell stock index futures, the
margin requirement is a fraction of that, about 5 percent for
speculators and 2.5 percent for hedgers.
   Critics say volatility _ like the wave of selling thta occurred
during the 1987 market crash _ scares investors away from the
market. Others maintain that sharp price movements are a problem
only when prices are dropping.
   The SEC report said that during the Oct. 19 crash, low stock
index futures margin requirements contributed to sharp price
movements.
   ``Aside from the direct impact on market volatility, low stock
index futures margin can contribute to disruptions for market
systems and participants during periods of short-term volatility,''
said the report, prepared by the SEC's division of market
regulation.
   But commodity exchange officials in Chicago said the SEC was
comparing apples and oranges.
   ``Margins on futures and margins on securities are not
comparable,'' said Andrew A. Yemma, a spokesman for the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where futures tied to the S&amp;P 500 are traded.
``Margins on stocks are a downpayment of a purchase of an asset.
Margins on futures are deposits on a binding contract to perform.''
   At the Chicago Board of Trade, which trades stock index futures
based on the Major Market Index of 20 blue chip industrial stocks,
spokesman Mark Prout noted that larger traders can post margins as
low as 10 percent.
   The SEC long has sought to raise the levels of futures contracts
margins. Last May, SEC Chairman David Ruder recommended lifting
margins to 20 percent or 25 percent of contract value.
   But the exchanges in Chicago, Kansas City and New York that deal
in stock index futures are regulated by the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission, which lets the exchanges set margin limits.
   A CFTC spokeswoman, who did not want to be identified, said
Ruder was the only member of a four-person presidential panel
appointed to investigate the 1987 crash that believed high margin
levels would reduce volatility.
   ``There's no proof of this,'' she said, adding that the CFTC
``believes that higher margin levels will raise transaction costs
and will have a negative effect on liquidity and efficiency.''
   The SEC report came in response to a request from Rep. Edward J.
Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the House Subcommittee on
Telecommunications and Finance.
   The report also said there was a correlation between volatility
and computerized program trading, although it could not prove one
caused the other.
   Program trading, the rapid, computer-driven buying and selling
of baskets of stocks, was considered a key factor in the crash.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
