<SECOND>AM-LIN-McCaw,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCaw Lines Up Financing, But Deal Hangs In Balance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McCaw Cellular Communications Inc.
officials say they have lined up $2.5 billion in financing to
finance its $5.6 billion bid for LIN Broadcasting Corp.
   A statement issued by McCaw, based in this Seattle suburb, said
the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. said it was
confident the money could be raised ``either privately or publicly
in today's capital markets.''
   The deal is ``a key element of our overall $5.6 billion
financing plan,'' said Peter L.S. Currie, McCaw senior vice
president for finance, ``and we remain highly confident as well
that we will complete arrangements for the balance of the financing
on a timely basis.''
   Meanwhile, LIN released an exchange of letters Thursday between
McCaw Chairman Craig O. McCaw and LIN, indicating the two companies
remained at odds on the takeover bid.
   McCaw, the nation's largest cellular telephone company in terms
of ``pops,'' a measurement of market potential, is offering $110
for each LIN share, while LIN management is seeking $127.50 a share.
   At $127.50 a share, the buyout would value the New York-based
cellular telephone, television broadcasting and publishing company
at nearly $6.9 billion.
   McCaw already owns 5 million of LIN's 53.9 million shares.
   McCaw initially offered $120 a share, which LIN rejected as
inadequate. The offer was lowered to $110 after a court ruling that
went against LIN concerning cellular operations owned jointly by it
and Metromedia.
   On July 13 a joint statement said a buyout for $127.50 a share
in cash and stock was under negotiation, but McCaw withdrew from
those talks last week and extended its $110-a-share tender offer.
   On Tuesday, LIN Chairman Donald A. Pels said he would support a
McCaw buyout offer of no less than $127.50 per share if a
definitive agreement were reached by Monday.
   McCaw replied in the letter that he was still willing ``to
entertain a price above our current offer,'' but ``the
inflexibility of your requirements ... has made it impossible to
reach a definitive agreement.''
