<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv31   07-28 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 31,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv31</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, July 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>Payoff of Sears New Strategy is Slow in Coming _ As Expected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone searching through Sears, Roebuck and
Co.'s latest financial results for clues about the success of its
new retail strategy should remember one thing. Giants usually don't
move quickly.
   ``It's not something that we're going to see in a quarter or two
_ just because of the amount of change that has to occur,'' says
retail analyst Linda R. Morris of PNC Financial Corp.
   Karen Sach of Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. offered a similar
assessment after Sears, the nation's biggest retailer and also a
power in financial services, released its second-quarter earnings
figures last week.
   ``It's going to be awhile before we see any turnaround in the
merchandising group,'' says Ms. Sach. ``That's something that's
maybe a year down the road. I didn't expect anything fantastic this
soon.''
   At first glance, Sears' stats looked attractive:earnings grew
21.4 percenton a 9.2 percent revenue gain. Earnings in the quarter
ended June 30 rose to $391.2 million, or $1.11 a share, from $322.2
million, or 85 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$13.28 billion from $12.16 billion.
   But two special factors inflated the figures.
   The $69 million earnings increase included a $54.9 million gain
from the sale of the commercial division of the Coldwell Banker
Real Estate Group, counted as a discontinued operation. Earnings
solely from continuing operations declined to $334.9 million from
$338.3 million.
   For the merchandise group, which accounts for the bulk of the
corporation's business, a change in the method of accounting for
inventory added $21.9 million to earnings. The group's earnings
totaled $161.6 million in the second quarter vs. $157.6 million in
1988.
   If not for the one-time gain from the change in accounting
procedures, the Sears Merchandise Group would have had an earnings
decline.
   Despite expectations for a slow revival in its core retailing
operation, securities analysts aren't raising red flags of warning
about holding Sears' stock.
   This is partly because its financial services divisions, such as
the Discover credit card, Allstate insurance and Dean Witter
Reynolds investment unit have been doing well and should continue
to do so.
   For another thing, the retailing giant could end up clobbering
the competition if its new everyday low-pricing policy and other
new marketing tactics produce the desired benefits.
   Ms. Sach says it will take time to re-educate Sears' customers
and persuade them that they don't have to wait for sales _ they can
come into stores any day and pick up bargains.
   Sears hasn't abandoned special markdowns completely. Since the
March introduction of ``everyday low prices'' it has run several
``this week only'' promotions and other campaigns advertising
extra-low prices on certain items.
   These special promotions might confuse customers who may think
they'd be better off delaying purchases at Sears in hopes of lower
prices to come, some retail analysts say.
   Some of the changes at Sears have hefty price tags that will
probably impair earnings for awhile. But they are intended
eventually to yield significant savings and enhance profits.
   ``There are short-term negatives that hopefully will turn into
long-term positives,'' said Ms. Morris, citing severance pay to
departing employees whose jobs were eliminated as part of Sears'
restructuring and the cost of relocating the merchandise group out
of downtown Chicago to a nearby location.
   Many aspects of Sears' new strategy have yet to be put fully in
place. More name-brand merchandise is appearing gradually in Sears
stores, an addition that Sears and industry analysts expect will
boost business, for example.
   Sears and its rivals may all face a tough time if an economic
downturn causes consumers to shut their pocketbooks. Low-to
moderate-income consumers, who typically shop at discounters _ may
be the first to react in a recession.
   ``It just seems to me that this group is usually the one with
very little savings, living pay check to pay check and they're the
ones who get concerned about the economy first,'' says Ms. Morris.
``You really start to pull back and you don't take that weekly trip
to Sears or K mart to see what you need.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday, July 31</NOTE>
