<SECOND>PM-Wheeling-Pitt,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Approves Raise For Wheeling-Pitt Employees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge approved a 50-cent
hourly pay increase for 5,000 union employees of financially
troubled Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp.
   But Judge Warren Bentz said Thursday that he found the motion
requesting the pay hike ``offensive'' because it referred to the
company's recent profitability. He noted that there are about $1.2
billion in bankruptcy claims ``on which not a nickel has been
paid.''
   Union employees, who haven't had a wage hike in a decade, make a
minimum of $9 an hour.
   Bentz initially threatened to tie the wage increase to a
two-month deadline for the company and creditors to submit a final
plan of bankruptcy reorganization. The steelmaker filed for Chapter
11 protection from its creditors in 1985.
   ``How soon can I get a plan finalized,'' he asked company
attorneys. ``Why can't you do this in two months?''
   A major issue in the reorganization is a new labor agreement
with the United Steelworkers to replace one that expires 10 days
after the company emerges from bankruptcy court protection.
   The union has insisted it could not negotiate a new contract
until a long-running dispute is resolved with the federal Pension
Benefit Guaranty Corp.
   But Bentz said that issue, which is before U.S. District Judge
Paul Simmons, could take years to solve.
   ``You'll have the same uncertainties a year from now, two years
from now,'' he said. ``You might as well get on with it.''
   Paul Whitehead, an attorney for the union, said the interim
raise was requested after the USW learned the company was granting
merit pay increases of about 5 percent to salaried employees.
