<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     07-28 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Current Account Surplus Falls 33 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rapidly rising imports pushed Japan's current
account surplus down in June for the fourth consecutive monthly
decline from year-earlier levels, the Finance Ministry reported
Friday.
   The ministry said the surplus for the month was $4.12 billion,
down 33 percent from the $6.12 billion registered a year earlier.
   The imbalance in the current account, which includes merchandise
trade and other financial flows, was up from $3.39 billion in May,
it said.
   The trade surplus followed the same pattern, falling to $6.44
billion from $7.39 billion a year earlier, but rising from $5.06
billion in May, as measured when contracts were settled.
   Finance Ministry officials said imports were sharply higher than
a year earlier due to continuing strong domestic economic demand.
They said imports of manufactured goods were particularly brisk.
   On the other hand, exports of some products, including steel and
automobiles, fell short of year-earlier levels, the officials said.
They said political unrest in Beijing in June, which disrupted
China's economy, may have had a bearing on the relatively sluggish
export performance.
   Steel and auto industry associations have said the turmoil in
Beijing hurt Japan's shipments of steel and motor vehicles to China.
   Imports climbed 12.8 percent from the year-earlier level to
$15.8 billion dollars, while declining 2.7 percent from May.
Exports grew a modest 3.9 percent from a year earlier to $22.3
billion while rising 4.4 percent from May.
   After seasonal adjustment, the current account surplus came to
$2.92 billion, down from $3.36 billion the preceding month.
   Officials attributed the growing deficit in services to a surge
in the number of Japanese tourists traveling overseas to capitalize
on the yen's strength.
</TEXT>
