<FIRST>r f PM-PrimeComputer     07-28 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Four Won't Extend Deadline to Take Prime Computer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. announced it is backing off
its $1.1 billion attempt to take over Prime Computer Inc., but is
still vying for Prime's minicomputer business.
   MAI said in a statement it would allow its tender offer to
expire at midnight Thursday. MAI said it had ``concluded that it
could not obtain extensions of its financing commitments ...
because of the frequent changes which have occurred in Prime's
estimates and projections.''
   However, the announcement did not end the battle for Prime. J.H.
Whitney &amp; Co., which has agreed to buy Prime for $1.2 billion, has
been unable to complete its offer because of two lawsuits and
financing problems.
   Whitney announced today it was extending its offer until Aug. 4.
   MAI offered $19.50 in cash for about 75 percent of Prime's
shares and a package of bonds and preferred stock for the rest.
   J.H. Whitney, the nation's oldest venture capital firm, has
offered $21.50 a share in case for about 50 million Prime shares
and would exchange notes for the rest.
   Spokesmen for Prime and Whitney said they had no comment on
MAI's announcement.
   Prime stock rose 50 cents to $16.25 a share in New York Stock
Exchange trading Thursday.
   Stephen K. Smith, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc. in New York,
said the continued uncertainty over Prime's future was hurting the
company, but predicted J.H. Whitney would still come out the victor.
   ``Just the fact that these things are dragging on so long are
dragging them down,'' said Smith. ``We still feel Whitney will come
through.''
   The J.H. Whitney bid has been delayed by a suit brought by Prime
bondholder Conarb Partners seeking to extend the deadline for the
offer.
   U.S. District Court Judge David Edelstein denied Conarb's
request for a temporary restraining order on Thursday, J.H. Whitney
said in a statement.
   Theodore Altman, an attorney for Conarb, said news that Whitney
needed additional financing for a merger with Prime sparked the
suit. ``We weren't fighting for anything but more information,'' he
said.
   Conarb Partners holds bonds that can be converted into Prime
stock.
   Prime faces a lawsuit from a Miami-based company seeking to stop
a merger with J.H. Whitney, according federal court documents.
   United Trust Fund Inc. filed suit against Prime July 21 over a
lease agreement with Prime's wholly owned subsidiary,
Computervision Corp., saying Prime had agreed it would not enter
any merger that would decrease its net worth below $250 million
according to the suit filed in U.S. District Court in Boston.
   In an order issued Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Joseph Tauro
said he would only rule on an injunction seven days before the
proposed merger between Prime and J.H. Whitney.
   Two banks also have asked J.H. Whitney to obtain additional
financing before they will back the friendly buyout of Prime.
   Prime, based in Natick, has about 11,000 employees. It makes
minicomputers and is the second to International Business Machines
Corp. in the computer-aided design and manufacturing systems field.
MAI Basic, of Tustin, Calif., is about one-quarter Prime's size.
</TEXT>
