<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1019EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-28 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0320</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market continued to push ahead in
active trading today, extending the rally of the past two sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 2.66 at 2,638.09
at 10 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones on the New York
Stock Exchange by about 100 stocks, with 519 up, 427 down and 537
unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 0.25 to 190.47.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 29.22 million shares after the
first 30 minutes of trading.
   After the powerful advance over the past two days, Wall
Streeters are saying they wouldn't be surprised if the stock market
took a breather while investors sell to collect profits.
   In the early going, Smith Corona was the most heavily traded
share on the Big Board and was unchanged at 21.
   Drug stocks continued to attract investors' attention today
after Thursday's rally in the sector sparked by a surprise
announcement that Bristol-Myers and Squibb planned to merge.
   Among the active drug stocks: Bristol-Myers was off | at 48~;
Squibb fell 1[ to 111]; Syntex rose { to 50{; and Upjohn added { to
33{.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average closed at a new
post-crash high of 2,635.43, up 22.38, producing a gain of 52.35
points for Thursday and Wednesday combined.
   The NYSE's composite index rose 2.08 to 190.22, an all-time
high. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index closed
at a record 375.35, up 2.57.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board surged to 213.68 million
shares from 188.27 million in the previous session.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by about 2 to 1 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 1,021 up, 496 down
and 483 unchanged.
