<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-DATPlayers     07-28 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-DAT Players,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Of DAT Players May Proliferate Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Widespread sales of digital audio tape (DAT)
recorders may begin next year under a new agreement between
international record and electronic industry groups, officials said
Friday.
   DAT machines can make high-quality sound recordings using the
same digital technology as compact disc (CD) players. But their
introduction has been slowed by opposition from record companies,
who feared they would encourage pirating and cut into CD and record
sales.
   In a pact announced this week, record and audio industry groups
agreed on a new worldwide standard for DATs that clears the way for
widespread marketing but limits the machines' ability to make
repeated copies of CDs and other recorded material.
   Industry officials said it would take a minimum of eight to nine
months before new DAT recorders are introduced and marketing begins
in countries such as the United States because of the time needed
for design and government approval.
   ``It will require new integrated circuits. You will not see a
machine coming out from my company this year,'' said a Sony Corp.
spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   DAT players currently are being marketed in Japan and some parts
of Europe. The more than 10 Japanese electronics firms that produce
most of the world's DAT equipment have refrained from actively
selling the machines in the United States because of opposition
from the U.S. record industry.
   DAT players combine many of the technologies used to make
videocassette recorders and compact disc players. U.S. electronics
companies have largely abandoned the manufacture of both products,
and therefore are unlikely to make DATs.
   DAT is not expected to become a serious threat to the thriving
compact disk industry until the price of DAT recorders and tapes
comes down. The least expensive DAT models in Japan currently cost
about $800, while one-hour tapes sell for considerably more than
$10.
   Both prices are expected to fall substantially as production
increases due to economies of scale, Hata said.
   Kinji Kawamoto, general manager of Panasonic's Audio and Video
Research Laboratory, said the pact would have ``virtually no
effect'' on DAT production costs. ``It will only involve a slight
redesign of the semiconductor chips controlling logic functions,''
he said.
   Included in Friday's agreement were the Recording Industry
Association of America, the International Federation of the
Phonographic Industry, and Japanese and European electronics makers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest     07-28 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Completes Northwest Airlines' Parent Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by Los Angeles
businessman Alfred Checchi says it has completed its $3.6 billion
tender offer and appeared to have won control of NWA Inc., the
parent of Northwest Airlines.
   But Checchi's victory Thursday was soon followed by a worsening
of labor problems at the nation's fourth-largest airline. Northwest
and its pilots union announced that 28-month-long talks on a new
contract had broken down.
   The union said it would seek binding arbitration from the
National Mediation Board.
   Checchi's group, Wings Holdings Inc. said it accepted for
purchase all duly tendered shares of NWA common stock, and that it
now controlled 99 percent of the company's common shares.
   As of May 31, NWA had 29.4 million shares outstanding. The
$121-per-share takeover offer expired at 5 p.m. EDT Wednesday.
   ``We are delighted to have completed this acquisition,'' Checchi
said in a statement released in New York. ``Now we can get on with
the real job which is continuing to build Northwest over the long
term.''
   He said the new owners hoped to double the company's revenue
over the next five years, while improving service and assuring
harmonious relations between management and employees.
   Mark Daugherty, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New
York, was wary about NWA's prospects.``If you're looking at the
future of the company, I'd be very worried,'' he said.
   Daugherty said Checchi's buyout plan, which includes $700
million in cash and $3.35 billion in financing, is risky because
the airline industry is capital intensive, volatile and cyclical.
   ``If I were a pilot or any other employee, I would be very
concerned that my company would have to support this debt burden,''
he said.
   Checchi has said fears about debt in the deal are ``almost
laughable.''
   ``The amount of debt in this proposal is not the least bit
excessive,'' he said last month.
   The pilots' union and another analyst say they also don't fear
the debt.
   ``I don't think the man is foolhardy,'' said Kevin Murphy, an
analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York. ``It provides a lot
of debt, but who cares if it's a private company?''
   Murphy noted that Checchi already has passed several checkpoints
designed to make sure he can continue to provide the service,
safety and growth Northwest has in the past.
   But he also said Northwest's ticket prices may increase to pay
for the debt.
   Steve Arnold, a spokesman for the 5,000-member Air Line Pilots
Association local at Northwest, said the union became less
concerned about the debt level after reviewing Checchi's plan
earlier this year.
   ``While his debt is a concern to us, we feel he can accomplish
what he says he can do,'' Arnold said.
   Northwest's talks with the pilots recessed due to what was
called a dispute over pay issues.
   Rich Siakel, a spokesman for the pilots, said some progress had
been made until Thursday, ``and today apparently everything went
sour.'' The pilots made a counterproposal on pay issues to which
Northwest would not respond, he said.
   Alan Muncaster, Northwest's vice president for corporate
communications, said several key issues had been resolved:
pensions, work rules and job security.
   But ``some big dollars'' still separate the two sides on wages,
health insurance for retirees and a special payment fund for
pilots, he said.
   The National Mediation Board must decide whether to grant the
pilots' request for arbitration. If Northwest rejected arbitration,
a 30-day cooling-off period would begin, after which the pilots
would be free to strike and the company would be free to impose its
latest offer.
   Although Checchi has become Northwest's new owner, a few more
steps must be taken to make the change formal.
   The merger of NWA with a subsidiary of Wings must be consummated
and Wings needs an operating permit from the U.S. Transportation
Department, which is conducting a financial fitness review of the
new owners.
</TEXT>
