<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1122EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-JapanPoll     07-28 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan Poll,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans More Concerned About Japan Than About Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are more concerned by the economic
threat from Japan than by the military threat from the Soviet Union
by a 3-to-1 margin, a new poll indicates.
   In the poll for Business Week magazine, 68 percent of
respondents named Japan as the bigger threat to the future of the
United States, while 22 percent named the Soviet Union and 10
percent rated them equal or were not sure.
   Sixty-eight percent felt American companies' troubles exporting
to Japan were partly the result of unfair Japanese barriers, while
57 percent said American products were too expensive and 38 percent
said they were not as good as Japanese products.
   Pollsters mentioned proposals that might ``make the Japanese
markets more receptive to this country's products.'' Seventy-nine
percent favored requiring that a certain amount of U.S. products be
allowed into Japan; 61 percent favored higher tariffs on imports
from Japan; 69 percent favored a limit on imports from Japan; and
59 percent favored restricting the flow of technology from the
United States to Japan.
   The poll of 1,250 adults was connected July 7-11 by Louis Harris
&amp; Associates. Results should be accurate to within 3 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
