<FIRST>u f PM-WarnerBankruptcy     07-28 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Warner Bankruptcy,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Orders Trustee Appointed In Warner Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge today
ordered a trustee be appointed to identify assets of convicted bank
swindler Marvin Warner that could be sold to pay off creditors who
claim they are owed a total of $4.5 billion.
   Refusing to grant Warner's request for more time to organize his
affairs, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George L. Proctor set a hearing Aug.
25 on motions in the case.
   Daniel Bakst, a West Palm Beach attorney, was appointed trustee
by the U.S. Trustee's Office to examine Warner's holdings and
lawsuits against him before deciding what to do with his assets.
   Warner withdrew his latest plan to emerge from protection from
his creditors Thursday after all but one of the unsecured creditors
rejected it. He asked today for another 30 days to develop a new
plan, but Proctor moved the case from Chapter 11 reorganization to
Chapter 7 liquidation instead.
   Among the secured creditors is Home State Savings Bank of
Cincinnati, which is owed more than $275 million, according to
court records. Warner was president of the bank prior to its
collapse in 1985.
   American Savings &amp; Loan Association of Miami, where Warner
served as a director, also is listed among the unsecured creditors.
It is suing Warner for breach of fiduciary duty and claims to be
owed $316 million.
   Warner, who now lives in Ocala, claims his estate is worth $2
million to $3 million, although creditors' attorneys hope to
include another $30 million to $40 million that creditors allege
Warner fraudulently transferred to members of his family.
   According to documents filed by attorneys representing Warner's
creditors, he transferred $500,000 in diamonds and $3.6 million in
cash to his wife.
   He also transferred 168 acres at his Ocala horse ranch to his
son and $4.2 million worth of thoroughbred horses to Fred M. Cone,
his trustee, court records allege.
   Warner filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S.
Bankruptcy Code in October 1987. He listed $4.5 billion in debts
and later claimed $20 million in assets, although creditors say the
amount is higher.
   His filing followed the collapse of Home State in March 1984,
which lost $144 million in investments arranged by Warner with ESM
Securities Inc., a security trading company in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Warner is appealing his 1987 Ohio conviction of illegally
funneling Home State Funds to ESM. He was sentenced to 3{ years in
prison and ordered to pay $22 million in restitution.
</TEXT>
