<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe     07-28 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers of Commodities Traders Summoned In Anticipation of Indictments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers representing commodities traders have
been asked to meet today with top U.S. Justice Department officials
before indictments are sought charging traders with cheating
customers, published reports say.
   The Chicago Tribune said up to 50 traders could be hit with
charges that they engaged in illegal practices at the Chicago Board
of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Unidentified sources
quoted by The Wall Street Journal said the number of traders ranged
from 10 to more than 20.
   The charges would be the first from a two-year investigation of
the nation's largest futures exchanges in which FBI agents
infiltrated the trading floors to gather evidence on suspected
corrupt practices.
   Indictments could come as early as next week, unidentified
sources told both papers.
   Their number and timing could depend on the outcome of the
closed-door meeting where prosecutors will begin unfolding their
case. Defense lawyers are expected to try to convince them not to
seek charges against clients under the federal Racketeer Influenced
and Corrupt Organizations Act, known as RICO.
   Under RICO, convicted traders could lose their exchange seats
and any assets judged to have been acquired through illegal actions.
   Federal prosecutors typically call in individual defense lawyers
on the eve of major indictments for one-on-one negotiations to seek
cooperation in exchange for reduced charges.
   But such a large meeting is unusual, the Tribune said, noting
that at least a dozen defense attorneys have been invited and the
Justice Department has flown in its top RICO expert.
   The attorneys invited to meet with prosecutors represent clients
who were told two weeks ago that they had 14 days to decide to
cooperate with the government or face a racketeering charge, the
newspaper said.
   The Journal noted that the Justice Department could name the
futures trading pits as ``racketeering enterprises,'' an unlikely
and unprecedented step.
   Not only would such action damage the image of the exchanges,
the paper said, it would allow traders to be indicted and tried
together even if they did not trade with each other.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
