<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market resumed its climb today after
taking a breather in early trading while investors sold to collect
profits.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials moved ahead 7.78 to
2,643.21 by noon on Wall Street.
   Advancing issues outpaced declining ones on the New York Stock
Exchange by about 6 to 5, with 709 up, 582 down and 522 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.49 to 190.71.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 99.86 million shares compared to
112.76 million at the same point in Thursday's session.
   After the powerful advance over the past two days, Wall
Streeters expected the stock market to run into some profit-taking.
   A government report showing U.S. personal income edged up 0.3
percent in June while the level of consumer spending was unchanged
ignited a rally in the bond market, sending interest rates lower, a
movement which was welcomed by the stock market.
   Drug stocks continued to attract investors' attention today
after Thursday's rally in the sector sparked by a surprise
announcement that Bristol-Myers and Squibb planned to merge.
   Squibb, which soared 24} on Thursday, lost 1} to 110}. Among
other actively traded drug stocks: Bristol-Myers was off 1\ at 48\;
Upjohn went up 1} to 34}; and Marion Laboratories dipped [ to 35}.
   Chase Manhattan headed the Big Board's list of actively traded
issues, rising ] to 39.
   The heavily traded blue chips included: American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, down [ to 40{; Eastman Kodak, up { to 49\; and General
Electric, up { at 58.
   Another active stock was retailer K mart, gaining 1[ to 40].
