<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Post-Crash High Set</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices soared to a new post-crash high
Friday as strong speculative interest, a firm showing on Wall
Street and a the start of a new trading account period encouraged a
flurry of buying interest.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended up 22.3
points, or 1 percent, at 2306.0, a session high and well above an
early low of 2286.2 recorded at the opening.
   Dealers said the market's upward move featured a buying squeeze
on several lines of stock. ``No one wants to sell at the moment and
the institutions are still buying strongly,'' one trader said.
   Dealers also had expected Wall Street to open slightly lower but
it moved ahead and the London market followed.
   Most dealers expect the market to rise higher in the near-term,
unless institutions find an excuse to start selling. London's Stock
Exchange divides trading into two-week and three-week trading
periods for accounting purposes.
   Volume was 585.7 million shares Friday, up from 481.3 million
Thursday.
</TEXT>
