<FIRST>u f AM-Spain-BigBang Bjt   07-28 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spain-Big Bang, Bjt,0605</SECOND>
<HEAD>Era Ends in Spanish Markets On Eve of Market Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An era came to an end for Spain's
158-year-old stock market Friday as investors and market operators
traded for the last time under old rules to be swept away over the
weekend in Spain's so-called Big Bang market reform.
   A law set to take effect Saturday introduces the most sweeping
changes in markets in Madrid, Barcelona, Bilbao and Valencia since
the founding of the first bourse in the Spanish capital in 1831.
   The privatization of the exchanges is expected to introduce
greater competition in the markets, which could mean that many of
the new, privately-owned brokerage firms created by the Big Bang
won't last long.
   Monday will be the first day of trading under the new system,
which Spanish National Radio termed ``an authentic revolution in
the Spanish financial system.''
   On Friday, civil servant stockbrokers enjoyed their last day of
monopoly over trading rights. The new law forced them to establish
or join new private brokerages or broker-dealer companies or
abandon trading altogether and act as public notaries.
   Market operators and regulators marked the final day under the
old rules at a ceremony in the Madrid Stock Exchange building
following the morning trading session.
   Javier Ramos Gascon, head of the old Madrid state-entity
exchange, symbolically turned over power to 36-year-old Pedro
Guerrerro, who was elected last week to preside over the new
private exchange. It is now owned and managed by new member
brokerages and dealer firms.
   National Securities Commission president Luis Carlos Croissier
acknowledged that ``survival in the new tough market is going to be
difficult'' for some of the more than 50 new member brokerages or
dealer-broker firms.
   Many analysts have predicted that from 20 to 30 of the new firms
won't be around within two years because of a greater competition
spurred by the reform.
   ``There are too many new firms,'' Ramos Gascon told reporters.
``I'm afraid a good number of them will not last.''
   The government set up the securities comission nine months ago
to implement the June 1988 market reform law. The commission is the
chief markets supervisory body and watchdog agency.
   A key part of the reform law established the Computer Automated
Trading System, or CATS, last April. So far 23 stock issues
accounting for 22 percent of trading volume have gone onto the
system.
   Croissier predicted that by the end of the year more than 50
percent of the total trading volume in Spain would take place on
the CATS system, which was pioneered by the Toronto Stock Exchange.
   On Friday, as in recent weeks, trading volume remained low on
the four stock exchanges, partly because of investor concerns about
the market reform changeover process and because of recent
government moves to restrict credit and slow down a booming
economy, analysts said.
   Trading volume Friday on the Madrid stock exchange, which
accounts for nearly 70 percent of trading in Spain, totaled 3.3
million shares or the equivalent of $62.3 million.
   Last April, when the Madrid market was surging, trading volume
moved between 5-6 million shares a day and $85.5 million to $102.5
million a day, said Madrid stock exchange spokesman Jaime Sanz.
   The Madrid general index Friday rose a slight 1.43 points to
302.23.
   The Barcelona exchange general index dipped 0.26 points to
105.80 and the Bilbao exchange general index climbed 3.56 points to
418.49. The Valencia exchange general index rose 1.50 points to
243.32.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
