<FIRST>r f AM-CommercialCosts     07-28 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commercial Costs,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Group Says Costs of Making a Commercial Rose 15 Percent Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of producing a television commercial
rose 15 percent to $168,000 last year, with automobile ads ranking
as the most expensive product category, according to an industry
survey.
   The American Association of Advertising Agencies said in
releasing the report Thursday that the increases ``were not as
dramatic as some of those reported earlier this decade.''
   The survey included 2,624 commercials produced in 1988 for
products ranging from automobiles and soft drinks to toys and
financial services.
   The average cost of a commercial created for national broadcast
was $176,000, up 15 percent, while costs rose 29 percent to
$132,000 for regional commercials and leaped 37 percent to $78,000
for local commercials.
   Automotive ads were the most expensive to produce, rising 28
percent to an average of $213,000. The average cost of ads for fast
food, beer, soft drinks and snacks fell 9 percent to $210,000.
   Some other categories, followed by percentage change and average
costs, included: beauty, fashion and cosmetics, up 40 percent to
$209,000; consumer services, travel and corporate image, up 34
percent to $190,000; appliances, office equipment and audio visual
products, up 10 percent to $182,000; packaged goods, up 7 percent
to $127,000; and toys and recreation, up 29 percent to $152,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
