<DOCNO> AP890728-0276 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0347EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-HomeShopping Adv30   07-28 1062</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Home Shopping, Adv 30,1097</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, July 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Home Shopping Business Shakes Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Televised home shopping, once heralded as a
revolutionary leap that would turn millions of living rooms into
shopping malls, has lurched through a painful childhood because
many potential customers aren't buying.
   Sales of items ranging from zirconia jewelry to fancy electronic
hardware have failed to meet the projections of analysts who had
predicted remarkable growth in a business that's less than a decade
old.
   Dozens of shopping networks begun with high ambitions have
closed or shifted focus. Some aspiring networks are finding it
difficult to persuade cable television system operators to make
room for them.
   Nonetheless, many analysts say home shopping's prospects remain
promising because they expect operators to put aside territorial
battles and concentrate on marketing themselves to prospective
buyers, those cable TV viewers who either aren't watching or don't
like what's for sale.
   ``Home shopping channels have a place in the future,'' said
Larry Gerbrandt, who follows the business for the media research
firm Paul Kagan Associates Inc. of Carmel, Calif. ``We have just
seen the tip of the iceberg of what they can do.''
   Recently, two of the three biggest home shopping network owners,
CVN Companies Inc. and QVC Network Inc., proposed to join forces in
a move that would reduce Home Shopping Network Inc.'s commanding
lead.
   Minneapolis-based CVN, which operates Cable Value Network, the
Fashion Channel and America's Shopping Channel with more than 23
million subscribers, would be acquired for about $400 million in
cash and stock by QVC, the West Chester, Pa.-based operator of the
14 million subscriber QVC Network.
   Home Shopping says its three services are carried on cable and
broadcast stations that can be seen by more than 60 million
households.
   The only other national home shopping service of significant
size is the J.C. Penney Television Shopping Channel, formerly known
as Shop Television Network. It is available on cable systems with
5.3 milion subscribers.
   The management consulting and accounting firm Touche Ross &amp; Co.
had estimated in 1986 that all home shopping programs would have a
combined total of more than $5 billion in annual sales by 1990.
   Douglas Hosking, a top executive in electronic retail consulting
at the San Francisco-based firm, concedes the projection was too
optimistic and expects industrywide revenues will reach $3 billion
to $5 billion in five years.
   Paul Kagan Associates estimates industry revenues totaled $1.4
billion in 1988 and projects growth to $2.75 billion by 1993.
   Critics say they are not surprised that home shopping has failed
to meet expectations. They say the public's appetite for closeout
merchandise and gadgets is bound to fade further.
   But Gerbrandt notes that home shopping channels are available to
more than 60 percent of the nation's television households.
   William Block, vice president of research at the brokerage
Newhard Cook &amp; Co., said surveys have shown more than half of all
cable subscribers aren't even of home shopping, an untapped
opportunity.
   Gerbrandt said the typical home shopping channel customer is
over 35 years old with a college education and household income
exceeding $35,000.
   ``That's more upscale than some people may have thought, but
then again nobody ever admits going into a K mart,'' he said.
   Home Shopping Network was the industry's first big star when it
went national in mid-1985 with the shopping service that it had
been running for three years on a local cable TV system in
Florida's Tampa Bay area.
   It put hosts on the air who tried to create a bargain-basement
atmosphere as they described eight to 12 products an hour, often
with a monitor counting down the number of items left or the number
of seconds remaining until the sale would end. They tooted horns
and chatted with callers who only had to make a purchase to be
admitted as a member of the ``club.''
   Its approach was to offer a range of products _ a VCR may follow
a gold necklace, for instance _ to catch the impulse buyer.
   ``Our entertaining format where you don't know what is coming
next keeps the viewer tuned in,'' said spokeswoman Kathy Jurado.
   But QVC Network _ the letters stand for quality, value and
convenience _ took a different approach after it aired in November
1986, about six months after CVN debuted.
   QVC segments its programming by spending an hour at a time on
one product category and promoting the presentations in advance.
   QVC may spend an hour on telephones, for instance, discussing
the features and pricing of each model. QVC executive vice
president Bruce Sellers said the approach allows people to shop as
they would at a mall and gets fewer complaints than catalog
retailers.
   While HSN, QVC and CVN built an audience, Gerbrandt said three
dozen or more home shopping channels came and went over the past
three years.
   Among the casualties were Shoppers' Casino, Collectible
Showcase, Caravan of Values and Crazy Eddie's World of Home
Entertainment.
   Hosking said one reason why so many failed was the relatively
small startup cost.
   ``It didn't take a lot of capital to get into the business, but
it takes a lot to be successful,'' he said.
   Another problem was that many cable systems reached their
capacity and decided they had no room for more than two shopping
channels. That was especially true when networks such as QVC signed
long-term agreements with cable operators and offered them equity
stakes in the service.
   Home Shopping has failed to meet the ambitious sales goals its
top executives have set, and is embroiled in a civil trial in
Florida with GTE Corp. over telephone problems that HSN said cost
it millions of dollars in lost business. GTE has denied
responsibility.
   Financial News Network joined the ranks of shopping service
dropouts in May when its discontinued its 2{-year-old FNN: Telshop
service.
   Telshop had been running overnight and on weekends on the same
channel as the Financial News Network.
   ``We didn't lose our enthusiasm for the home shopping business,
but felt a need to go 24 hours a day with business information,''
said former Telshop general manager John Berentson.
   He said within a few years, expansion of cable channel capacity
may reopen the door to new shopping services. ``It's a darn good
business,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
