<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge Below $6.50 On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged below $6.50 a
bushel, a 16-month low, in late trading Friday on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid expectations for continued improvement in Midwestern
growing conditions.
   Other grain futures also closed lower, largely in sympathy with
the plummeting soybean market.
   Analysts cited a bevy of bearish signals, including improving
crop conditions, forecasts for another week of scattered showers in
the Midwest, lower cash soybean prices and increased farmer selling
of soybeans.
   ``There was no incentive for anyone to buy,'' said Janice
Kincheloe, a market analyst in Chicago with Cargill Investor
Services Inc.
   Soybean futures prices have been moving lower since reaching
nearly $11 a bushel during last summer's drought.
   At the close, soybean futures were 1{ cents to 19{ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in August at $6.48{ cents a bushel,
the lowest price for a near-month contract since March 30, 1988.
Wheat was 1} cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $3.88 a
bushel; corn was 2 cents to 3} cents lower with September at $2.28}
a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 8 cents lower with September at
$1.36 a bushel.
