<FIRST>r f AM-CentralNewspapers     07-28 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central Newspapers,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shareholders Approve Stock Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Central Newspapers Inc.,
which owns newspapers in Indiana and Arizona, on Friday approved a
recapitalization plan that clears the way for the company's first
public stock offering.
   Central Newspapers subsidiaries publish eight newspapers,
including The Indianapolis Star, The Indianapolis News, The Arizona
Republic and The Phoenix Gazette. Vice President Dan Quayle is
among under 200 stockholders.
   The company said in a statement that the Eugene C. Pulliam
Trust, which has had voting control of Central Newspapers since
1965, permits the recapitalization as long as it retains at least
53.77 percent voting power.
   Pulliam, Quayle's grandfather, was publisher of The Star and
News. He died in 1975. His son, Eugene S. Pulliam, Quayle's uncle,
is the current publisher.
   Under the recapitalization plan, the number of shares authorized
for issuance would be increased from 200,000 to 75 million for
Class A stock; 20,000 to 50 million for Class B; and 120,000 to 25
million for preferred stock.
   The plan grants limited voting rights to holders of Class A
stock and convertibility of Class B stock into Class A. It also
permits a 200 for 1 stock split in Class A and Class B stock.
   Central Newspapers also publishes the Arizona Business Gazette
and, in Indiana, The Muncie Star, The Muncie Evening Press and the
Vincennes Sun-Commercial.
   The company reported net income of about $29 million last year
on revenue of nearly $418 million.
</TEXT>
