<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern     07-28 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Strikers and Unions Rally in New York</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 2,500 striking Eastern Airlines
workers and union representatives rallied Friday to draw attention
to the nearly five-month-long walkout.
   ``Frank Lorenzo is saying, `We are flying the planes, the strike
is over.' The strike is not over,'' said George E. Leitz,
international president of the Transport Workers of America.
   ``That's why we have this today, that he gets the message load
and clear,'' he said. ``They're still out on the picket lines and
they won't go back to work unless they get a decent contract,
something they can live with.''
   Lorenzo is chairman of Texas Air Corp., parent of Miami-based
Eastern. Texas Air also owns Continental Airlines.
   Eastern, which virtually was grounded when its Machinists,
pilots and flight attendants walked off the job March 4, has
undertaken a restructuring plan that calls for selling $1.8 billion
in assets and emerging from bankruptcy reorganization as a smaller
airline.
   The company, which has been hiring and training replacement
pilots, also has reached agreement with its creditors on a
bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   The striking employees have endorsed a separate plan to rebuild
the airline, centering on a buyout by a group led by Chicago
options trader Joseph Ritchie.
   Friday's rally was held at Rockefeller Center outside a
Continental ticket office. Some participants went to other ticket
offices in the area to demonstrate opposition to flying Eastern,
Continental and Scandinavian Airlines, which has financial ties to
Texas Air.
   ``This is like the last hurrah here. We're trying to do
something before it's too late,'' said Betsy Hartmann of Transport
Workers local 553 in Newark, N.J.
   Among those joining the rally were members of the International
Association of Machinists and representatives from the local postal
workers union, District Council 37, the Air Line Pilots
Association, United Mine Workers of Virginia and AFSCME Local 420,
representing hospital workers.
</TEXT>
