<FIRST>u f AM-Hooker 1stLd-Writethru   07-28 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hooker, 1st Ld - Writethru,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hooker Rules Out `Fire Sale', Delegation U.S.-Bound</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10 pvs, bgng In the... with 2 new grafs to UPDATE
with home-building subsidiary denying report that it shutting down. Picks
up 11th graf, Earlier this...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooker Corp. on Friday ruled out a
``fire sale'' of its $1.8 billion assets while a team of advisers
headed for the United States to investigate ways to head off
foreclosure by U.S creditors.
   Hooker, a major Australian property company with significant
U.S. retail and real estate interests, turned itself over to a
court-appointed provisional liquidator on Wednesday in one of
Australia's biggest corporate collapses.
   The Sydney-based company, which owns B. Altman &amp; Co., Bonwit
Teller plus other U.S. department stores and shopping malls, owes
the equivalent of $1.2 billion to more than 42 banks.
   Hooker has blamed its financial mess on sluggish U.S. consumer
spending, exchange rate fluctuations, and Australian economic
troubles such as high interest rates that have hurt operations
there.
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke said Thursday the collapse had nothing
to do with the fundamental strength of the Australian economy.
   ``...We live in a situation where, as far as this government is
concerned, we deregulated the market, we let market forces oeprate
and market forces have operated here.''
   John Harkness, appointed provisional liquidator on July 26, told
a news conference Friday he was in the process of assessing the
situation and hoped to stabilize the corporation and then reduce
its debt.
   He said there would be no fire sale of assets and every attempt
would be made to maximize their value. The company has 10,000
employees and 13,000 shareholders.
   On Friday, subsidiary L.J. Hooker Homes, a U.S. residential
construction company based in Atlanta, denied published reports
that it was shutting down its operations as a result of this week's
developments.
   Brian McGregor, president of the company, issued a statement in
Atlanta saying Hooker's financial problems had temporarily altered
normal business operations at the subsidiary, ``but we are still in
business, all of our employees are at work, and we have no plans at
this time to close down.''
   Earlier this week, First National Bank of Chicago reportedly
started foreclosure proceedings on Hooker's Richland Fashion Mall
in Columbia, S.C. Hooker's financial advisers Friday said they were
aware of possible foreclosure but declined to comment further.
   The officials also said a delegation was preparing to fly to the
United States this weekend to consider whether Hooker would seek
court protection under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   A Chapter 11 filing would protect the company from creditors'
lawsuits in the United States while Hooker works out a plan of
reorganization.
   Richard Grellman of the accounting firm Peat Marwick Hungerfords
has been advising Hooker and is part of the delegation. He said the
company's U.S. interests are vital to its future.
   ``The actions of creditors that hold specific securities is
something that will have to be addressed very carefully,'' Grellman
said. ``Whether Chapter 11 or some other alternative is most
appropriate is really the purpose of our trip.''
   Grellman acknowledged that some of Hooker's U.S. creditors have
certain rights over some of the company's assets.
   ``If they act within those rights, then so be it,'' he said.
``Clearly, actions along those lines will have to be examined very
carefully from the company's point of view.''
   Harkness, in ruling out a fire sale, said: ``We are running the
business as it was run and (will be) continuing business as usual.''
   He said it was essential the company be given time to conduct an
orderly sale of assets so their value could be maximized.
   Hooker's other U.S. interests include Sakowitz Inc., Parisian
Inc. and Merksamer Jewelers Inc. It has interests in shopping
malls, commercial property developments and house building.
   Hooker was suspended from share trading on Thursday. George
Herscu, who owns 50 percent of Hooker, resigned as chief executive
July 11 but remains chairman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
