<DOCNO> AP890728-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CattleInventory     07-28 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cattle Inventory,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unchanged From Year Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mid-year cattle inventory showed 108.6
million head on the nation's farms and ranches as of July 1,
virtually unchanged from 108.5 million a year ago, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   ``This stops the seven-year trend of a declining cattle
industry,'' said the report by the department's National
Agricultural Statistics Service.
   However, the July 1 total was down 1 percent from the 109.5
million head reported two years ago. Last year's inventory was said
then to be the lowest since the July 1 count began in 1973.
   In February, the agency reported the Jan. 1 cattle inventory at
a 28-year low of fewer than 99.5 million head.
   Officials said the 1989 calf crop is expected to be 40.7 million
head, down fractionally from last year but up 2 percent from 1987.
   The July 1 inventory of 108.6 million head, which includes
calves and dairy cattle as well as beef stock, included these
categories:
   _Beef cows, 34.2 million, up slightly from July 1, 1988 and 1
percent above July 1, 1987.
   _Milk cows, 10.1 million, down 1 percent from last year and 3
percent below two years ago.
   _All heifers, 500 pounds and over, 16.7 million, up 1 percent
from last year but down 2 percent from two years ago.
   _Beef replacement heifers, 5 million, up 4 percent from each of
the past two years.
   _Milk replacement heifers, 4.5 million, up 2 percent from last
year but down 2 percent from two years ago.
   _Other heifers, 7.2 million, down 1 percent from a year ago and
down 5 percent from two years ago.
   _Steers weighing 500 pounds and over, 14.5 million, unchanged
from last year but down 2 percent from two years ago.
   _Bulls weighing 500 pounds and over, 2.2 million, unchanged from
both years.
   _Calves under 500 pounds, 30.9 million, down fractionally from
last year and down 1 percent from two years ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
