<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Kellogg     07-28 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Kellogg,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kellogg Reports Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising global demand for cereal
boosted Kellogg Co.'s second-quarter earnings by 15 percent, the
world's largest cereal maker said Friday.
   Kellogg reported earnings of $129.7 million, or $1.06 a share,
for the three months ended June 30, up from $112.7 million, or 92
cents a share, for the second quarter of 1988.
   Sales for the quarter were $1.23 billion, up 13.6 percent from
$1.10 billion for the year-earlier period.
   For the first six months of the year, Kellogg said earnings
increased 23.7 percent to $289.2 million, or $2.36 a share, on
sales of $2.37 billion. That was up from $233.8 million, or $1.90 a
share, on sales of $2.13 billion in the first half of 1988.
   The six-month earnings included a one-time credit of $48.1
million from implementation on Jan. 1 of an accounting change
involving income taxes. Without the change, earnings for the six
months would have been up 3.1 percent to $241.1 million, or $1.97 a
share, the company said.
   Kellogg expects demand to continue to rise, said William
LaMothe, board chairman and chief executive officer.
</TEXT>
