<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-28 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slowing Economy, Rains Spark Broad Drop In Commodity Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Commodity futures prices tumbled Friday as traders of gold,
crude oil, soybeans and coffee reacted to bearish signals ranging
from signs of an economic slowdown to ideal growing conditions in
the Corn Belt.
   The worsening economic outlook was reflected on New York's
Commodity Exchange, where gold futures plunged $6.50 to $7.40 with
the contract for delivery in August settling at $367 a troy ounce.
Silver was 8 cents to 8.7 cents lower with September at $5.183 a
troy ounce.
   Analyst Bette Raptopoulos of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
said the sharp drop in gold prices was due to ``the convergence of
a number of moderately bearish factors,'' chief among them the
firming of the dollar Friday against other other major currencies.
   A stronger dollar discourages foreign purchases of U.S. goods,
which could reduce the incentive for the Federal Reserve Board to
ease up on interest rates. The Fed has recently been allowing
interest rates to fall in a bid to encourage borrowing and steer
the economy away from a recession.
   But economic data released this week have shown the economy
slowing, which has added to the pessimism in the gold market and
discouraged investment buying of gold as an inflation hedge.
   Some analysts found little cause for alarm in gold's decline,
noting that the market has held up well in recent weeks despite the
darkening economic scenario.
   ``I don't find today's sell-off to be terribly depressing or
negative,'' said Sharon Ziemian of Citibank in New York. ``I think
it's quite reasonable.''
   Crude oil futures prices continued a week-long slide on the New
York Mercantile Exchange that analysts have attributed to growing
supplies and slackening demand.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for September delivery fell
below $18 a barrel for the first time since late February and some
observers predicted further losses next week.
   Crude settled 14 cents to 19 cents lower with September at
$17.93 a barrel; heating oil was .55 cent to 1.03 cents lower with
August at 48.23 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .54 cent
lower to .97 cent higher with August at 52.95 cents a gallon.
   Soybeans for near-term delivery plunged below $6.50 a bushel for
the first time in 16 months on the Chicago Board of Trade amid
expectations of continued improvement in Midwestern growing
conditions.
   Other grain futures also closed lower, largely in sympathy with
the plummeting soybean market. Wheat's losses were limited by
rumors of new export business. The Agriculture Department announced
after the close that it had targeted Algeria for sales of 1 million
metric tons of wheat at subsidized prices.
   Soybeans settled 1{ cents to 19 cents lower with August at $6.49
a bushel; wheat was 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with September
at $3.87} a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 3} cents lower with
September at $2.29 a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 8 cents lower
with September at $1.36 a bushel.
   Coffee futures fell to a new 13-year low on on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange amid aggressive selling by
coffee-producing countries in an escalating battle for market
share. The price drop follows the International Coffee
Organization's July 3 suspension of coffee export quotas.
   Coffee settled 1.20 cents to 2.25 cents lower with September at
82.02 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange in cautious trading ahead of the USDA's semi-annual cattle
inventory report. The report, released after the close, confirmed
perceptions of a modest expansion of the U.S. cattle herd and was
considered neutral for futures prices.
   Live cattle were .18 cent lower to .05 cent higher with August
at 72.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .40 cent
lower with August at 83.07 cents a pound; live hogs were .27 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with August at 46.05 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.22 cents lower to .25 cent higher with August
at 25.70 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
