<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-28 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Plunges, Dollar Mostly Stronger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices tumbled and the dollar was mostly
higher in thin trading Friday, although there were no major
developments to spark the activity.
   Republic National Bank reported a late-afternoon bid of $367 for
a troy ounce of gold, down $5.90 from Thursday. Earlier, gold fell
an even sharper $6.70 a troy ounce on the New York Commodity
Exchange, closing at $367.
   Stephen Platt, a metals analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
in Chicago, said some of gold's sharp decline was in response to
the dollar's surge in early domestic trading Friday.
   But gold's own lack of upward progress also took a toll on its
price, Platt said.
   The metal also fell sharply overseas. In London, gold fell to a
late bid price of $369.20 a troy ounce, down $4.80 from late
Thursday.
   In Zurich, it fell $4.30 to $369.75 bid, and in Hong Kong
earlier, it slipped $1.87 to a closing bid of $373.
   Silver also declined. On the Commodity Exchange, silver fell 8.1
cents to close at $5.137 a troy ounce, and it also fell 9 cents
earlier in London to a late bid of $5.14 a troy ounce.
   The dollar generally posted modest gains in U.S. trading after
rising sharply overseas.
   Dealers said there was no apparent reason for an early strong
advance on U.S. markets that influenced activity abroad. But the
dollar couldn't hold the gains in domestic trading, and retraced
some of its steps in the afternoon.
   The British pound fell to $1.6527 from $1.6540 in late New York
trading Thursday. Earlier in London, the pound fell to $1.6455 from
late Thursday's $1.6598.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.8815 West German marks, up from
1.8785; 1.6175 Swiss francs, up from 1.6150; 6.3715 French francs,
up from 6.3605; 1,356.875 Italian lire, up from 1,351.60; and
1.18275 Canadian dollars, down from 1.18355.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8845 West German marks, up from 1.8692; 1.6180
Swiss francs, up from 1.6075; 6.3825 French francs, up from 6.3310;
2.1240 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1085; 1,354.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,346.00; and 1.1838 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1827.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to a closing 139.45 Japanese yen, up
from 139.35 yen at Thursday's close. Later, in London, the dollar
fell back to 139.31 yen, and in New York, it slipped to 139.20 yen
from 139.25 yen late Thursday.
</TEXT>
