<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 1807EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     07-28 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long Bond Yield Finishes Under 8 Percent For First Time Since Spring
1987</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond investors, exuberant about the outlook for
low inflation, pushed the yield on a widely watched long-term
Treasury bond below 8 percent for the first time since spring 1987.
   Strength in the bond market eventually should spill over into
lower rates for consumers on mortgage, car and education loans.
   The bond market rally also means the federal government will
have to pay lower interest rates on its issue of new debt next week.
   ``Eight percent had been viewed as a great barrier and
economists said it would take a very unusual set of developments to
get us there short of a recession, and lo and behold we're there
even without a recession,'' said Maury Harris, a PaineWebber Inc.
economist.
   In a sign of lower consumer interest rates to come, Bank of
America announced it was lowering its prime lending rate to 10.5
percent on Monday from 11 percent. Chase Manhattan Bank lowered the
benchmark rate to that level earlier this month, but most other
major banks were still at 11 percent.
   The Commerce Department helped the bond market Friday with a
report that indicated slow economic growth. It said personal
incomes rose a lackluster 0.3 percent in June as consumer spending
declined for a second straight month.
   Bondholders generally welcome news of a slowdown in the economy
because it implies less demand for goods and services, easing the
risk of inflation, which erodes the value of such fixed-income
investments as bonds.
   The bellwether 30-year Treasury bond rose 15-32 point, or $4.69
per $1,000 in face amount, after gaining nearly 1 point in the
previous session. Its yield fell to 7.985 percent from 8.02 percent
late Thursday. The yield falls when the price rises.
   The yield on the benchmark 30-year bond had flirted with 8
percent all month. Helping push it below was the Federal Reserve's
injection of new reserves into the banking system this week as well
as a report Thursday showing slower-than-expected economic growth
in the second quarter.
   The bond had dipped below 8 percent during the July 11 session
but Friday was the first day since April 8, 1987, that it had
finished below that level.
   ``What's happening is that people are sort of coming in off the
sidelines to buy bonds as the Federal Reserve easing is becoming
more apparent and the inflation outlook is looking pretty
reasonable,'' said John Slosberg, senior fixed-income analyst at
Technical Data Global Markets Group in Boston.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments rose between 5-32 and ] point, intermediate maturities
advanced between about ] point and long-term issues gained about {
point, the Telerate Inc. financial information service reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 3.46 to 1,198.45 from a
revised 1,194.99 on Thursday.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities
of five years or longer, rose 0.97 to 333.23.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 3-32 point. The average yield to
maturity fell to 7.18 percent from 7.19 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.11 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points to 7.85 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 7.89 percent as the discount fell 1 basis points to
7.50 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 7.67 percent from
the rate at auction Thursday as the discount fell 5 basis points to
7.16 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 8 15-16 percent, down from 9 percent late
Thursday. The Fed controls the rate by adding or subtracting
banking reserves, and many economists believe it has set a new
target of 9 percent, down from 9\ percent.
</TEXT>
