<FIRST>r f AM-CBS-Jankowski     07-28 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBS-Jankowski,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jankowski Resigns from CBS to Form Company to Buy TV Stations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Broadcast Group Chairman Gene F. Jankowski
has resigned and plans to head a new company that will buy
television stations and produce programming for the U.S. and
international markets.
   Jankowski, 55, has held the post of chairman of the broadcast
group for a year. The post was created for him when he stepped
aside after 11 years as the president of the broadcast group with
2{ years left on his employment contract.
   He is the latest in a succession of top executives to leave CBS
since Laurence A. Tisch took over three years ago as president and
chief executive. Tisch controls a 24.9 percent stake in CBS, which
has shed virtually all of its non-broadcast operations.
   Jankowski said Friday his new company, Jankowski Communications
System Inc., would buy a minimum of five television stations,
preferably network affiliates ranked in markets ranked between the
nation's 25th and 75th largest.
   He said prices for such stations have fallen in the past year to
attractive levels.
   Jankowski said he and CBS reached a mutually beneficial
settlement for the remaining portion of his contract which runs
intil the end of 1990.
   In a statement announcing Jankowski's departure, Tisch and CBS
Chairman William S. Paley applauded Jankowski for his 28 years of
service to CBS.
</TEXT>
