<DOCNO> AP890728-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 2215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BusinessHighlights     07-28 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0862</SECOND>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of America lowered its prime lending
rate to 10.5 percent from 11 percent, only the second money center
bank to follow the lead of Chase Manhattan, which cut the benchmark
interest rate on July 10.
   Analysts said Friday other major banks may soon lower their
prime rates because their own cost of borrowing money has fallen
sharply over the past few days. The federal funds rate, which is
the interest banks charge each other for short-term loans, finished
below 9 percent Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Personal incomes rose a lackluster 0.3 percent
in June as consumer spending declined for a second straight month,
the government said in a report that renewed recession fears.
   The Commerce Department said Friday consumer spending edged down
0.1 percent in June after adjusting for inflation following a 0.2
percent May decline. It marked the first back-to-back monthly
declines in spending since September and October 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge plans to dismiss lawsuits
filed by 17 states accusing major insurance companies of making
insurance less available and more expensive, the attorney general's
office said.
   U.S. District Judge William Schwarzer, in a ``notice of intended
decision,'' concluded the companies were immune from the antitrust
suits under federal law, attorney general's spokesman Alan Ashby
said Friday.
   The lawsuits, filed in March 1988, accused 32 major U.S. and
British insurance firms, reinsurers and a trade group of
manufacturing a liability crisis through secret agreements,
internal pressure and threats of boycotts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said he is willing to
compromise with Congress on his proposal to cut capital-gains taxes
and he repeated his contention that such a reduction actually would
increase revenues.
   ``If there's some compromise that can spur investment, spur
jobs, increase employment _ the cause of new jobs starting up _ I'd
be interested in it,'' Bush told a news conference Friday.
   Bush's proposal would cut the 33 percent maximum capital-gains
rate to 15 percent, which would apply to stocks and most other
assets, but not timber and real estate. There is little support for
that proposal among Democrats on the committee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted to delay for one year a
business-opposed tax rule that would encourage companies to expand
the number of employees covered by health insurance.
   The provision is included in a spending bill the House approved
376-26 on Friday and sent to the Senate. Proponents hope enough
pressure will build to convince Congress to repeal the so-called
Section 89 entirely.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio financier Marvin Warner's estate
must be liquidated to settle $4.5 billion in claims against him, a
federal bankruptcy judge ruled.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George L. Proctor moved thecase Friday
from a Chapter 11 filing to Chapter 7 under the U.S. Bankruptcy
Code. Chapter 11 allowed Warner to develop a plan to handle his
debts, while Chapter 7 calls for the liquidation of Warner's
property to be distributed to his creditors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee approved legislation to make
permanent a smoking ban on short airline flights after rejecting a
temporary ban affecting all domestic flights.
   The bill is one of several proposals to make permanent the
smoking ban on flights of two hours or less. That prohibition
expires next April.
   Friday's voice vote in the House Public Works and Transportation
Committee followed a tie vote on a proposal to extend the temporary
smoking ban for two more years and make it cover all domestic
flights.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. told Congress it was committed to
a ``reasonable'' continuation of the Alaska oil spill cleanup next
spring and President Bush said he would try to ensure that Exxon
doesn't ``pull back on an agreement.''
   Exxon officials testified Friday that the company intends to
suspend cleanup activities in September because of approaching
winter weather and would return to see if more work is necessary in
the spring.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooker Corp. has ruled out a ``fire
sale'' of its $1.8 billion in assets while a team of advisers
headed for the United States to investigate ways to head off
foreclosure by U.S creditors.
   Hooker, a major Australian property company with significant
U.S. retail and real estate interests, turned itself over to a
court-appointed provisional liquidator last week in one of
Australia's biggest corporate collapses.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Many stock prices continued to rise in moderately active trading
Friday but a rally in blue chips stalled as investors sold to
collect profits.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials at 2,635.24, off 0.19
for the day but up 27.88 points for the week.
   Bond investors pushed the yield on a widely watched long-term
Treasury bond below 8 percent for the first time since spring 1987.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies.
   Futures prices for gold, crude oil, grain, cattle and coffee all
dropped.
</TEXT>
