<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0101EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BanksClosed     07-28 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Banks Closed,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Texas Banks Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators closed three more Texas banks
Thursday, bringing to 99 the total number failures in the state
this year, only 14 less than all of last year.
   In two of Thursday's closures, all deposits were transferred to
new owners, but at Forestwood National Bank of Dallas only deposits
up to the $100,000 insured limit were transferred.
   The federal Office of the Comptroller of the Currency closed
Forestwood's two branches, citing problems brought on by a
continuing real estate collapse combined with liberal and
aggressive lending practices.
   OCC Senior Deputy Comptroller Frank Maguire also closed Brushy
Creek National Bank in Round Rock, with the FDIC transferring the
bank's deposits and some other liabilities to Union National Bank
in Austin for a $1,000 premium.
   And Texas Banking Commissioner Kenneth W. Littlefield shut The
Texas Bank &amp; Trust Co. in Sweetwater, about 42 miles west of
Abilene.
   The OCC said 10-year-old Forestwood had assets of about $61.4
million. The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., named as receiver of
the bank, approved the transfer of insured deposits and secured
liabilities to Comerica Bank-Texas in Dallas.
   In most failures, the FDIC has transferred all deposits, even
those above the insurance limit, but it said only insured deposits
were transferred ``because of an inability to determine the value
of the bank's assets and undeterminable exposure in significant
contingent liabilities.''
   Comerica Bank is paying the FDIC $200,000 for the right to
receive the deposits, and it will purchase $39.4 million of the
failed bank's assets. The FDIC will retain assets with a book value
of about $22 million.
   Union will assume $10.1 million in 2,400 Brushy Creek deposit
accounts and has agreed to purchase certain Brushy Creek assets for
$6.5 million with options to purchase more. The FDIC also will
provide $3.5 million in assistance and retain assets with a book
value of $3.5 million.
   The OCC said Brushy Creek had assets of $10.1 million.
   The FDIC sold the Texas Bank &amp; Trust Co.'s $35.6 million in
deposits to First National Bank in Sweetwater for $457,000. First
National also agreed to purchase $29.1 million of the failed bank's
assets.
   The FDIC will advance First National $6.1 million in assistance,
plus retain assets with a book value of $7.5 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890728-0300 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0110EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Anheuser-Busch     07-28 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Anheuser-Busch,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anheuser-Busch Reports Record Increase in Beer Sales, Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc., the world's largest
brewer, reported an industry-leading jump in beer sales that
contributed to record second-quarter earnings.
   The St. Louis-based company, whose brands include Budweiser and
Michelob, said beer volume has increased 1.1 million barrels so far
this year. The company sold 21.4 million barrels of beer during the
second quarter and 41 million barrels for the first six months.
   According to estimates from the Beer Institute, those sales
accounted for 42 percent of total industry sales for the first six
months, up 1.4 percent and the largest share gain of any brewer.
   ``Our volume growth remains strong and earnings continue to
benefit from operating efficiencies, despite material cost
increases,'' August A. Busch III, president and chairman, said in a
statement Wednesday.
   Anheuser-Busch reported a 10.5 percent profit increase for the
second quarter. Earnings were $233.7 million, or 82 cents a share,
up from $211.5 million, or 72 cents a share, the same period last
year. Sales increased 6.8 percent to $2.48 billion from $2.32
billion.
   For the year so far, the company reported a 10.1 percent profit
increase to $400.8 million, or $1.40 a share, from $363.9 million,
or $1.23 a share. Sales increased 6.6 percent to $4.685 billion
from $4.396 billion.
   ``Our brand families are performing well,'' Busch said. ``We are
particularly pleased with the consumers' acceptance of Michelob
Dry.''
   Anheuser-Busch began selling Michelob Dry nationally in
November. It also has begun test-marketing Bud Dry, Busch Light and
O'Doul's, a non-alcoholic malt beverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
